{"title_page": "Oakwood Village", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- Name  ---------------->\n| name                   = Oakwood Village\n| settlement_type        = Neighbourhood\n| image_skyline          = Oakwood-Vaughan St. Clair.jpg\n| image_caption          = View of Oakwood-Vaughan from Oakwood and [[St. Clair Avenue]]\n| image_map              =\n| pushpin_map            = Canada Toronto\n| pushpin_label_position = none\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location within Toronto\n| coordinates            = {{coord|43|41|33|N|79|26|27|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Governments  ---------------->\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = {{CAN}}\n| subdivision_type1      = Province\n| subdivision_name1      = {{ON}}\n| subdivision_type2      = City\n| subdivision_name2      = {{Flagicon|Toronto}} [[Toronto]]\n| subdivision_type3      = Community\n| subdivision_name3      = [[York, Toronto|York]]\n<!-- History  ---------------->\n| established_title      =\n| established_date       =\n| established_title1     = Changed Municipality\n| established_date1      = 1998 [[Toronto]] from [[York, Toronto|York]]\n<!-- Politicians  ---------------->\n| leader_title           = [[Parliament of Canada|MP]]\n| leader_name            = [[Carolyn Bennett]] ([[St. Paul's (electoral district)|St. Paul's]])\n| leader_title1          = [[Legislative Assembly|MPP]]\n| leader_name1           = [[Jill Andrew]] ([[St. Paul's (electoral district)|St. Paul's]])\n| leader_title2          = [[Toronto City Council|Councillor]]\n| leader_name2           = [[Josh Matlow]] (Ward 12 [[Toronto\u2014St. Paul\u2019s]])\n| population_total                = 21,210\n| population_as_of     = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=pop>{{cite web |title=2016 Neighborhood Profile Oakwood Village|url=https://www.toronto.ca/ext/sdfa/Neighbourhood%20Profiles/pdf/2016/pdf1/cpa107.pdf |publisher=City of Toronto |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n| population_metro                = \n| population_urban                = \n| population_density_km2          = 9,511\n}}\n\n'''Oakwood Village''', formerly known as '''Oakwood-Vaughan''', is a neighbourhood in the [[York, Toronto|York]] district of [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. The neighbourhood is a [[business improvement district|Business Improvement Area]] (BIA), has an annual arts festival, and a public library built in 1997.\n\nThe neighbourhood, commonly known as '''OV''', is bordered by [[Eglinton Avenue|Eglinton Avenue West]] to the north ([[Fairbank, Toronto|Briar Hill\u2013Belgravia]]), [[Dufferin Street]] to the west ([[Fairbank, Toronto|Caledonia\u2013Fairbank]]), [[St. Clair Avenue|St. Clair Avenue West]] to the south ([[Corso Italia (Toronto)|Corso Italia]] and [[Bracondale Hill]]), and Winona Drive to the east ([[Humewood\u2013Cedarvale]]). Oakwood\u2013Vaughan was part of the former [[York, Toronto|City of York]] before the [[Amalgamation of Toronto|amalgamation]] of Toronto in 1998. <!-- [[Five Points, Toronto]] redirects here -->The neighbourhood's northern half is nicknamed '''Five Points''' for the intersection of Oakwood Avenue, Vaughan Road, and Belvidere Avenue. <!-- [[Northcliffe, Toronto]] redirects here -->The western half was called '''Northcliffe''' and is more recently known as Northcliffe Village.\n\n==Character==\n[[File:York Township, Oakwood Ave, north of St Clair.jpg|thumb|left|View of Oakwood\u2013Vaughan from Oakwood Avenue, north of [[St. Clair Avenue]] in 1924. The area was initially developed as a [[streetcar suburb]].]]\nOakwood developed as a [[streetcar suburb]] of Toronto. Stephen Rogers constructed one of the first houses (on a {{convert|5|acre|order=flip|adj=on}} plot)<ref>http://digital.library.mcgill.ca/countyatlas/showrecord.php?PersonID=70605</ref> in this neighbourhood at what is now Rogers Road and Oakwood Avenue. The main streets of Oakwood\u2013Vaughan are Oakwood Avenue, [[Vaughan Road]], Rogers Road (named after Stephen Rogers), Dufferin Street, Eglinton Avenue West and St. Clair Avenue West. These main streets (aside from Vaughan Road) generally demarcate borders with other York and old City of Toronto neighbourhoods or borders of the sub-neighbourhoods and neighbourhoods (Five Points, Northcliffe Village) previously mentioned. A portion of [[Eglinton West|Little Jamaica]] is located on the northern border of the neighbourhood, situated along the south side of Eglinton Avenue West between Oakwood Avenue and Marlee Avenue.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nNorth of Vaughan Road and east of Oakwood Avenue, this part of the neighbourhood has a set of [[One-way traffic|one-way streets]] that acts as a maze for motorists.\n\n===Political boundaries===\n{{update|section|date=December 2019}}\nOakwood\u2013Vaughan's municipal status/boundaries has changed on several occasions. One of the most significant changes was the result of an amalgamation in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toronto.ca/toronto_history/amalgamation/amal_speech.htm |title=The Toronto Amalgamation: Looking Back, Moving Ahead |accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref> Formerly part of the [[York, Toronto|City of York]], York became part of the larger City of Toronto, along with Etobicoke, Scarborough, and North York\u2014all cities in their own right\u2014and the Borough of East York  on January 1, 1998.\n\nMunicipally, the area has a complex history and its boundaries have changed several times. Since the 1998 amalgamation, from Dufferin Street to Winona Drive and north of Rogers Road up to Eglinton Avenue (and beyond), it is a small part of Ward 15: Eglinton\u2014Lawrence. The eastern part of the neighbourhood (east of Oakwood Avenue) also extends into Ward 21: St. Paul's. Residents west of Oakwood Avenue and south of Rogers Road reside in Ward 17: Davenport. A visual representation of the wards is provided for reference.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://app.toronto.ca/wards/jsp/wards.jsp |title=City of Toronto: Ward Profiles |accessdate=2009-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621094346/http://app.toronto.ca/wards/jsp/wards.jsp |archivedate=2009-06-21 }}</ref>\n\nProvincially, the political boundaries have also changed, as recently as in the 2007 provincial election where it was designated part of the St. Paul's riding. Until 2009, MPP [[Michael Bryant (politician)|Michael Bryant]] represented the residents. Bryant stepped down in early 2009, and [[Eric Hoskins]] won a by-election, becoming the new MPP. Residents living east of Oakwood Ave. are part of the St. Paul's provincial riding. The official website, however, has an outdated map from 2005, and so lists the area, incorrectly, as part of the Davenport riding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/members/members_detail.do?locale=en&ID=85&detailPage=members_detail_riding_map |title=Davenport Riding |accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref>\n\nFederally, the area is also part of St. Paul's riding and is represented by MP Dr. [[Carolyn Bennett]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://carolynbennett.liberal.ca|title=St. Paul's Federal Riding |accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nThere are several organizations in the Oakwood\u2013Vaughan area that are working to effect positive change and are trying to counteract the negative, often stereotypical, media coverage of the area. The Oakwood Village BIA, founded in 2009, is actively trying to beautify the area and attract vibrant businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakwoodvillage.ca/|title=Oakwood Village BIA|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref>\n\nAnother organization is the Oakwood Village Community Association (formerly 5 Points Community Action)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakwoodvillage.tumblr.com/|title=Oakwood Village Community Association|accessdate=2011-02-10}}</ref> that was founded in 2005 and has grown tremendously as young families continue to move into this safe, conveniently located, and affordable neighbourhood. 5 Points Community Action originally took its name from the \"5 Point\" intersection of Oakwood Ave., Vaughan Rd., and Belvidere Ave.\n\nWhile there are several outstanding issues to be tackled, the group has coordinated and completed several community projects to strengthen connections between neighbours, politicians, police, and community agencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.towncrieronline.ca/main/main.php?direction=viewstory&storyid=7319&rootcatid=&rootsubcatid=|title=All night booze cans mar area|last=Coorsh|first=Karolyn|date=2008-10-01|publisher=Town Crier|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> A community garden, located at the corner of Belvidere and Oakwood Avenues, was completed with funding from Clean & Beautiful City. A plaque located on the site testifies to the commitment and determination of residents to reclaim and beautify their shared space.\n\nAnother project, a striking mosaic, is located on the south side of Belvidere Avenue, on the community garden's retaining wall. This was completed in partnership with Art Starts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artstarts.net/web/?page_id=587 |title=Art Starts Belvidere Ave. Mosaic Wall, 2007|accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref> The mosaic illustrates the motif of 'roots' and has \u201cwelcome\u201d in many different languages, including Polish, Hebrew, Italian and Portuguese, among others.\n[[File:Oakwood-Vaughan2010.jpg|thumb|upright|The Oakwood Village Transit Island features a {{convert|4.88|m|ft|adj=on}} metal palm tree erected in October 2010.]]\nA more recent project was an art installation that was completed in partnership with Clean & Beautiful City and the City of Toronto. The newly reconstructed Oakwood Village Transit Island, located directly at the corner of Oakwood and Vaughan, was completed in October 2010. Standing tall in this oasis is a {{convert|4.88|m|ft}} steel palm tree that represents the strong roots put down by the residents of Oakwood Village.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/09/10/15312901.html|title=Community supports aluminum palm tree, 2010|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> The palm tree, which can be found throughout the world's warmer nations, is a symbol of unity\u2014the coming together of the many diverse groups in the Oakwood\u2013Vaughan community. However, the tree generated local controversy, as a political hopeful stated that it cost the city $350,000 to erect.  The actual cost of the tree was $4200.<ref>{{cite web|last=McLean|first=Jesse|title=The Smell Test: The real cost of a steel palm tree|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/elections/article/877893--the-smell-test-the-real-cost-of-a-steel-palm-tree|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=19 October 2010|date=19 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Festivals===\nThe Oakwood Village Arts Festival, held annually in June, is brings the community together around arts by providing a public platform for local artists and musicians. As a curated festival revolving around the theme of village, this event features theatre, dance, music, creative writing, art exhibits, interdisciplinary works and public discussions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oakwoodvillageartsfestival.com/IT_TAKES_A_VILLAGE__The_Oakwood_Village_Arts_Festival/Welcome.html|title=It Takes a Village|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref>\n\nThe area is also home to the Arlington Village Project, along the western border with Humewood-Cedarvale, which works to create more positive community building and connecting events in the area. Starting in 2010, the project has organized outdoor fairs.\n\n===Landmarks===\nBuilt in 1936, the former Mount Zion Apostolic Church of Canada is one of the hundreds of apostolic churches in Toronto. It was relocated to North York.\n\n==Demographics==\nMajor ethnic populations (2016):<ref name=pop/>\n* 56.2% [[White Canadians|White]]; ''14.8% [[Italian Canadians|Italian]]'', ''11.8% [[Canadians]]'', ''11.7% [[Portuguese Canadians|Portuguese]]''\n* 12.8% [[Black Canadians|Black]]; ''5.0% [[Jamaican Canadians|Jamaican]]''\n* 9.4% [[Filipino Canadians|Filipino]]\n* 6.3% [[Latin American Canadians|Latin American]] (of any race\n* 3.2% [[East Indian Canadians|East Indian]])\n* 3.0% [[South Asian Canadians|South Asian]]\n\n==Education==\nThe public school districts serving the community are [[Toronto District School Board]] (secular anglophone), [[Toronto Catholic District School Board]] (Catholic anglophone), ''[[Conseil scolaire Viamonde]]'' (secular francophone), and ''[[Conseil scolaire de district catholique Centre-Sud]]'' (Catholic francophone).\n;High schools:\n* [[Oakwood Collegiate Institute]], at the southwest corner of Oakwood Avenue and St. Clair Avenue. The school is technically located in the [[Regal Heights]] neighbourhood enclave of Corso Italia/Davenport, south of Oakwood\u2013Vaughan, but serves students from both neighbourhoods.\n;Former high schools:\n* [[Vaughan Road Academy]], at Vaughan Road between Alameda Avenue and Winona Drive, closed in 2017. It offered the [[IB Diploma Programme]] when it was open.\n[[File:TPL Shchuka.JPG|thumb|The Maria A. Shchuka Library is one of two branches of the [[Toronto Public Library]] located in Oakwood\u2013Vaughan.]]\n;Roman Catholic elementary schools:\n* St. Thomas Aquinas, D'Arcy McGee, and St. Alphonsus.\n;Secular public [[elementary school]]s:\n* Rawlinson Community School, on Glenholme Avenue south of Oakwood Village.\n* J.R. Wilcox Community School, on Ava Road between Winona Drive and Atlas Avenue.\n* Fairbank Public School, at the intersection of [[Eglinton Avenue]] West and [[Dufferin Street]].\n\n===Public library===\nBuilt in 1997, Oakwood Village Public Library is located on Oakwood Avenue and Holland Park Avenue. In addition to Oakwood Village branch, the Maria A. Shchuka Public Library, which was re-rebuilt in 2003, is also located on the neighbourhood's periphery at Eglinton Avenue and Northcliffe Boulevard. Both of these libraries are run by the [[Toronto Public Library]].\n\n==Transportation==\nThe neighbourhood is west of the [[Eglinton West (TTC)|Eglinton West station]], and has three 24-hour bus routes: the 29 (Dufferin Street), the 32 (Eglinton Avenue West), and the 63 (Oakwood Ave) which runs between Eglinton West station and [[Liberty Village]]. There are other buses that operate very frequently, including the 161, which runs along the southern stretch of Oakwood Avenue and along Rogers Road, and the 90, which runs along Vaughan Road to [[St. Clair West station]]. The [[512 St. Clair]] [[Toronto streetcar system|streetcar route]] runs east\u2013west along St. Clair, just below the southern border of Oakwood\u2013Vaughan. The [[Toronto Transit Commission buses|bus routes]] and the 512 St. Clair streetcar route are operated by the [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]].\n\nThe [[Rogers Road streetcar line]] formerly ran along Rogers Road before being replaced by a trolley bus route, in turn later replaced by the route 161 Rogers Road bus.\n\n==Notable residents==\n{{alumni|residents|date=April 2019}}\n*[[Kardinal Offishall]], hip hop musician\n*[[Zalika Reid-Benta]], writer<ref name=midtown>Deborah Dundas, [https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2019/06/07/zalika-reid-bentas-debut-book-puts-midtown-toronto-on-the-page-at-last.html \"Zalika Reid-Benta\u2019s debut book puts midtown Toronto on the page at last\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', June 7, 2019.</ref>\n*[[Watts (producer)|Watts]], hip hop producer\n\n\u2022 Heartless.G, Hip hop Rapper\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Oakwood-Vaughan}}\n*[http://www.toronto.ca/demographics/cns_profiles/cns107.htm Oakwood\u2013Vaughan neighbourhood profile] at Toronto.ca\n\n{{Geographic location\n| North  = [[Fairbank, Toronto|Fairbank]]\n| Northeast = [[Forest Hill, Toronto|Forest Hill]]\n| East   = [[Humewood\u2013Cedarvale]]\n| Southeast  = [[Bracondale Hill]]\n| South = [[Regal Heights]]\n| Southwest = [[Earlscourt]]<br/>[[Corso Italia (Toronto)|Corso Italia]]\n\n| West   = [[Fairbank, Toronto|Fairbank]]\n| Center = Oakwood-Vaughan\n}}\n{{Toronto Neighbourhoods}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oakwood-Vaughan}}\n[[Category:Black Canadian culture in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian settlements]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Streetcar suburbs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- Name  ---------------->\n| name                   = Oakwood Village\n| settlement_type        = Neighbourhood\n| image_skyline          = Oakwood-Vaughan St. Clair.jpg\n| image_caption          = View of Oakwood-Vaughan from Oakwood and [[St. Clair Avenue]]\n| image_map              =\n| pushpin_map            = Canada Toronto\n| pushpin_label_position = none\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location within Toronto\n| coordinates            = {{coord|43|41|33|N|79|26|27|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Governments  ---------------->\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = {{CAN}}\n| subdivision_type1      = Province\n| subdivision_name1      = {{ON}}\n| subdivision_type2      = City\n| subdivision_name2      = {{Flagicon|Toronto}} [[Toronto]]\n| subdivision_type3      = Community\n| subdivision_name3      = [[York, Toronto|York]]\n<!-- History  ---------------->\n| established_title      =\n| established_date       =\n| established_title1     = Changed Municipality\n| established_date1      = 1998 [[Toronto]] from [[York, Toronto|York]]\n<!-- Politicians  ---------------->\n| leader_title           = [[Parliament of Canada|MP]]\n| leader_name            = [[Carolyn Bennett]] ([[St. Paul's (electoral district)|St. Paul's]])\n| leader_title1          = [[Legislative Assembly|MPP]]\n| leader_name1           = [[Jill Andrew]] ([[St. Paul's (electoral district)|St. Paul's]])\n| leader_title2          = [[Toronto City Council|Councillor]]\n| leader_name2           = [[Josh Matlow]] (Ward 12 [[Toronto\u2014St. Paul\u2019s]])\n| population_total                = 21,210\n| population_as_of     = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=pop>{{cite web |title=2016 Neighborhood Profile Oakwood Village|url=https://www.toronto.ca/ext/sdfa/Neighbourhood%20Profiles/pdf/2016/pdf1/cpa107.pdf |publisher=City of Toronto |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n| population_metro                = \n| population_urban                = \n| population_density_km2          = 9,511\n}}\n\n'''Oakwood Village''', formerly known as '''Oakwood-Vaughan''', is a neighbourhood in the [[York, Toronto|York]] district of [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. The neighbourhood is a [[business improvement district|Business Improvement Area]] (BIA), has an annual arts festival, and a public library built in 1997.\n\nThe neighbourhood, commonly known as '''OV''', is bordered by [[Eglinton Avenue|Eglinton Avenue West]] to the north ([[Fairbank, Toronto|Briar Hill\u2013Belgravia]]), [[Dufferin Street]] to the west ([[Fairbank, Toronto|Caledonia\u2013Fairbank]]), [[St. Clair Avenue|St. Clair Avenue West]] to the south ([[Corso Italia (Toronto)|Corso Italia]] and [[Bracondale Hill]]), and Winona Drive to the east ([[Humewood\u2013Cedarvale]]). Oakwood\u2013Vaughan was part of the former [[York, Toronto|City of York]] before the [[Amalgamation of Toronto|amalgamation]] of Toronto in 1998. <!-- [[Five Points, Toronto]] redirects here -->The neighbourhood's northern half is nicknamed '''Five Points''' for the intersection of Oakwood Avenue, Vaughan Road, and Belvidere Avenue. <!-- [[Northcliffe, Toronto]] redirects here -->The western half was called '''Northcliffe''' and is more recently known as Northcliffe Village.\n\n==Character==\n[[File:York Township, Oakwood Ave, north of St Clair.jpg|thumb|left|View of Oakwood\u2013Vaughan from Oakwood Avenue, north of [[St. Clair Avenue]] in 1924. The area was initially developed as a [[streetcar suburb]].]]\nOakwood developed as a [[streetcar suburb]] of Toronto. Stephen Rogers constructed one of the first houses (on a {{convert|5|acre|order=flip|adj=on}} plot)<ref>http://digital.library.mcgill.ca/countyatlas/showrecord.php?PersonID=70605</ref> in this neighbourhood at what is now Rogers Road and Oakwood Avenue. The main streets of Oakwood\u2013Vaughan are Oakwood Avenue, [[Vaughan Road]], Rogers Road (named after Stephen Rogers), Dufferin Street, Eglinton Avenue West and St. Clair Avenue West. These main streets (aside from Vaughan Road) generally demarcate borders with other York and old City of Toronto neighbourhoods or borders of the sub-neighbourhoods and neighbourhoods (Five Points, Northcliffe Village) previously mentioned. A portion of [[Eglinton West|Little Jamaica]] is located on the northern border of the neighbourhood, situated along the south side of Eglinton Avenue West between Oakwood Avenue and Marlee Avenue.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nNorth of Vaughan Road and east of Oakwood Avenue, this part of the neighbourhood has a set of [[One-way traffic|one-way streets]] that acts as a maze for motorists.\n\n===Political boundaries===\n{{update|section|date=December 2019}}\nOakwood\u2013Vaughan's municipal status/boundaries has changed on several occasions. One of the most significant changes was the result of an amalgamation in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toronto.ca/toronto_history/amalgamation/amal_speech.htm |title=The Toronto Amalgamation: Looking Back, Moving Ahead |accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref> Formerly part of the [[York, Toronto|City of York]], York became part of the larger City of Toronto, along with Etobicoke, Scarborough, and North York\u2014all cities in their own right\u2014and the Borough of East York  on January 1, 1998.\n\nMunicipally, the area has a complex history and its boundaries have changed several times. Since the 1998 amalgamation, from Dufferin Street to Winona Drive and north of Rogers Road up to Eglinton Avenue (and beyond), it is a small part of Ward 15: Eglinton\u2014Lawrence. The eastern part of the neighbourhood (east of Oakwood Avenue) also extends into Ward 21: St. Paul's. Residents west of Oakwood Avenue and south of Rogers Road reside in Ward 17: Davenport. A visual representation of the wards is provided for reference.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://app.toronto.ca/wards/jsp/wards.jsp |title=City of Toronto: Ward Profiles |accessdate=2009-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621094346/http://app.toronto.ca/wards/jsp/wards.jsp |archivedate=2009-06-21 }}</ref>\n\nProvincially, the political boundaries have also changed, as recently as in the 2007 provincial election where it was designated part of the St. Paul's riding. Until 2009, MPP [[Michael Bryant (politician)|Michael Bryant]] represented the residents. Bryant stepped down in early 2009, and [[Eric Hoskins]] won a by-election, becoming the new MPP. Residents living east of Oakwood Ave. are part of the St. Paul's provincial riding. The official website, however, has an outdated map from 2005, and so lists the area, incorrectly, as part of the Davenport riding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/members/members_detail.do?locale=en&ID=85&detailPage=members_detail_riding_map |title=Davenport Riding |accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref>\n\nFederally, the area is also part of St. Paul's riding and is represented by MP Dr. [[Carolyn Bennett]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://carolynbennett.liberal.ca|title=St. Paul's Federal Riding |accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nThere are several organizations in the Oakwood\u2013Vaughan area that are working to effect positive change and are trying to counteract the negative, often stereotypical, media coverage of the area. The Oakwood Village BIA, founded in 2009, is actively trying to beautify the area and attract vibrant businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakwoodvillage.ca/|title=Oakwood Village BIA|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref>\n\nAnother organization is the Oakwood Village Community Association (formerly 5 Points Community Action)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakwoodvillage.tumblr.com/|title=Oakwood Village Community Association|accessdate=2011-02-10}}</ref> that was founded in 2005 and has grown tremendously as young families continue to move into this safe, conveniently located, and affordable neighbourhood. 5 Points Community Action originally took its name from the \"5 Point\" intersection of Oakwood Ave., Vaughan Rd., and Belvidere Ave.\n\nWhile there are several outstanding issues to be tackled, the group has coordinated and completed several community projects to strengthen connections between neighbours, politicians, police, and community agencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.towncrieronline.ca/main/main.php?direction=viewstory&storyid=7319&rootcatid=&rootsubcatid=|title=All night booze cans mar area|last=Coorsh|first=Karolyn|date=2008-10-01|publisher=Town Crier|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> A community garden, located at the corner of Belvidere and Oakwood Avenues, was completed with funding from Clean & Beautiful City. A plaque located on the site testifies to the commitment and determination of residents to reclaim and beautify their shared space.\n\nAnother project, a striking mosaic, is located on the south side of Belvidere Avenue, on the community garden's retaining wall. This was completed in partnership with Art Starts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artstarts.net/web/?page_id=587 |title=Art Starts Belvidere Ave. Mosaic Wall, 2007|accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref> The mosaic illustrates the motif of 'roots' and has \u201cwelcome\u201d in many different languages, including Polish, Hebrew, Italian and Portuguese, among others.\n[[File:Oakwood-Vaughan2010.jpg|thumb|upright|The Oakwood Village Transit Island features a {{convert|4.88|m|ft|adj=on}} metal palm tree erected in October 2010.]]\nA more recent project was an art installation that was completed in partnership with Clean & Beautiful City and the City of Toronto. The newly reconstructed Oakwood Village Transit Island, located directly at the corner of Oakwood and Vaughan, was completed in October 2010. Standing tall in this oasis is a {{convert|4.88|m|ft}} steel palm tree that represents the strong roots put down by the residents of Oakwood Village.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/09/10/15312901.html|title=Community supports aluminum palm tree, 2010|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> The palm tree, which can be found throughout the world's warmer nations, is a symbol of unity\u2014the coming together of the many diverse groups in the Oakwood\u2013Vaughan community. However, the tree generated local controversy, as a political hopeful stated that it cost the city $350,000 to erect.  The actual cost of the tree was $4200.<ref>{{cite web|last=McLean|first=Jesse|title=The Smell Test: The real cost of a steel palm tree|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/elections/article/877893--the-smell-test-the-real-cost-of-a-steel-palm-tree|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=19 October 2010|date=19 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Festivals===\nThe Oakwood Village Arts Festival, held annually in June, is brings the community together around arts by providing a public platform for local artists and musicians. As a curated festival revolving around the theme of village, this event features theatre, dance, music, creative writing, art exhibits, interdisciplinary works and public discussions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oakwoodvillageartsfestival.com/IT_TAKES_A_VILLAGE__The_Oakwood_Village_Arts_Festival/Welcome.html|title=It Takes a Village|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref>\n\nThe area is also home to the Arlington Village Project, along the western border with Humewood-Cedarvale, which works to create more positive community building and connecting events in the area. Starting in 2010, the project has organized outdoor fairs.\n\n===Landmarks===\nBuilt in 1936, former Mount Zion Apostolic Church of Canada is one of the hundreds of apostolic churches in Toronto. It was relocated to North York.\n\n==Demographics==\nMajor ethnic populations (2016):<ref name=pop/>\n* 56.2% [[White Canadians|White]]; ''14.8% [[Italian Canadians|Italian]]'', ''11.8% [[Canadians]]'', ''11.7% [[Portuguese Canadians|Portuguese]]''\n* 12.8% [[Black Canadians|Black]]; ''5.0% [[Jamaican Canadians|Jamaican]]''\n* 9.4% [[Filipino Canadians|Filipino]]\n* 6.3% [[Latin American Canadians|Latin American]] (of any race\n* 3.2% [[East Indian Canadians|East Indian]])\n* 3.0% [[South Asian Canadians|South Asian]]\n\n==Education==\nThe public school districts serving the community are [[Toronto District School Board]] (secular anglophone), [[Toronto Catholic District School Board]] (Catholic anglophone), ''[[Conseil scolaire Viamonde]]'' (secular francophone), and ''[[Conseil scolaire de district catholique Centre-Sud]]'' (Catholic francophone).\n;High schools:\n* [[Oakwood Collegiate Institute]], at the southwest corner of Oakwood Avenue and St. Clair Avenue. The school is technically located in the [[Regal Heights]] neighbourhood enclave of Corso Italia/Davenport, south of Oakwood\u2013Vaughan, but serves students from both neighbourhoods.\n;Former high schools:\n* [[Vaughan Road Academy]], at Vaughan Road between Alameda Avenue and Winona Drive, closed in 2017. It offered the [[IB Diploma Programme]] when it was open.\n[[File:TPL Shchuka.JPG|thumb|The Maria A. Shchuka Library is one of two branches of the [[Toronto Public Library]] located in Oakwood\u2013Vaughan.]]\n;Roman Catholic elementary schools:\n* St. Thomas Aquinas, D'Arcy McGee, and St. Alphonsus.\n;Secular public [[elementary school]]s:\n* Rawlinson Community School, on Glenholme Avenue south of Oakwood Village.\n* J.R. Wilcox Community School, on Ava Road between Winona Drive and Atlas Avenue.\n* Fairbank Public School, at the intersection of [[Eglinton Avenue]] West and [[Dufferin Street]].\n\n===Public library===\nBuilt in 1997, Oakwood Village Public Library is located on Oakwood Avenue and Holland Park Avenue. In addition to Oakwood Village branch, the Maria A. Shchuka Public Library, which was re-rebuilt in 2003, is also located on the neighbourhood's periphery at Eglinton Avenue and Northcliffe Boulevard. Both of these libraries are run by the [[Toronto Public Library]].\n\n==Transportation==\nThe neighbourhood is west of the [[Eglinton West (TTC)|Eglinton West station]], and has three 24-hour bus routes: the 29 (Dufferin Street), the 32 (Eglinton Avenue West), and the 63 (Oakwood Ave) which runs between Eglinton West station and [[Liberty Village]]. There are other buses that operate very frequently, including the 161, which runs along the southern stretch of Oakwood Avenue and along Rogers Road, and the 90, which runs along Vaughan Road to [[St. Clair West station]]. The [[512 St. Clair]] [[Toronto streetcar system|streetcar route]] runs east\u2013west along St. Clair, just below the southern border of Oakwood\u2013Vaughan. The [[Toronto Transit Commission buses|bus routes]] and the 512 St. Clair streetcar route are operated by the [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]].\n\nThe [[Rogers Road streetcar line]] formerly ran along Rogers Road before being replaced by a trolley bus route, in turn later replaced by the route 161 Rogers Road bus.\n\n==Notable residents==\n{{alumni|residents|date=April 2019}}\n*[[Kardinal Offishall]], hip hop musician\n*[[Zalika Reid-Benta]], writer<ref name=midtown>Deborah Dundas, [https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2019/06/07/zalika-reid-bentas-debut-book-puts-midtown-toronto-on-the-page-at-last.html \"Zalika Reid-Benta\u2019s debut book puts midtown Toronto on the page at last\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', June 7, 2019.</ref>\n*[[Watts (producer)|Watts]], hip hop producer\n\n\u2022 Heartless.G, Hip hop Rapper\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Oakwood-Vaughan}}\n*[http://www.toronto.ca/demographics/cns_profiles/cns107.htm Oakwood\u2013Vaughan neighbourhood profile] at Toronto.ca\n\n{{Geographic location\n| North  = [[Fairbank, Toronto|Fairbank]]\n| Northeast = [[Forest Hill, Toronto|Forest Hill]]\n| East   = [[Humewood\u2013Cedarvale]]\n| Southeast  = [[Bracondale Hill]]\n| South = [[Regal Heights]]\n| Southwest = [[Earlscourt]]<br/>[[Corso Italia (Toronto)|Corso Italia]]\n\n| West   = [[Fairbank, Toronto|Fairbank]]\n| Center = Oakwood-Vaughan\n}}\n{{Toronto Neighbourhoods}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oakwood-Vaughan}}\n[[Category:Black Canadian culture in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian settlements]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Streetcar suburbs]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLandmarks:Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oakwood_Village"}
{"title_page": "No Way Jose (wrestler)", "text_new": "{{short description|Dominican-American wrestler}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = No Way Jose\n|image       = No Way Jose (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = No Way Jose in April 2018\n|birth_name  = Levis Valenzuela Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1988|05|30}}\n|birth_place = [[Durham, North Carolina]], U.S.\n|residence   =\n|names       = Levis Valenzuela Jr.<ref name=owow/><br>Manny Garcia<ref name=owow>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/n/no-way-jose/|title=No Way Jose OWW|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br>'''No Way Jose'''<ref name=owow/>\n|height      = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=WWEbio>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/nowayjose|title=No Way Jose|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref>\n|weight      = 245 lb<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|billed      = [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|trainer     = Roy Wilkins<br>[[Trevor Lee]]<ref name=\"Miamiherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article18388127.html|title= WWE welcomes new NXT recruits: Introducing Levis Valenzuela Jr.|work=Miami Herald|accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|debut       = May 17, 2013<ref name=\"owow\"/>\n|retired     = \n}}\n'''Levis Valenzuela Jr.'''<ref name=\"WWEinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/levis-valenzuela-jr-interview|title= Levis Valenzuela Jr. proud to represent Dominican Republic in NXT|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=WWE.com}}</ref> (born May 30, 1988) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], Best known for his time with [[WWE]], where he performed under the [[ring name]] '''No Way Jose'''.\n\nValenzuela debuted in May 2013, wrestling under the name '''Manny Garcia''' for North Carolina promotion [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]], where he became a two-time [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship|CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Champion]]. He signed with WWE in 2015, wrestling in its developmental territory [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] before being called up to the main roster in April 2018.\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Independent circuit (2013\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Manny Garcia 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Garcia in 2014]]\nValenzuela made his debut in [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]] as '''Manny Garcia''' on May 17, 2013. Manny lost his debut match against [[Ric Converse]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://cwf247.com/wp/manny-garcia-joins-nxt/|title=Manny Garcia Joins NXT|work=cwf.com|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On May 3, 2014, he defeated Mark James to win the [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]].<ref name=CWFTitle>{{cite web |url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvcwf3.html |title=CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Title |author=Tanabe, Hisaharu |year=2011 |work=Solie's Title Histories |publisher=Solie.org |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On December 6, 2014, Manny lost the title to Chris Lea.<ref name=CWFTitle/> On December 27, 2014, Manny re-captured the TV Championship.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://indypowerrankingsipr.wordpress.com/2014/12/28/1227-cwf-mid-atlantic-battlecade-xv-results/ |title = 12/27 CWF Mid-Atlantic Battlecade XV Results|date = December 28, 2014}}</ref> On March 21, 2015, Manny lost his title in a Fatal 4 Way where Chet Sterling came out as victorious.<ref name=cagematch/> In addition to CWF Mid-Atlantic, Garcia also appeared for promotions including Fire Star Pro Wrestling and [[OMEGA Championship Wrestling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_83652.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - SHOW RESULTS 2/28 OMEGA in Durham, N.C.: Jeff Hardy new OMEGA champion, Mick Foley, Gallows vs. Dreamer, more|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== WWE ===\n====NXT (2015\u20132018) ====\nIn April 2015, it was reported that Valenzuela signed a contract with WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-News-The-newest-NXT-class-includes-an-independent-standout-and-ten-others-41786|title=WWE News: The newest NXT class includes an independent standout and ten others|publisher=}}</ref> On April 10, 2015, Valenzuela was announced as one of 11 new signings to begin training at the [[WWE Performance Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/wwe-performance-center-welcomes-new-class-of-recruits|title=WWE Performance Center welcomes new class of recruits|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref> Wrestling under his real name, Valenzuela made his first appearance on ''[[WWE NXT (TV series)|NXT]]'' as an [[Job (professional wrestling)|enhancement talent]], teaming with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias Samson]] in a tag team match, losing to [[American Alpha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwenxtreport/article_86582.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WWE NXT RESULTS 7/29: Blake & Murphy defend NXT Tag Titles, Kevin Owens \"fined,\" Charlotte in action, Jesse Sorensen, more|publisher=}}</ref> Valenzuela then began to make frequent appearances at [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] [[house show]]s for the rest of 2015 and the early part of 2016.<ref name=cagematch/>\n\nIn April 2016, vignettes began to air hyping the debut of Valenzuela, now repackaged as '''No Way Jose'''. He made his official debut on the April 20, 2016 episode of ''NXT'', defeating [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]]. On the June 22 episode of ''NXT'', Jose interrupted [[Austin Aries]] during his interview backstage and told him to be positive following Aries' loss at [[NXT TakeOver: The End]]. Later that night, Jose defeated Josh Woods. Aries then came out and ended up dancing with Jose, but he then attacked Jose. After weeks of missing ''NXT'', Jose attacked Aries after Aries' match on the July 20 episode of ''NXT''. Jose rushed Aries outside into the locker room. Aries defeated Jose at [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn II]].\n\nThen, Jose entered a feud with [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]] and the [[Sanity (professional wrestling)|SAnitY]] faction by calling them out after they interrupted a match between [[Rich Swann]] and [[Kona Reeves]]. This led to an assault on Jose. On the November 30 episode of ''NXT'', Jose faced Eric Young in a losing effort. On the December 7 episode of ''NXT'', Jose and Rich Swann faced the team of Eric Young and [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]] again in a losing effort.<ref name=debut>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/22/420-wwe-nxt-tv-results-jamess-full-report-on-joe-vs-crews-main-event-enzo-cass-face-nxt-tag-champs-nia-jax-no-way-jose-debuts/|title=4/20 WWE NXT TV Results - James's Full Report on Joe vs. Crews main event, Enzo & Cass face NXT tag champs, Nia Jax, No Way Jose debuts -|publisher=|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NXTBrooklynII\">{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=8/20 \"WWE NXT Takeover: Brooklyn\" Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/20/820-wwe-nxt-takeover-brooklyn-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> Jose continued to feud with SAnitY, forming an alliance with [[Tye Dillinger]] and [[Roderick Strong]] to battle the faction in early 2017. He was scheduled to team with Dillinger, Strong and [[Ruby Riott|Ruby Riot]] against SAnitY at [[NXT TakeOver: Orlando]] but he was attacked by Sanity before the show. He was replaced by [[Kassius Ohno]] in the match, which was eventually won by SAnitY.\n\n==== Raw (2018\u20132020) ====\nOn the April 9 episode of [[WWE Raw|''Raw'']], the first after [[WrestleMania 34]], Jose made his main roster debut, defeating [[Job (professional wrestling)|local talent]] John Skyler in a [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#squash|squash match]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=No Way Jose def. John Skyler|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-09/article/no-way-jose-def-john-skyler|website=WWE.com|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Jose picked up an [[Upset (competition)|upset victory]] against [[Baron Corbin]] on the April 30 episode of ''Raw'', after interference from [[Titus O'Neil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-30/article/titus-oneil-no-way-jose-baron-corbin|title=No Way Jose def. Baron Corbin|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> This would lead to Jose teaming with O'Neil and [[Apollo Crews]] to face Corbin and [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] on the May 7 episode of ''Raw'' in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/103879-may-7-2018-mitb-qualifying-matches-uniondale/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 5/7/18 (Two Triple Threat Money in the Bank Qualifying Matches)|work=WrestleView|first=Mike|last=Tedesco|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> He failed to qualify for the [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Men's Money in the Bank ladder match]] in a triple threat match against Corbin and the eventual winner [[Bobby Roode]] on the May 14 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2018/5/14/17354444/bobby-roode-wins-into-mens-money-in-the-bank-ladder-match-wwe-raw|title=Bobby Roode wins his way into the men's Money in the Bank ladder match|last=Messano|first=Tommy|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref> On the May 21 episode of ''Raw'', Jose was defeated by Corbin to end their feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-05-21/article/baron-corbin-def-no-way-jose|title=Baron Corbin def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose then started a feud with [[Mojo Rawley]]. After losing  to Rawley on the June 18 episode of ''Raw'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-06-18/article/mojo-rawley-def-no-way-jose|title=Mojo Rawley def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose would ask for a rematch, only to be constantly denied one by Rawley for the next three weeks. Jose finally got his rematch on the July 9 episode of ''Raw'', however he would once again be defeated by Rawley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/07/09/heydorns-wwe-raw-report-7-9-alt-perspective-coverage-of-the-live-show-including-the-final-hype-for-extreme-rules-brock-lesnar-fallout-and-more/|title=HEYDORN'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/9: Alt Perspective coverage of the live show including the final hype for Extreme Rules, Rollins vs. McIntyre, and more|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Zack|last=Heydorn|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Afterwards, Jose did not compete on ''Raw'' for four months, instead regularly appearing on [[WWE Main Event|''Main Event'']]. Jose returned to ''Raw'' on November 26, where he was defeated by [[Jinder Mahal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-11-26/article/jinder-mahal-def-no-way-jose|title=Jinder Mahal def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJose made his [[Royal Rumble match|Royal Rumble]] debut at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|namesake event]] on January 27, 2019, only to be eliminated in two seconds by [[Samoa Joe]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Seth Rollins won the 30-Man Royal Rumble Match|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2019/2019-mens-royal-rumble-match-\nresults|publisher=WWE|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn the 15th of April it was announced on WWE\u2019s official website that No Way Jose was released as well as various other superstars.\n\n==Other media==\nValenzuela made his WWE video game debut as a playable character in ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|author=WWE Staff|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref> and subsequently appears in ''[[WWE 2K19]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nordic.ign.com/m/xbox-one-gaming-hardware/18381/news/wwe-2k19-roster-reveal-75-playable-superstars-announced |title=WWE 2K19 Roster Reveal: 75 Playable Superstars Announced |last=Fowler |first=Matt |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''[[CWF Mid-Atlantic]]'''\n** [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]] ([[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship#title history|2 times]])<ref name=CWFTitle/>\n* '''Fire Star Pro Wrestling'''\n** FSPW South Eastern Championship (1 time)<ref name=cagematch>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247&name=Manny+Garcia|title=No Way Jose|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him No. 200 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|work=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{wwe superstars|nowayjose|No Way Jose}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247 No Way Jose on Cagematch.net]\n\n{{WWE personnel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:No Way Jose}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American people of Dominican Republic descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dominican-American wrestler}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = No Way Jose\n|image       = No Way Jose (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = No Way Jose in April 2018\n|birth_name  = Levis Valenzuela Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1988|05|30}}\n|birth_place = [[Durham, North Carolina]], U.S.\n|residence   =\n|names       = Levis Valenzuela Jr.<ref name=owow/><br>Manny Garcia<ref name=owow>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/n/no-way-jose/|title=No Way Jose OWW|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br>'''No Way Jose'''<ref name=owow/>\n|height      = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=WWEbio>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/nowayjose|title=No Way Jose|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref>\n|weight      = 245 lb<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|billed      = [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|trainer     = Roy Wilkins<br>[[Trevor Lee]]<ref name=\"Miamiherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article18388127.html|title= WWE welcomes new NXT recruits: Introducing Levis Valenzuela Jr.|work=Miami Herald|accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|debut       = May 17, 2013<ref name=\"owow\"/>\n|retired     = \n}}\n'''Levis Valenzuela Jr.'''<ref name=\"WWEinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/levis-valenzuela-jr-interview|title= Levis Valenzuela Jr. proud to represent Dominican Republic in NXT|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=WWE.com}}</ref> (born May 30, 1988) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], Best known for his time with [[WWE]], where he performed under the [[ring name]] '''No Way Jose'''.\n\nValenzuela debuted in May 2013, wrestling under the name '''Manny Garcia''' for North Carolina promotion [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]], where he became a two-time [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship|CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Champion]]. He signed with WWE in 2015, wrestling in its developmental territory [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] before being called up to the main roster in April 2018.\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Independent circuit (2013\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Manny Garcia 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Garcia in 2014]]\nValenzuela made his debut in [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]] as '''Manny Garcia''' on May 17, 2013. Manny lost his debut match against [[Ric Converse]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://cwf247.com/wp/manny-garcia-joins-nxt/|title=Manny Garcia Joins NXT|work=cwf.com|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On May 3, 2014, he defeated Mark James to win the [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]].<ref name=CWFTitle>{{cite web |url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvcwf3.html |title=CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Title |author=Tanabe, Hisaharu |year=2011 |work=Solie's Title Histories |publisher=Solie.org |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On December 6, 2014, Manny lost the title to Chris Lea.<ref name=CWFTitle/> On December 27, 2014, Manny re-captured the TV Championship.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://indypowerrankingsipr.wordpress.com/2014/12/28/1227-cwf-mid-atlantic-battlecade-xv-results/ |title = 12/27 CWF Mid-Atlantic Battlecade XV Results|date = December 28, 2014}}</ref> On March 21, 2015, Manny lost his title in a Fatal 4 Way where Chet Sterling came out as victorious.<ref name=cagematch/> In addition to CWF Mid-Atlantic, Garcia also appeared for promotions including Fire Star Pro Wrestling and [[OMEGA Championship Wrestling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_83652.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - SHOW RESULTS 2/28 OMEGA in Durham, N.C.: Jeff Hardy new OMEGA champion, Mick Foley, Gallows vs. Dreamer, more|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== WWE ===\n====NXT (2015\u20132018) ====\nIn April 2015, it was reported that Valenzuela signed a contract with WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-News-The-newest-NXT-class-includes-an-independent-standout-and-ten-others-41786|title=WWE News: The newest NXT class includes an independent standout and ten others|publisher=}}</ref> On April 10, 2015, Valenzuela was announced as one of 11 new signings to begin training at the [[WWE Performance Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/wwe-performance-center-welcomes-new-class-of-recruits|title=WWE Performance Center welcomes new class of recruits|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref> Wrestling under his real name, Valenzuela made his first appearance on ''[[WWE NXT (TV series)|NXT]]'' as an [[Job (professional wrestling)|enhancement talent]], teaming with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias Samson]] in a tag team match, losing to [[American Alpha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwenxtreport/article_86582.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WWE NXT RESULTS 7/29: Blake & Murphy defend NXT Tag Titles, Kevin Owens \"fined,\" Charlotte in action, Jesse Sorensen, more|publisher=}}</ref> Valenzuela then began to make frequent appearances at [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] [[house show]]s for the rest of 2015 and the early part of 2016.<ref name=cagematch/>\n\nIn April 2016, vignettes began to air hyping the debut of Valenzuela, now repackaged as '''No Way Jose'''. He made his official debut on the April 20, 2016 episode of ''NXT'', defeating [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]]. On the June 22 episode of ''NXT'', Jose interrupted [[Austin Aries]] during his interview backstage and told him to be positive following Aries' loss at [[NXT TakeOver: The End]]. Later that night, Jose defeated Josh Woods. Aries then came out and ended up dancing with Jose, but he then attacked Jose. After weeks of missing ''NXT'', Jose attacked Aries after Aries' match on the July 20 episode of ''NXT''. Jose rushed Aries outside into the locker room. Aries defeated Jose at [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn II]].\n\nThen, Jose entered a feud with [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]] and the [[Sanity (professional wrestling)|SAnitY]] faction by calling them out after they interrupted a match between [[Rich Swann]] and [[Kona Reeves]]. This led to an assault on Jose. On the November 30 episode of ''NXT'', Jose faced Eric Young in a losing effort. On the December 7 episode of ''NXT'', Jose and Rich Swann faced the team of Eric Young and [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]] again in a losing effort.<ref name=debut>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/22/420-wwe-nxt-tv-results-jamess-full-report-on-joe-vs-crews-main-event-enzo-cass-face-nxt-tag-champs-nia-jax-no-way-jose-debuts/|title=4/20 WWE NXT TV Results - James's Full Report on Joe vs. Crews main event, Enzo & Cass face NXT tag champs, Nia Jax, No Way Jose debuts -|publisher=|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NXTBrooklynII\">{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=8/20 \"WWE NXT Takeover: Brooklyn\" Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/20/820-wwe-nxt-takeover-brooklyn-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> Jose continued to feud with SAnitY, forming an alliance with [[Tye Dillinger]] and [[Roderick Strong]] to battle the faction in early 2017. He was scheduled to team with Dillinger, Strong and [[Ruby Riott|Ruby Riot]] against SAnitY at [[NXT TakeOver: Orlando]] but he was attacked by Sanity before the show. He was replaced by [[Kassius Ohno]] in the match, which was eventually won by SAnitY.\n\n==== Raw (2018\u20132020) ====\nOn the April 9 episode of [[WWE Raw|''Raw'']], the first after [[WrestleMania 34]], Jose made his main roster debut, defeating [[Job (professional wrestling)|local talent]] John Skyler in a [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#squash|squash match]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=No Way Jose def. John Skyler|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-09/article/no-way-jose-def-john-skyler|website=WWE.com|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Jose picked up an [[Upset (competition)|upset victory]] against [[Baron Corbin]] on the April 30 episode of ''Raw'', after interference from [[Titus O'Neil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-30/article/titus-oneil-no-way-jose-baron-corbin|title=No Way Jose def. Baron Corbin|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> This would lead to Jose teaming with O'Neil and [[Apollo Crews]] to face Corbin and [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] on the May 7 episode of ''Raw'' in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/103879-may-7-2018-mitb-qualifying-matches-uniondale/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 5/7/18 (Two Triple Threat Money in the Bank Qualifying Matches)|work=WrestleView|first=Mike|last=Tedesco|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> He failed to qualify for the [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Men's Money in the Bank ladder match]] in a triple threat match against Corbin and the eventual winner [[Bobby Roode]] on the May 14 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2018/5/14/17354444/bobby-roode-wins-into-mens-money-in-the-bank-ladder-match-wwe-raw|title=Bobby Roode wins his way into the men's Money in the Bank ladder match|last=Messano|first=Tommy|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref> On the May 21 episode of ''Raw'', Jose was defeated by Corbin to end their feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-05-21/article/baron-corbin-def-no-way-jose|title=Baron Corbin def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose then started a feud with [[Mojo Rawley]]. After losing  to Rawley on the June 18 episode of ''Raw'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-06-18/article/mojo-rawley-def-no-way-jose|title=Mojo Rawley def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose would ask for a rematch, only to be constantly denied one by Rawley for the next three weeks. Jose finally got his rematch on the July 9 episode of ''Raw'', however he would once again be defeated by Rawley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/07/09/heydorns-wwe-raw-report-7-9-alt-perspective-coverage-of-the-live-show-including-the-final-hype-for-extreme-rules-brock-lesnar-fallout-and-more/|title=HEYDORN'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/9: Alt Perspective coverage of the live show including the final hype for Extreme Rules, Rollins vs. McIntyre, and more|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Zack|last=Heydorn|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Afterwards, Jose did not compete on ''Raw'' for four months, instead regularly appearing on [[WWE Main Event|''Main Event'']]. Jose returned to ''Raw'' on November 26, where he was defeated by [[Jinder Mahal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-11-26/article/jinder-mahal-def-no-way-jose|title=Jinder Mahal def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJose made his [[Royal Rumble match|Royal Rumble]] debut at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|namesake event]] on January 27, 2019, only to be eliminated in two seconds by [[Samoa Joe]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Seth Rollins won the 30-Man Royal Rumble Match|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2019/2019-mens-royal-rumble-match-\nresults|publisher=WWE|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 15th April it was announced on WWE\u2019s official website that No Way Jose was released as well as various other superstars.\n\n==Other media==\nValenzuela made his WWE video game debut as a playable character in ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|author=WWE Staff|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref> and subsequently appears in ''[[WWE 2K19]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nordic.ign.com/m/xbox-one-gaming-hardware/18381/news/wwe-2k19-roster-reveal-75-playable-superstars-announced |title=WWE 2K19 Roster Reveal: 75 Playable Superstars Announced |last=Fowler |first=Matt |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''[[CWF Mid-Atlantic]]'''\n** [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]] ([[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship#title history|2 times]])<ref name=CWFTitle/>\n* '''Fire Star Pro Wrestling'''\n** FSPW South Eastern Championship (1 time)<ref name=cagematch>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247&name=Manny+Garcia|title=No Way Jose|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him No. 200 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|work=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{wwe superstars|nowayjose|No Way Jose}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247 No Way Jose on Cagematch.net]\n\n{{WWE personnel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:No Way Jose}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American people of Dominican Republic descent]]\n", "name_user": "Ghaithx", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRaw (2018\u20132020)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_Way_Jose_(wrestler)"}
{"title_page": "Temple B'nai Israel (Oklahoma City)", "text_new": "{{for|similarly named synagogues|B'nai Israel (disambiguation){{!}}B'nai Israel}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| building_name         =Temple B'nai Israel\n| image                 =Tbi-historicmarker.jpg\n| image_upright = \n| caption               =Historic Marker at TBI\n| map_type              =\n| map_size              =\n| map_caption           =\n| location              =4901 N. Pennsylvania,<br>[[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]],<br/>{{flag|United States}}\n| geo                   = {{coord|35.5205476|-97.5506019|display=inline,title}}\n| religious_affiliation =[[Reform Judaism]]\n| rite                  =\n| region                =\n| province              =\n| territory             =\n| prefecture            =\n| sector                =\n| district              =\n| cercle                =\n| municipality          =\n| consecration_year     =1955\n| status                =\n| functional_status     =Active\n| heritage_designation  =\n| leadership            =Rabbi:&nbsp;Vered Harris<br/>Zemer:&nbsp;Linda Sweeney\n| website               ={{url|thetempleokc.org}}\n| architecture          =yes\n| architect             =\n| architecture_type     =\n| architecture_style    =\n| general_contractor    =\n| facade_direction      =\n| groundbreaking        =\n| year_completed        =1955\n| construction_cost     =\n| specifications        =\n| capacity              =\n| length                =\n| width                 =\n| width_nave            =\n| height_max            =\n| dome_quantity         =\n| dome_height_outer     =\n| dome_height_inner     =\n| dome_dia_outer        =\n| dome_dia_inner        =\n| minaret_quantity      =\n| minaret_height        =\n| spire_quantity        =\n| spire_height          =\n| materials             =\n| nrhp                  =\n| added                 =\n| refnum                =\n| designated            =\n}}\n\n'''Temple B'nai Israel''' is a [[Reform Judaism|Reform Jewish]] congregation located in [[Oklahoma City]],<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref> and is the oldest active Jewish synagogue in Oklahoma.<ref>[https://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=JE009|''Oklahoma History.org'' \"Judaism in Oklahoma\"]</ref> \n\n==History==\n\n===Early 20th Century===\n\nThe congregation was founded in May 1903<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref><ref>[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-oklahoma-city-encyclopedia.html | ''Encyclopedia of Southern Jewish Communities'' \"Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\"]</ref><ref>\"From a synagogue: Jews of Oklahoma City met last night in a Christian church\" ''The Oklahoman'' (May 2, 1903)</ref> but it met at [[St. Luke's Methodist church]] and other local churches<ref>[''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Historic Marker - First Permanent Jewish House of Worship in Oklahoma\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/mdpa/oklahomacityoklahoma.html]</ref> until it constructed its own building in 1907.<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref><ref>[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-oklahoma-city-encyclopedia.html|''Encyclopedia of Southern Jewish Communities'' \"Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\"]</ref> This building was located at 50 Broadway Circle and was dedicated on January 17, 1908<ref>[''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Historic Marker - First Permanent Jewish House of Worship in Oklahoma\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/mdpa/oklahomacityoklahoma.html]</ref> (only about 2 months after Oklahoma became a state). \n\nFor the congregation's first high holiday services in 1903, the service led by a student rabbi from the Reform movement's [[Hebrew Union College]] in Cincinnati, Harry Friedman, while regular Shabbat services were led by Gus Paul (the city attorney of Oklahoma City)<ref>[http://www.jmaw.org/jewish-oklahoma-city-jew/ | ''Jewish Museum of the American West'' \"Jewish Pioneers of Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\"]</ref>. The following year, the congregation hired its first full-time rabbi, Arthur Lewisohn (also a student at HUC), but his tenure was short as he tragically died in 1905.<ref>[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-oklahoma-city-encyclopedia.html | ''Encyclopedia of Southern Jewish Communities'' \"Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\"] Please note that some sources omit Rabbi Lewisohn from the list of the congregation's rabbis due to his being a student rabbi, but he was the first professional full-time rabbi of the conregation.</ref> Lewisohn's death did not stop the congregation from holding its first confirmation service for six graduates, said at the time to be the first Jewish confirmation services held in the Oklahoma and Indian territories.<ref>\"Confirmation Service Held\" ''The Oklahoman'' (June 11, 1905) - (available for Metrolibrary.org library users via the Oklahoman database)</ref>\n\nThe congregation called its longest serving rabbi, Joseph Blatt in 1906 who served until 1946.<ref>[''JewishVirtualLibrary.org'' \"Oklahoma Jewish History\" |https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/oklahoma-jewish-history]</ref><ref>[Klinger, Jerry ''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Oklahoma, a Jewish story\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/images/Oklahoma_Marker-3.pdf]</ref> Rabbi Blatt is remembered for his [[Classical Reform Judaism|classical reform]] approach<ref>By an example, an ad placed in the Sept. 26, 1906 edition of ''The Oklahoman'' offered music lessons from a \"Wm. A. Gray\" who was currently serving as both the choir director of St. Paul's Episcopal Cathedral and as  music director at Temple B'nai Israel. - (resource available from the Oklahoman archives at Metrolibrary.org)</ref>, interfaith efforts (including guest speaking at many churches in Oklahoma City), but also for his strident defense of the Jewish community in the face of anti-semitic accusations by the ''Guthrie Daily Leader'' newspaper (accusations that the state capitol's move from Guthrie to Oklahoma City was inappropriately orchestrated by a group of prominent Jewish businessmen in Oklahoma City).<ref>[ | ''Guthrie Daily Leader'' \"Shylocks of Oklahoma City have state by the throat\" (Nov. 1, 1912) - Archived from the Oklahoma Historical Society]</ref> Rabbi Blatt responded that the newspaper's claims were slanderous and that they were a \u201ca disgrace to the civilization of our state.\u201d<ref>[https://www.sdjewishworld.com/2016/11/21/a-short-history-of-jewish-oklahoma/ | ''San Diego Jewish World'' \"A Short history of Jewish Oklahoma\" (Nov. 21, 2016)]</ref><ref>[https://www.myjewishlearning.com/southern-and-jewish/the-guthrie-incident-an-episode-of-anti-semitism-in-oklahoma/ | Rockoff, Stuart, ''MyJewishLearning.com'' \"The Guthrie incident, an episode of anti-semitism in Oklahoma\" (Nov. 26, 2012)]</ref>\n\n===Mid 20th Century===\n\nJoseph Levenson served as rabbi for 30 years, from 1946-1976.<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Obituary - Rabbi Joseph Levenson\" (February 3, 2006) |https://oklahoman.com/article/2930018/rabbi-joseph-levenson]</ref><ref>[''Findagrave.com'' \"Joseph Levenson\" |https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/44430411/joseph-levenson]</ref> Major events during his rabbinate included the congregation's move into its current building (at what was then the edge of Oklahoma City, near NW 50th & Penn) in 1955,<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref><ref>[''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Historic Marker - First Permanent Jewish House of Worship in Oklahoma\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/mdpa/oklahomacityoklahoma.html]</ref> as well a tornado that hit the synagogue in 1970; necessitating significant repairs.<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref> It was during the rabinnate of Rabbi Levenson that the congregation moved decided towards a [[zionist]] orientation, in contrast to the classical reform's non-zionist tradition.<ref>Cite needed</ref>\n\n===Late 20th Century===\n\nDavid A. Packman served as rabbi of the Temple from 1976-2004<ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4464773/rabbi-david-packman-lament]</ref><ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Rabbi's retirement recognized\" |https://oklahoman.com/article/2856058/rabbis-retirement-recognized]</ref> His years of service were marked by increased involvement by the congregation in interfaith efforts,<ref>[http://city-sentinel.com/2020/02/rabbi-a-david-packman-rabbi-emeritus-of-temple-bnai-israel-dies/ \"Rabbi David A. Packman, Rabbi Emeritus of Temple Bnai Israel dies\" ''City Sentinel'' (Feb. 2020 Oklahoma City)]</ref> most notably Oklahoma City's annual Interfaith Thanksgiving service.<ref>[https://oklahoman.com/article/5654818/memorial-services-set-for-renaissance-man-rabbi-david-packman| Hinton, Carla \"Memorial services set for 'renaissance man' Rabbi David Packman\" ''The Oklahoman'' (Feb. 13, 2020)</ref>\n\n===21st Century===\n\nRabbi Barry Cohen began his rabbinate in Oklahoma in 2004 and served until 2012.<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Oklahoma City Rabbi's family celebrates miracles during hanukkah\" |https://oklahoman.com/article/3632548/oklahoma-city-rabbis-family-celebrates-miracles-during-hanukkah]</ref> It was also in 2004 that synagogue building was bombed by a member of the [[Aryan Nation]] but only minor damage was done to the building with no injuries. The assailant was later sentenced to 39 years in prison.<ref>[MSNBC \"Oklahoma synagogue bomber gets 39 years : Washington state man threw Molotov cocktail, sent letter to congregation\" (April 30, 2005) |https://web.archive.org/web/20051227200436/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/9136468/]</ref><ref>[https://www.adl.org/news/article/white-supremacist-arrested-in-oklahoma-synagogue-attack?print=true}\"White Supremacist arrested in Oklahoma synagogue attack\" ''ADL.org''(April 26, 2004)]</ref><ref>[https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-10th-circuit/1151798.html | UNITED STATES of America, Plaintiff-Appellee, v. Sean Michael GILLESPIE, Defendant-Appellant (10th Circuit, June 30, 2006)]</ref>\n\nDuring the covid pandemic of 2020, the congregation began holding all of its worship services and educational programming via online streaming services, as well as providing resources to enable members in social isolation to have the needed supplies to celebrate [[Passover]] at home.<ref>[https://oklahoman.com/article/5659916/coronavirus-in-oklahoma-faith-communities-are-as-busy-as-ever-amid-pandemic | Hinton, Carla \"Coronavirus in Oklahoma: Faith Communities are as busy as ever amid pandemic\" (April 11, 2020)</ref>\n\n==Current Programs==\n\nToday the congregation holds weekly Shabbat evening services, monthly Shabbat morning services and a variety of special observances for Jewish holidays.<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Water ritual helps mark Rosh Hashanah, the Jewish New Year\" (Oct. 5, 2019)|Thttps://oklahoman.com/article/5642915/water-ritual-helps-mark-rosh-hashana-the-jewish-new-year]</ref> It is led by Rabbi Vered Harris.\n\nThe congregation also hosts a pre-school, a Hebrew school and works in cooperation with Emanuel Synagogue (a Conservative synagogue in Oklahoma City) to operate an Inter-congregational Sunday School. Hebrew and other educational programming is provided for adult learners and the congregation has an active social justice program which focuses on issues related to hunger, poverty and the rights of refugees.\n\n==Rabbis==\n* Arthur Lewisohn (served from 1904-1905)<ref>[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-oklahoma-city-encyclopedia.html]</ref>\n* Joseph Blatt (served from 1906-1946)<ref>[''JewishVirtualLibrary.org'' \"Oklahoma Jewish History\" |https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/oklahoma-jewish-history]</ref><ref>[Klinger, Jerry ''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Oklahoma, a Jewish story\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/images/Oklahoma_Marker-3.pdf]</ref>\n* Joseph Levenson (served from 1946-1976)<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Obituary - Rabbi Joseph Levenson\" (February 3, 2006) |https://oklahoman.com/article/2930018/rabbi-joseph-levenson]</ref><ref>[''Findagrave.com'' \"Joseph Levenson\" |https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/44430411/joseph-levenson]</ref>\n* David A. Packman (served from 1976-2004)<ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4464773/rabbi-david-packman-lament]</ref><ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Rabbi's retirement recognized\" |https://oklahoman.com/article/2856058/rabbis-retirement-recognized]</ref>\n* Barry Cohen (served from 2004-2012)<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Oklahoma City Rabbi's family celebrates miracles during hanukkah\" |https://oklahoman.com/article/3632548/oklahoma-city-rabbis-family-celebrates-miracles-during-hanukkah]</ref>\n* Vered Harris (served from 2012-present)<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Oklahoma City temple's new rabbi had faith piqued at college\" (July 14, 2012)|https://oklahoman.com/article/3692107/oklahoma-city-temples-new-rabbi-had-faith-piqued-at-college-camp]</ref><ref>[''New York Times'' \" Praying for the Home Team in Oklahoma City\" (Feb. 28, 2014) |https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/sports/basketball/praying-for-the-home-team-in-oklahoma-city.html]</ref>\n\n==Prominent members==\n* [[Sylvan Goldman]] (1898-1984) inventor of the [[shopping cart]]\n* [[Leo Meyer]], Oklahoma State Auditor from 1911-1915<ref>[https://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=JE009</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Israel (Oklahoma City, Oklahoma)}}\n[[Category:1903 establishments in Oklahoma Territory]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Oklahoma City]]\n[[Category:Reform synagogues in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations established in 1903]]\n[[Category:Synagogues completed in 1955]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|similarly named synagogues|B'nai Israel (disambiguation){{!}}B'nai Israel}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| building_name         =Temple B'nai Israel\n| image                 =Tbi-historicmarker.jpg\n| image_upright = \n| caption               =Historic Marker at TBI\n| map_type              =\n| map_size              =\n| map_caption           =\n| location              =4901 N. Pennsylvania,<br>[[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]],<br/>{{flag|United States}}\n| geo                   = {{coord|35.5205476|-97.5506019|display=inline,title}}\n| religious_affiliation =[[Reform Judaism]]\n| rite                  =\n| region                =\n| province              =\n| territory             =\n| prefecture            =\n| sector                =\n| district              =\n| cercle                =\n| municipality          =\n| consecration_year     =1955\n| status                =\n| functional_status     =Active\n| heritage_designation  =\n| leadership            =Rabbi:&nbsp;Vered Harris<br/>Zemer:&nbsp;Linda Sweeney\n| website               ={{url|thetempleokc.org}}\n| architecture          =yes\n| architect             =\n| architecture_type     =\n| architecture_style    =\n| general_contractor    =\n| facade_direction      =\n| groundbreaking        =\n| year_completed        =1955\n| construction_cost     =\n| specifications        =\n| capacity              =\n| length                =\n| width                 =\n| width_nave            =\n| height_max            =\n| dome_quantity         =\n| dome_height_outer     =\n| dome_height_inner     =\n| dome_dia_outer        =\n| dome_dia_inner        =\n| minaret_quantity      =\n| minaret_height        =\n| spire_quantity        =\n| spire_height          =\n| materials             =\n| nrhp                  =\n| added                 =\n| refnum                =\n| designated            =\n}}\n\n'''Temple B'nai Israel''' is a [[Reform Judaism|Reform Jewish]] congregation located in [[Oklahoma City]],<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref> and is the oldest active Jewish synagogue in Oklahoma.<ref>[https://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=JE009|''Oklahoma History.org'' \"Judaism in Oklahoma\"]</ref> \n\n==History==\n\n===Early 20th Century===\n\nThe congregation was founded in May 1903<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref><ref>[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-oklahoma-city-encyclopedia.html | ''Encyclopedia of Southern Jewish Communities'' \"Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\"]</ref><ref>\"From a synagogue: Jews of Oklahoma City met last night in a Christian church\" ''The Oklahoman'' (May 2, 1903)</ref> but it met at [[St. Luke's Methodist church]] and other local churches<ref>[''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Historic Marker - First Permanent Jewish House of Worship in Oklahoma\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/mdpa/oklahomacityoklahoma.html]</ref> until it constructed its own building in 1907.<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref><ref>[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-oklahoma-city-encyclopedia.html|''Encyclopedia of Southern Jewish Communities'' \"Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\"]</ref> This building was located at 50 Broadway Circle and was dedicated on January 17, 1908<ref>[''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Historic Marker - First Permanent Jewish House of Worship in Oklahoma\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/mdpa/oklahomacityoklahoma.html]</ref> (only about 2 months after Oklahoma became a state). \n\nFor the congregation's first high holiday services in 1903, the service led by a student rabbi from the Reform movement's [[Hebrew Union College]] in Cincinnati, Harry Friedman, while regular Shabbat services were led by Gus Paul (the city attorney of Oklahoma City)<ref>[http://www.jmaw.org/jewish-oklahoma-city-jew/ | ''Jewish Museum of the American West'' \"Jewish Pioneers of Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\"]</ref>. The following year, the congregation hired its first full-time rabbi, Arthur Lewisohn (also a student at HUC), but his tenure was short as he tragically died in 1905.<ref>[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-oklahoma-city-encyclopedia.html | ''Encyclopedia of Southern Jewish Communities'' \"Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\"] Please note that some sources omit Rabbi Lewisohn from the list of the congregation's rabbis due to his being a student rabbi, but he was the first professional full-time rabbi of the conregation.</ref> Lewisohn's death did not stop the congregation from holding its first confirmation service for six graduates, said at the time to be the first Jewish confirmation services held in the Oklahoma and Indian territories.<ref>\"Confirmation Service Held\" ''The Oklahoman'' (June 11, 1905) - (available for Metrolibrary.org library users via the Oklahoman database)</ref>\n\nThe congregation called its longest serving rabbi, Joseph Blatt in 1906 who served until 1946.<ref>[''JewishVirtualLibrary.org'' \"Oklahoma Jewish History\" |https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/oklahoma-jewish-history]</ref><ref>[Klinger, Jerry ''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Oklahoma, a Jewish story\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/images/Oklahoma_Marker-3.pdf]</ref> Rabbi Blatt is remembered for his [[Classical Reform Judaism|classical reform]] approach<ref>By an example, an ad placed in the Sept. 26, 1906 edition of ''The Oklahoman'' offered music lessons from a \"Wm. A. Gray\" who was currently serving as both the choir director of St. Paul's Episcopal Cathedral and as  music director at Temple B'nai Israel. - (resource available from the Oklahoman archives at Metrolibrary.org)</ref>, interfaith efforts (including guest speaking at many churches in Oklahoma City), but also for his strident defense of the Jewish community in the face of anti-semitic accusations by the ''Guthrie Daily Leader'' newspaper, that that the state capitol's move from Guthrie to Oklahoma City was orchestrated by a group of prominent Jewish businessmen in Oklahoma City.<ref>[ | ''Guthrie Daily Leader'' \"Shylocks of Oklahoma City have state by the throat\" (Nov. 1, 1912) - Archived from the Oklahoma Historical Society]</ref> Rabbi Blatt responded that the newspaper's claims were slanderous and that they were a \u201ca disgrace to the civilization of our state.\u201d<ref>[https://www.sdjewishworld.com/2016/11/21/a-short-history-of-jewish-oklahoma/ | ''San Diego Jewish World'' \"A Short history of Jewish Oklahoma\" (Nov. 21, 2016)]</ref><ref>[https://www.myjewishlearning.com/southern-and-jewish/the-guthrie-incident-an-episode-of-anti-semitism-in-oklahoma/ | Rockoff, Stuart, ''MyJewishLearning.com'' \"The Guthrie incident, an episode of anti-semitism in Oklahoma\" (Nov. 26, 2012)]</ref>\n\n===Mid 20th Century===\n\nJoseph Levenson served as rabbi for 30 years, from 1946-1976.<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Obituary - Rabbi Joseph Levenson\" (February 3, 2006) |https://oklahoman.com/article/2930018/rabbi-joseph-levenson]</ref><ref>[''Findagrave.com'' \"Joseph Levenson\" |https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/44430411/joseph-levenson]</ref> Major events during his rabbinate included the congregation's move into its current building (at what was then the edge of Oklahoma City, near NW 50th & Penn) in 1955,<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref><ref>[''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Historic Marker - First Permanent Jewish House of Worship in Oklahoma\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/mdpa/oklahomacityoklahoma.html]</ref> as well a tornado that hit the synagogue in 1970; necessitating significant repairs.<ref name=Homepage>[[#refHomepage|Temple B'nai Israel website]]</ref> It was during the rabinnate of Rabbi Levenson that the congregation moved decided towards a [[zionist]] orientation, in contrast to the classical reform's non-zionist tradition.<ref>Cite needed</ref>\n\n===Late 20th Century===\n\nDavid A. Packman served as rabbi of the Temple from 1976-2004<ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4464773/rabbi-david-packman-lament]</ref><ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Rabbi's retirement recognized\" |https://oklahoman.com/article/2856058/rabbis-retirement-recognized]</ref> His years of service were marked by increased involvement by the congregation in interfaith efforts,<ref>[http://city-sentinel.com/2020/02/rabbi-a-david-packman-rabbi-emeritus-of-temple-bnai-israel-dies/ \"Rabbi David A. Packman, Rabbi Emeritus of Temple Bnai Israel dies\" ''City Sentinel'' (Feb. 2020 Oklahoma City)]</ref> most notably Oklahoma City's annual Interfaith Thanksgiving service.<ref>[https://oklahoman.com/article/5654818/memorial-services-set-for-renaissance-man-rabbi-david-packman| Hinton, Carla \"Memorial services set for 'renaissance man' Rabbi David Packman\" ''The Oklahoman'' (Feb. 13, 2020)</ref>\n\n===21st Century===\n\nRabbi Barry Cohen began his rabbinate in Oklahoma in 2004 and served until 2012.<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Oklahoma City Rabbi's family celebrates miracles during hanukkah\" |https://oklahoman.com/article/3632548/oklahoma-city-rabbis-family-celebrates-miracles-during-hanukkah]</ref> It was also in 2004 that synagogue building was bombed by a member of the [[Aryan Nation]] but only minor damage was done to the building with no injuries. The assailant was later sentenced to 39 years in prison.<ref>[MSNBC \"Oklahoma synagogue bomber gets 39 years : Washington state man threw Molotov cocktail, sent letter to congregation\" (April 30, 2005) |https://web.archive.org/web/20051227200436/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/9136468/]</ref><ref>[https://www.adl.org/news/article/white-supremacist-arrested-in-oklahoma-synagogue-attack?print=true}\"White Supremacist arrested in Oklahoma synagogue attack\" ''ADL.org''(April 26, 2004)]</ref><ref>[https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-10th-circuit/1151798.html | UNITED STATES of America, Plaintiff-Appellee, v. Sean Michael GILLESPIE, Defendant-Appellant (10th Circuit, June 30, 2006)]</ref>\n\nDuring the covid pandemic of 2020, the congregation began holding all of its worship services and educational programming via online streaming services, as well as providing resources to enable members in social isolation to have the needed supplies to celebrate [[Passover]] at home.<ref>[https://oklahoman.com/article/5659916/coronavirus-in-oklahoma-faith-communities-are-as-busy-as-ever-amid-pandemic | Hinton, Carla \"Coronavirus in Oklahoma: Faith Communities are as busy as ever amid pandemic\" (April 11, 2020)</ref>\n\n==Current Programs==\n\nToday the congregation holds weekly Shabbat evening services, monthly Shabbat morning services and a variety of special observances for Jewish holidays.<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Water ritual helps mark Rosh Hashanah, the Jewish New Year\" (Oct. 5, 2019)|Thttps://oklahoman.com/article/5642915/water-ritual-helps-mark-rosh-hashana-the-jewish-new-year]</ref> It is led by Rabbi Vered Harris.\n\nThe congregation also hosts a pre-school, a Hebrew school and works in cooperation with Emanuel Synagogue (a Conservative synagogue in Oklahoma City) to operate an Inter-congregational Sunday School. Hebrew and other educational programming is provided for adult learners and the congregation has an active social justice program which focuses on issues related to hunger, poverty and the rights of refugees.\n\n==Rabbis==\n* Arthur Lewisohn (served from 1904-1905)<ref>[https://www.isjl.org/oklahoma-oklahoma-city-encyclopedia.html]</ref>\n* Joseph Blatt (served from 1906-1946)<ref>[''JewishVirtualLibrary.org'' \"Oklahoma Jewish History\" |https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/oklahoma-jewish-history]</ref><ref>[Klinger, Jerry ''Jewish American Society for Historic Preservation'' \"Oklahoma, a Jewish story\"|http://www.jewish-american-society-for-historic-preservation.org/images/Oklahoma_Marker-3.pdf]</ref>\n* Joseph Levenson (served from 1946-1976)<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Obituary - Rabbi Joseph Levenson\" (February 3, 2006) |https://oklahoman.com/article/2930018/rabbi-joseph-levenson]</ref><ref>[''Findagrave.com'' \"Joseph Levenson\" |https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/44430411/joseph-levenson]</ref>\n* David A. Packman (served from 1976-2004)<ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4464773/rabbi-david-packman-lament]</ref><ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Rabbi's retirement recognized\" |https://oklahoman.com/article/2856058/rabbis-retirement-recognized]</ref>\n* Barry Cohen (served from 2004-2012)<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Oklahoma City Rabbi's family celebrates miracles during hanukkah\" |https://oklahoman.com/article/3632548/oklahoma-city-rabbis-family-celebrates-miracles-during-hanukkah]</ref>\n* Vered Harris (served from 2012-present)<ref>[''The Oklahoman'' \"Oklahoma City temple's new rabbi had faith piqued at college\" (July 14, 2012)|https://oklahoman.com/article/3692107/oklahoma-city-temples-new-rabbi-had-faith-piqued-at-college-camp]</ref><ref>[''New York Times'' \" Praying for the Home Team in Oklahoma City\" (Feb. 28, 2014) |https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/sports/basketball/praying-for-the-home-team-in-oklahoma-city.html]</ref>\n\n==Prominent members==\n* [[Sylvan Goldman]] (1898-1984) inventor of the [[shopping cart]]\n* [[Leo Meyer]], Oklahoma State Auditor from 1911-1915<ref>[https://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=JE009</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Israel (Oklahoma City, Oklahoma)}}\n[[Category:1903 establishments in Oklahoma Territory]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Oklahoma City]]\n[[Category:Reform synagogues in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations established in 1903]]\n[[Category:Synagogues completed in 1955]]\n", "name_user": "Jmbranum", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly 20th Century:fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temple_B%27nai_Israel_(Oklahoma_City)"}
{"title_page": "Samuel J. Tilden", "text_new": "{{short description|19th-century American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Samuel Tilden\n|image        = SamuelJonesTilden.jpg\n|order        = 25th [[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]]\n|lieutenant   = [[William Dorsheimer]]\n|term_start   = January 1, 1875\n|term_end     = December 31, 1876\n|predecessor  = [[John Adams Dix]]\n|successor    = [[Lucius Robinson]]\n|office1      = Member of the [[New York State Assembly]]<br>from [[Manhattan|New York County]]'s 18th district\n|term_start1  = January 1, 1872\n|term_end1    = December 31, 1872\n|predecessor1 = Leander Buck\n|successor1   = [[Biglin Brothers|Barney Biglin]]\n|office2      = Chair of the [[New York State Democratic Committee|New York Democratic Party]]\n|term_start2  = August 1866\n|term_end2    = September 1874\n|predecessor2 = [[Dean Richmond]]\n|successor2   = [[Allen C. Beach]]\n|office3      = Member of the New York State Assembly from [[Manhattan|New York County]]\n|alongside3   = 13 others<br/>(Multi-member district)\n|term_start3  = 1846\n|term_end3    = 1847\n|predecessor3 = Various (Multi-member district)\n|successor3   = Various (Multi-member district)\n|office4      = [[New York City Law Department|Corporation Counsel]] of [[New York City]]\n|term_start4  = 1843\n|term_end4    = 1844\n|predecessor4 = Alexander W. Bradford\n|successor4   = Stephen Sammons\n|birth_name   = Samuel Jones Tilden\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1814|2|9}}\n|birth_place  = [[New Lebanon, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1886|8|4|1814|2|9}}\n|death_place  = [[Yonkers, New York]], U.S.\n|restingplace = [[Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument]], Cemetery of the Evergreens, New Lebanon, New York\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[Yale University]]<br>[[New York University]]\n|signature    = Samuel Tilden Signature.svg\n}}\n'''Samuel Jones Tilden ''' (February 9, 1814 \u2013 August 4, 1886) was the 25th [[Governor of New York]] and the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] candidate for president in the [[1876 United States presidential election|disputed election of 1876]]. As of 2020, Tilden is the only individual to [[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|win an outright majority of the popular vote]] in a [[United States presidential election]] but lose the election.{{efn|As of 2020, four candidates have lost a presidential election despite garnering a [[plurality (voting)|plurality]] of the popular vote; [[Andrew Jackson]] in [[1824 United States presidential election|1824]]; [[Grover Cleveland]] in [[1888 United States presidential election|1888]]; [[Al Gore]] in [[2000 United States presidential election|2000]]; and [[Hillary Clinton]] in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]].}} \n\nTilden was born into a wealthy family in [[New Lebanon, New York]]. Attracted to politics at a young age, he became a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Martin Van Buren]], the eighth [[President of the United States]]. After studying at [[Yale University]] and [[New York University School of Law]], Tilden began a legal career in [[New York City]], becoming a noted corporate lawyer. He served in the [[New York State Assembly]] and helped launch Van Buren's [[third party (United States)|third party]], anti-[[slavery in the United States|slavery]] candidacy in the [[1848 United States presidential election|1848 presidential election]]. Though he opposed the election of [[Abraham Lincoln]] in 1860, Tilden supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] during the [[American Civil War]]. After the Civil War, Tilden was selected as the chairman of the [[New York State Democratic Committee]], and he managed Democratic nominee [[Horatio Seymour]]'s campaign in the [[1868 United States presidential election|1868 presidential election]]. \n\nTilden initially cooperated with the state party's [[Tammany Hall]] faction, but he broke with them in 1871 due to boss [[William M. Tweed]]'s rampant corruption. Tilden won election as [[Governor of New York]] in 1874, and in that office he helped break up the \"[[Canal Ring (New York)|Canal Ring]].\" Tilden's battle against public corruption, along with his personal fortune and electoral success in the country's most populous state, made him the leading candidate for the Democratic nomination for president in 1876. Tilden was selected as the nominee on the second ballot of the [[1876 Democratic National Convention]]. In the general election, Tilden faced [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Rutherford B. Hayes]], another governor with reform credentials. Tilden focused his campaign on civil service reform, support for the [[gold standard]], and opposition to high taxes, but many of his supporters were more concerned with ending [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] in the South.\n\nMost observers initially believed that Tilden had won the election, but disputes in four states left both Tilden and Hayes without a majority of the [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral vote]]. As Tilden had won 184 electoral votes, one vote shy of a majority, a Hayes victory required that he sweep all of the disputed electoral votes. Against Tilden's wishes, Congress appointed the bipartisan [[Electoral Commission (United States)|Electoral Commission]] to settle the controversy. Republicans had a one-seat advantage on the Electoral Commission, and in a series of party-line rulings, ruled that Hayes had won all of the disputed electoral votes. In the [[Compromise of 1877]], Democratic leaders agreed to accept Hayes as the victor in return for the end of Reconstruction. Tilden was a major contender for the Democratic presidential nomination in the [[1880 United States presidential election|1880]] and [[1884 United States presidential election|1884 presidential elections]], but declined to run.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[Image:SamuelJTilden.jpeg|thumb|Samuel Tilden as a young man]]\n\nTilden was born in [[New Lebanon, New York]], the youngest son of Elam Tilden and Polly Jones Tilden.<ref>Bigelow (2009), pp. 12\u201315</ref> He was descended from [[Tylden (family)|Nathaniel Tilden]], an early [[English people|English]] settler who came to [[North America]] in 1634. His father and other family members were the makers of [[Tilden's Extract]], a popular [[patent medicine]] of the 1800s and early 1900s derived from [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]].<ref>William Lee Richter, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cyGb-eMnmXkC&pg=PA610 ''Historical Dictionary of the Civil War and Reconstruction''], 2004, page 610</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=psbmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA117 Obituary, Samuel J. Tilden (nephew of New York Governor)], ''The Pharmaceutical Era'', March 1914, page 117</ref> Tilden's father maintained relationships with many influential politicians, including President [[Martin Van Buren]], who became Tilden's political idol. Tilden was frequently in poor health during his youth, and he spent much of his time studying politics and reading works such as ''[[The Wealth of Nations]]''. Tilden's health troubles prevented him from regularly attending school, and he dropped out of [[Yale University]] after a single term.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 84\u201386</ref>\n\nLikely motivated by a family friendship with [[Benjamin Franklin Butler (lawyer)|Benjamin Franklin Butler]], then serving as a professor at [[New York University School of Law]], Tilden enrolled there to resume his studies, and he continued to attend intermittently from 1838 to 1841.<ref>{{cite book|title=The life and public services of Hon. Samuel J. Tilden: Democratic nominee ...|author=Theodore Pease Cook|page=9}}</ref> While studying at NYU, Tilden also [[reading law|read law]] in the office of attorney [[John W. Edmonds]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Scharf |first=John Thomas |date=1886 |title=History of Westchester County, New York |volume=Volume 1, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EkgVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA504 |location=Philadelphia, PA |publisher=L. E. Preston & Co. |page=554 |ref={{sfnRef|''History of Westchester County, New York''}}}}</ref> He was admitted to the bar in 1841 and became a skilled [[corporate lawyer]].{{sfn|''History of Westchester County, New York''|page=554}} Unlike many New York attorneys, Tilden affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], and he frequently campaigned on behalf of Van Buren and other Democratic candidates.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 86\u201389</ref>\n\n== Early political career ==\n[[File:MVanBuren.png|thumb|upright=0.9|Tilden was a protege of [[Martin Van Buren]], the 8th [[President of the United States]].]]\n\nIn 1843, as a reward for campaign work on behalf of Governor [[William C. Bouck]], Tilden was appointed as New York City's corporation counsel. Tilden handled hundreds of cases on behalf of the city, but was forced out of office in 1844 after New York City elected a [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]] mayor. He served as a delegate to the [[1844 Democratic National Convention]], which rejected Van Buren and nominated [[James K. Polk]] for president. At the urging of Governor [[Silas Wright]], Tilden won election to the [[New York State Assembly]]. He became a key ally to Wright and helped end the [[Anti-Rent War]] by passing a compromise land bill that defused tensions between tenant farmers and their landlords. After serving as a delegate to the 1846 [[New York State Constitutional Convention]], Tilden left public office to focus on his legal practice, where he gained a national reputation as a \"financial physician\" for struggling railroads.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 89\u201393</ref> Tilden's successful legal practice, combined with shrewd investments, made him rich. His success at money management and investing caused many of his friends, relatives, and political allies, including Van Buren, to allow Tilden to manage their finances.<ref>Severn (1968), p. 64</ref>\n\nTilden helped to found the \"[[Barnburner]]s\", an anti-[[slavery in the United States|slavery]] faction of the New York Democratic Party that arose in the midst of the debate over the [[Wilmot Proviso]]. Like other Barnburners, Tilden sought to prevent the spread of slavery into the [[Mexican cession|land acquired from Mexico]] in the [[Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo]]. He helped organize the 1848 [[Free Soil Party|Free Soil]] Convention, which nominated Van Buren for president. Van Buren's candidacy in the [[1848 United States presidential election|1848 presidential election]] may have played a role in the victory of Whig nominee [[Zachary Taylor]] over Democratic nominee [[Lewis Cass]]. Unlike many other anti-slavery Democrats, Tilden did not join the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] in the 1850s, but he did not have close relations with Democratic presidents [[Franklin Pierce]] and [[James Buchanan]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 94\u201395</ref> In [[New York state election, 1855|1855]], Tilden was the unsuccessful [[New York State Attorney General|state attorney general]] candidate of the \"[[Hunkers and Barnburners|Soft]]\" faction of Barnburners, which favored compromise and reconciliation with the Democratic Party.<ref>Robinson (2001), p. 85</ref> In [[New York state election, 1859|1859]], after he lost an election to serve as New York City's corporation counsel, Tilden announced that he was \"out of politics.\"<ref>Morris (2003), p. 95</ref>\n\nIn the [[1860 United States presidential election|1860 presidential election]], Tilden strongly opposed the candidacy of Republican presidential nominee [[Abraham Lincoln]]. He warned that the election of Lincoln could lead to the secession of the South and a subsequent civil war.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 95\u201396</ref> Tilden initially opposed using force to prevent secession, but he supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] after the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]]. Tilden served as the manager of [[Horatio Seymour]]'s successful 1862 campaign for governor, and played a key role in securing the nomination of [[George B. McClellan]] at the [[1864 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 96\u201397</ref>\n\nIn 1867, Tilden received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from [[New York University]].<ref>{{cite book |last=General Alumni Society, New York University |date=1906 |title=General Alumni Catalogue |url=https://archive.org/details/generalalumnica01univgoog |location=New York, NY |publisher=New York University |page=170}}</ref> He was also chosen as a delegate to that year's [[New York Constitution#Constitutional Convention of 1867\u20131868|state constitutional convention]].<ref>{{cite news |date=June 4, 1867 |title=The Constitutional Convention to Assemble To-Day |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/329585675/ |work=[[New York Herald]] |location=New York, NY |url-access=subscription |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |page=7}}</ref>\n\n== State party leader ==\n[[File:SamuelTilden.png|thumb|right|upright|A portrait of Samuel Jones Tilden]]\n\nFollowing the end of the Civil War, Tilden won election as the chairman of the [[New York State Democratic Committee]]. He served as Seymour's campaign chairman in the [[1868 United States presidential election|1868 presidential election]], but Seymour lost the election to Republican nominee [[Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 97\u201398</ref> After the election, Tilden broke with [[William M. Tweed]], the leader of the [[Tammany Hall]] [[political machine]]. Through bribery, patronage, and control of [[Irish-American]] voters, Tweed and his allies had become the dominant power in both New York City and the state of New York.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 99\u2013102</ref> In 1871, former Tammany associate [[James O'Brien (U.S. Congressman)|James O'Brien]] leaked Tweed's account books to the ''[[New York Times]]''. The ''Times'' subsequently began a public crusade against Tammany Hall, and Tilden launched an investigation into Tweed's bank records. Tilden ran for the New York State Assembly as part of a slate of anti-Tammany Democrats; at the state party convention, he declared that it was \"time to proclaim that whoever plunders the people, though he steal the livery of heaven to serve the devil in, is no Democrat.\" The anti-Tammany Democrats, including Tilden, won a major victory in the [[New York state election, 1871|1871 state elections]], and Tweed was indicted on 120 counts of fraud and other violations. After the election, Tweed fled the state, but he was eventually extradited back to New York, where he died in prison in 1878.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nTilden's role in taking down Tweed bolstered his popularity, and he was elected Governor of New York in [[New York state election, 1874|1874]]. As governor, he continued to focus on rooting out corruption. He helped to break up the \"[[Canal Ring (New York)|Canal Ring]],\" a bipartisan group of state and local officials who had enriched themselves by overcharging for the maintenance of the [[New York State Canal System]]. Tilden gained a national reputation as a reform governor, a valuable asset given the number of [[Grant administration scandals|scandals]] that had come into public view during the [[presidency of Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 104\u2013105</ref>\n\nIn 1875, Tilden received an honorary LL.D. from [[Yale University]].<ref name=Yale_Catalogue>{{cite book |last=Yale University |date=1877 |title=Catalogue of the Officers and Graduates of Yale University |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=UahGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA51 |location=New Haven, CT |publisher=Morehouse and Taylor |page=51}}</ref> At the same time, Yale also enrolled him as a graduate of the Class of 1837 and he received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree.<ref name=\"Yale_Catalogue\"/>\n\n==Presidential election of 1876==\n{{See also|Samuel Tilden presidential campaign, 1876}}\n\n===Democratic nomination===\n[[Image:Tilden and Hendricks campaign poster.jpg|thumb|Campaign poster for the election of 1876]]\n\nBy the time of the June [[1876 Democratic National Convention]], Tilden had emerged as the front-runner for the Democratic nomination in the [[1876 United States presidential election|1876 presidential election]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 106</ref> Tilden's appeal to the national party was based on his reputation for reform and his electoral success in the country's most populous state. He was also a skilled organizer whose canvassing system and field knowledge was so thorough that, months before the 1874 election, he'd predicted his own winning margin accurately to within 300 votes.<ref>Holt (2008), p. 100</ref> Tilden further bolstered his presidential candidacy through a nationwide newspaper advertising campaign. As many Democrats expected that their party would win the 1876 presidential elections, Tilden faced competition from some of the party's most prominent leaders, including [[Thomas F. Bayard]], [[Allen G. Thurman]], [[Thomas A. Hendricks]], and General [[Winfield Scott Hancock]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 106\u2013107</ref>\n\nDuring the difficult economic times of the [[Panic of 1873]], the major ideological divide in the Democratic Party concerned the issue of [[History of monetary policy in the United States|currency]]. Many \"soft money\" Democrats wanted Congress to repeal the [[Specie Payment Resumption Act]] and authorize the printing of more [[greenback (money)|greenback]]s, [[banknotes]] that had first been printed during the Civil War. The printing of more greenbacks would result in [[inflation]] and potentially benefit farmers by raising prices and helping them pay down their debts. Like most Republicans and \"hard money\" members of the conservative business establishment, Tilden believed that the termination of greenback circulation (which would return the country to the [[gold standard]]) was the best way to solve the ongoing economic crisis. Tilden's lieutenants at the Democratic National Convention emphasized Tilden's reform credentials above all else, but they also ensured that the party platform endorsed Tilden's hard money views.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 108\u2013109, 112\u2013114</ref> \n\nTilden won a majority of the votes cast on the first presidential ballot of the convention, but fell short of the two-thirds majority required to win the Democratic presidential nomination. His closest rival was Hendricks, who had the support of New York party boss [[John Kelly (New York politician)|John Kelly]] and the soft money faction of Democrats. Tilden won the necessary two-thirds majority on the second presidential ballot, and the convention then voted to make his nomination unanimous. Delegates unanimously chose Hendricks as Tilden's running mate, providing a balance between the hard money and soft money factions.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 115\u2013117</ref> Though the Republicans had nominated a ticket led by [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] of Ohio, another governor who had established a reputation for honest governance, Tilden was widely regarded as the favorite in the general election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 80\u201383, 122</ref>\n\n===General election===\n[[File:1876 U.S. presidential election, contested states.png|thumb|upright=1.5|In the aftermath of the [[1876 United States presidential election|1876 presidential election]], the electoral votes of four states were disputed.]]\n\nPer tradition, both Tilden and Hayes avoided publicly campaigning for president, leaving that task to their supporters; Tilden appointed [[Abram Hewitt]] to lead his campaign.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 123, 131\u2013132</ref> The Republican campaign established a major cash advantage, partly because Tilden refused to contribute much of his personal fortune to the campaign.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 121</ref> The Democrats campaigned on the theme of \"retrenchment and reform\" and attacked the \"corrupt centralism\" of the Grant administration.<ref name=\"morris118120\"/> Tilden blamed high taxes and the Grant administration for the economic downturn, and, like Hayes, promised [[U.S. Civil Service Reform|civil service reform]] and hard money policies.<ref>White (2017), pp. 328\u2013330</ref> Republicans, meanwhile, focused on their party's identification with Lincoln and the Union cause in the Civil War; many Republicans still associated the Democratic Party with slavery and disunion.<ref name=\"morris118120\">Morris (2003), pp. 118\u2013120</ref> Rebutting Republican charges, Tilden categorically denied that he had any intention of compensating the South for any slaves emancipated or losses suffered during the Civil War.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 161\u2013162</ref> For their part, many Democrats cared little for Tilden's emphasis on reform, and were instead focused on ending sixteen years of Republican leadership. Southern Democrats especially hoped to end [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] and gain control of South Carolina, Florida, and Louisiana, the last three \"[[Redeemers|unredeemed]]\" Southern states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 125\u2013126, 146</ref> Southern whites, who overwhelmingly favored Tilden, used violence and intimidation to suppress the turnout of Republican-leaning [[African-American]] voters.<ref>White (2017), pp. 330\u2013331</ref> Tilden worked to distance himself from violent encounters like the [[Hamburg massacre]], in which disgruntled Southern whites clashed with the Republican-led government of South Carolina.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 129\u2013131</ref>\n\nBoth campaigns considered New York, Ohio, and Indiana to be the key [[swing states]], but the campaigns also focused on several smaller states, including the three unredeemed Southern states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 155\u2013156</ref> Ultimately, Hayes swept the West and won much of the North, but Tilden carried the closely contested Northern states of New York, New Jersey, Indiana, and Connecticut, swept the [[border states (American Civil War)|border states]], and carried most of the South. He had won a majority of the popular vote and tallied clear victories in seventeen states, leaving him one [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral vote]] short of a majority. On November 6, the day after election day, most major newspapers reported that Tilden had won the election; however, Hayes still had a narrow path to victory if he could sweep the electoral votes of Florida, South Carolina, and Louisiana.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 164\u2013166</ref> Hayes refused to formally concede, but told members of the press that he was \"of the opinion that the Democrats have carried the country and elected Tilden.\"<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 167\u2013171</ref> Tilden, meanwhile, urged his alarmed followers, many of whom believed that the Republicans were attempting to steal the election, to remain calm and refrain from violence. Both parties feared the possibility that a dispute over the election would lead to armed conflict; Tilden discussed appointing General [[George B. McClellan]] as his military assistant, while President Grant ordered army and naval units to reinforce Washington.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 172\u2013174</ref>\n\n===Post-election controversy===\n[[Image:SJTilden of NY.jpg|thumb|right|Samuel Jones Tilden]]\n\nWith the election in doubt, each party sent some of their most prominent leaders to monitor the election process in the three disputed Southern states. Initial election returns showed that Hayes had carried South Carolina by several hundred votes, but that Tilden had won Florida by 91 votes and Louisiana by over 6000 votes. Republicans controlled the bodies charged with determining the validity of election results in all three states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 174\u2013178</ref> On November 22, the South Carolina canvassing board adjourned after declaring that Hayes had won the state's electoral votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 180\u2013182</ref> On December 4, the Louisiana canvassing board announced that it had thrown out 15,623 votes due to \"systemic intimidation,\" leaving Hayes as the winner of all of the state's electoral votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 191\u2013192</ref> Early on the morning of December 6, the day the Electoral College was scheduled to convene, the Florida canvassing board announced that Hayes had won the state by a margin of 924 votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 193\u2013197</ref> Democrats challenged the results in all three contested Southern states. Meanwhile, another controversy had arisen in Oregon, where a Hayes elector, John Watts, resigned because his simultaneous service as a presidential elector and as a low-ranking official in the [[United States Post Office Department|Post Office]] violated the [[United States Constitution]]. After Watts resigned, the state's Democratic governor appointed an elector to fill the vacancy, while, separately, the state's two remaining Hayes electors chose a third elector to fill the vacancy caused by Watts's resignation.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 183\u2013185, 197\u2013198</ref>\n\nOn December 6, the members of the Electoral College met in Washington, D.C., but the disputes in four states prevented a conclusive vote for president.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 197\u2013198</ref> With the Electoral College unable to select a president, the disputed election became an issue for Congress to settle; Republicans controlled the Senate, while Democrats controlled the House. The vague wording of the Constitution gave rise to further controversy, as Republicans held that [[Thomas W. Ferry]], a Republican senator from Michigan and the [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|president pro tempore]] of the [[United States Senate]], could determine the validity of the disputed electoral votes. Democrats argued that Ferry could only count the votes that were not disputed; in such a scenario, neither candidate would have an electoral vote majority, necessitating a [[contingent election]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]]. Since Democrats controlled a majority of the state delegations in the House, they would be able to elect Tilden as president in a contingent election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 200\u2013201</ref> In response to the controversy, Tilden compiled his own study of electoral procedures in the previous 22 presidential elections. He delivered the study to every sitting member of Congress, but congressional Republicans were not swayed by Tilden's argument that history supported the Democratic position on the election returns.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 203\u2013204</ref> He continued to call for calm, and rejected Abram Hewitt's suggestion that he ask his supporters to engage in mass public demonstrations.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 206\u2013207, 214</ref>\n\n===Electoral Commission===\n[[File:President Rutherford Hayes 1870 - 1880 Restored.jpg|thumb|upright=1|[[Rutherford B. Hayes]] defeated Tilden in the 1876 election.]]\n\nOn January 26, both houses of Congress agreed to establish the 15-member [[Electoral Commission (United States)|Electoral Commission]] to settle the dispute over the contested electoral votes. The commission consisted of five Democratic members of Congress, five Republican members of Congress, and five justices of the [[Supreme Court of the United States]]. Of the Supreme Court justices, two were to be Democrats, two were to be Republicans, and the fifth justice would be selected by the other four justices. Tilden opposed the creation of the Electoral Commission because he still hoped to force a contingent election in the House of Representatives, but he was unable to prevent Democratic congressmen from voting for the establishment of the commission. Most had expected that the fifth justice on the commission would be Associate Justice [[David Davis (Supreme Court justice)|David Davis]], a [[political independent]], but Davis refused to serve on the commission after he accepted election to the Senate. Another associate justice, Republican [[Joseph P. Bradley]], was instead chosen as the fifth justice on the Electoral Commission.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 216\u2013219</ref> In a series of 8-to-7, party-line decisions, the Electoral Commission voted to award all of the contested electoral votes to Hayes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 222\u2013235</ref>\n\nEven after the Electoral Commission delivered its rulings, the House of Representatives could have blocked the inauguration of Hayes by refusing to certify the election results.<ref>White (2017), p. 332</ref> Though some House Democrats hoped to do just that, they were unable to prevent the House of Representatives from blocking certification, as many House Democrats joined with their Republican colleagues in accepting the results.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 235\u2013236</ref> During the proceedings of the Electoral Commission, high-ranking members of both parties had discussed the possibility of declaring Hayes the winner in exchange for the removal of all federal troops from the South. The [[Compromise of 1877]], as it became known, may have played a role in preventing the House from challenging the Electoral Commission's rulings, although author Roy Morris, Jr. argues that the compromise \"was more a mutual concession of the obvious than a device for controlling larger events.\"<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 232\u2013234</ref> Some other historians, including [[C. Vann Woodward]], have argued that the Compromise of 1877 played the decisive role in determining the outcome of the election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kleinfeld |first1=N. R. |title=COUNTING THE VOTE: THE HISTORY; President Tilden? No, but Almost, in Another Vote That Dragged On |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/us/counting-vote-history-president-tilden-no-but-almost-another-vote-that-dragged.html |accessdate=6 November 2018 |newspaper=New York Times |date=12 November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Review: NOT A COMPROMISE |journal=The Review of Politics |date=2009 |volume=71 |issue=4 |pages=698\u2013700 |jstor=25655882}}</ref> On March 2, two days before the end of Grant's term, Congress declared Hayes the victor of the 1876 presidential election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 237\u2013238</ref> Hayes took office on March 4, and withdrew the last federal soldiers from the South in April 1877, bringing an end to the Reconstruction Era.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 240, 244\u2013245</ref>\n\nSome Democrats urged Tilden to reject the results and take the presidential [[oath of office]], but Tilden declined to do so. On March 3, the House passed a resolution declaring Tilden the \"duly elected President of the United States,\" but this had no legal effect.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 241\u2013242</ref> Tilden himself stated that, \"I can retire to private life with the consciousness that I shall receive from posterity the credit of having been elected to the highest position in the gift of the people, without any of the cares and responsibilities of the office.\"{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} Tilden was the second individual, after [[Andrew Jackson]], to [[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|lose a presidential election despite winning at least a plurality of the popular vote]]. [[Grover Cleveland]], [[Al Gore]], and [[Hillary Clinton]] have subsequently achieved the same feat.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Revesz |first1=Rachel |title=Five presidential nominees who won popular vote but lost the election |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/popular-vote-electoral-college-five-presidential-nominees-hillary-clinton-al-gore-a7420971.html |accessdate=6 November 2018 |newspaper=The Independent |date=16 November 2016}}</ref> Tilden remains the only individual to lose a presidential election while winning a majority, rather than a plurality, of the popular vote.\n\n==Later life==\n===Potter Committee===\n[[Image:STilden.JPG|thumb|right|upright|Samuel Tilden]]\n\nIn 1878, Democratic Congressman [[Clarkson Nott Potter]] convinced the House of Representatives to create a committee to investigate allegations of fraud and corruption in the 1876 election. Potter was appointed as the head of the commission, which Democrats hoped would implicate Hayes and damage the Republican Party in the next presidential election.<ref>Guenther (1983), 284\u2013285</ref> Rather than produce conclusive evidence of Republican malfeasance, the committee uncovered conflicting evidence that reflected poorly on election and campaign officials of both parties. For ten months beginning in May 1878, the Potter Committee subpoenaed all telegrams sent by political operatives during the election dispute. 29,275 telegrams had been sent, but all save 641 had been routinely destroyed by [[Western Union]]. The remaining telegrams were in cipher, as was common with business and political communication in the telegraph era. ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' editor [[Whitelaw Reid]] obtained and deciphered many of the telegrams and, in October 1878, he published the story of the Democratic efforts to sway election officials through bribery and other means. The revelation of the bribery attempts undercut the Democratic Party's argument that Tilden had been cheated out of the presidency.<ref>Kahn (1996), pp. 221\u2013229</ref> Tilden was not implicated in any wrongdoing, but the investigation into the Cipher Telegrams damaged his national standing.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 250\u2013251</ref>\n\n===Election of 1880===\n\nAfter the controversy over the election of 1876, Tilden became the presumptive Democratic candidate in [[1880 United States presidential election|1880 presidential election]]. He declined to run for another term as governor in 1879, focusing instead on building support for the 1880 presidential nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), p. 52</ref> The revelations of the Potter Committee, along with Tilden's persistent health issues, both damaged Tilden's national standing, but his superior political organization and personal fortune ensured that he remained a serious contender for the Democratic nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 56\u201357</ref> Tilden's standing with the party slipped further following the Republican victory in the [[New York state election, 1879|New York gubernatorial election in 1879]]. In that election, a revitalized Tammany Hall organization split from the regular Democratic party in a patronage dispute with Tilden's faction.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 61\u201363</ref> In the months before the [[1880 Democratic National Convention]], rumors about Tilden's intentions circulated wildly, but Tilden refused to definitively state whether or not he would seek the Democratic nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 74\u201375</ref>\n\nAs the New York delegation left for the national convention in Cincinnati, Tilden gave a letter to one of his chief supporters, [[Daniel Manning]], suggesting that his health might force him to decline the nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 122\u2013123</ref> Tilden hoped to be nominated, but only if he was the unanimous choice of the convention; if not, Manning was entrusted to make the contents of Tilden's letter available to the New York delegation.<ref name=\"Goldman\">{{cite book |last=Goldman |first=Andrew |date=2015 |orig-year=1990 |title=The National Party Chairmen and Committees |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e0agDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT107 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Routledge |page=107 |isbn=978-1-3154-9067-0}}</ref> The New York delegation interpreted the letter as a notice of withdrawal, and the delegates began looking for a new candidate, eventually settling on Speaker of the House [[Samuel J. Randall]].<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 124\u2013126, 139</ref> Ultimately, the party nominated [[Winfield Scott Hancock]], who lost the election to [[James A Garfield]].<ref name=\"Goldman\"/>{{rp|108-109}} Though many Democrats favored Tilden for the party's nomination in the [[1884 United States presidential election|1884 presidential election]], Tilden once again declined to run due to poor health.<ref name=\"Goldman\"/>{{rp|110}} He endorsed New York Governor [[Grover Cleveland]], who won the Democratic nomination and went on to defeat [[James G. Blaine]] in the general election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 255\u2013256</ref>\n\n===Retirement and death===\n[[File:Tilden 112 cu jeh.jpg|thumb|Statue in New York City]]\n\nTilden retired in the early 1880s, living as a near-recluse at his {{convert|110|acre|km2|adj=on}} estate, Greystone, in [[Yonkers, New York|Yonkers]], New York. He died a [[bachelor]] at Greystone on August 4, 1886. He is buried at Cemetery of the Evergreens in [[New Lebanon, New York|New Lebanon]], [[Columbia County, New York]].<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101677|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument|date=December 2005|accessdate=July 3, 2010 |author=Kristin Gibbons and William E. Krattinger|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}}</ref> In reference to the 1876 election, Tilden's gravestone bears the words, \"I Still Trust The People\".<ref>Morris (2003), p. 256</ref>\n\nOf his fortune, estimated at $7&nbsp;million (over $190&nbsp;million in 2016), $4&nbsp;million (over $108&nbsp;million in 2016) was bequeathed for the establishment and maintenance of a free public library and reading-room in the City of New York; but, as the [[Will of Samuel J. Tilden|will]] was successfully contested by relatives, only about $3&nbsp;million (over $81&nbsp;million in 2014) was applied to its original purpose. In 1895, the [[Tilden Trust]] was combined with the [[Astor Library|Astor]] and [[Lenox Library (New York City)|Lenox]] libraries to found the [[New York Public Library]], and the building bears his name on its front.<ref>New York Public Library, [https://www.nypl.org/about/locations/schwarzman \"About the Stephen A. Schwarzman Building\"]; and ''Vol 1, New York City Guide'' (NY: Best Books, 1939), 328-30. {{ISBN|1623760550}}, 9781623760557</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nThe [[Samuel J. Tilden House]] at 15 [[Gramercy Park]] South, which he owned from 1860 until his death, is now used by the [[National Arts Club]]. Tilden's Graystone property is now known as [[Untermyer Park]]; it was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1974.<ref name=\"nris\"/> Several places have been named for Tilden, including [[Tilden, Wisconsin]],<ref>{{cite web| title=Home Page| url=http://www.townoftilden.com/| publisher=Town of Tilden| accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> [[Tilden, Nebraska]], [[Tilden, Texas]], [[Tilden Township, Berks County, Pennsylvania|Tilden Township]], Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web| title=History| url=http://www.tildentownship.com/history.html| publisher=Tilden Township| accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> and [[Tilden, Illinois]]. The [[Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument]] was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2006.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> Other things named for Tilden include [[Samuel J. Tilden High School]], [[Fort Tilden]], and the [[Root-Tilden Scholarship|Root-Tilden-Kern Scholarship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.nyu.edu/financialaid/jdscholarships/rootscholarship |title=Root-Tilden-Kern Public Interest Scholarships |last=NYU Law School Public Interest Law Center |date=2017 |website=NYU Law School Financial Aid |publisher=New York University Law School |location=New York, NY |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Secondary sources===\n\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|authorlink1=Thomas J. Archdeacon |last1=Archdeacon |first1=Thomas J. |title=The Erie Canal Ring, Samuel J. Tilden, and the Democratic Party |journal=New York History |date=1978 |volume=59 |issue=4 |pages=408\u2013429 |jstor=23170015}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bigelow |first1=John |editor1-last=Oldaker |editor1-first=Nikki |title=The Life of Samuel J. Tilden |date=2009 |publisher=Show Biz East Productions |isbn=978-0978669812 |edition=Revised|orig-year=1895}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Clancy\n  | first = Herbert J.\n  | year = 1958\n  | title = The Presidential Election of 1880\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/presidentialelec0000clan\n  | url-access = registration\n  | publisher = Loyola University Press\n  | isbn = 978-1-258-19190-0\n  }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Earle |first1=Jonathan Halperin |title=Jacksonian Antislavery and the Politics of Free Soil, 1824-1854 |date=2004 |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |isbn=9780807855553}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Flick |first1=Alexander C. |title=Samuel J. Tilden: A Study in Political Sagacity |date=1939 |publisher=Kennikat Press |OCLC=673301}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Guenther |first1=Karen |title=Potter Committee Investigation of the Disputed Election of 1876 |journal=The Florida Historical Quarterly |date=1983 |volume=61 |issue=3 |pages=281\u2013295 |jstor=30149125}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Hirsch |first1=Mark D. |title=Samuel J. Tilden: The Story of a Lost Opportunity |journal=The American Historical Review |date=1951 |volume=56 |issue=4 |pages=788\u2013802 |doi=10.2307/1851984 |jstor=1851984}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Holt |first1=Michael F. |title=By One Vote: The Disputed Presidential Election of 1876 |date=2008 |publisher=University Press of Kansas |isbn=9780700616084}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Kahn |first1=David |title=The Codebreakers: The Comprehensive History of Secret Communication from Ancient Times to the Internet |date=1996 |publisher=Scribner| edition=Revised|isbn=978-0684831305}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Kelley |first1=Robert |title=The Thought and Character of Samuel J. Tilden: The Democrat As Inheritor |journal=The Historian |date=1964 |volume=26 |issue=2 |pages=176-205 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-6563.1