al tickets|nominee]] for [[President of the United States]]|years=[[1876 United States presidential election|1876]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Winfield Scott Hancock]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Adams Dix]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]]|years=1875\u20131876}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lucius Robinson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Unsuccessful major party pres candidates}}\n{{USDemPresNominees}}\n{{Governors of New York}}\n{{New York State Democratic Committee}}\n{{United States presidential election, 1876}}\n{{United States presidential election, 1880}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tilden, Samuel J.}}\n[[Category:1814 births]]\n[[Category:1886 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Governors of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Free Soilers]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People from New Lebanon, New York]]\n[[Category:Tylden family]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1876 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Gramercy Park]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_J._Tilden"}
{"title_page": "Zim (software)", "text_new": "{{prose|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Zim\n| logo = [[File:Zim globe.svg|64px|Zim desktop wiki editor logo]]\n| screenshot = Zim-screenshot.png\n| caption = Zim (version 0.54) Screenshot of the editor window with some arbitrary text\n| developer = Jaap Karssenberg\n| latest release version = 0.72.1\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|01|01}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://github.com/zim-desktop-wiki/zim-desktop-wiki/releases|title=Releases \u2013 zim-desktop-wiki/zim-desktop-wiki\n|accessdate=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n| repo = https://github.com/zim-desktop-wiki/zim-desktop-wiki\n| discontinued = no\n| programming language = [[Python (programming language)|Python]]\n| operating system = [[Cross-platform]]\n| platform = [[Python (programming language)|Python]], [[GTK+]]\n| genre = [[Notetaking]] application, [[Personal wiki]]\n| license = [[GNU General Public License|GNU GPL]]\n| website = {{URL|zim-wiki.org}}\n}}\n{{also|ZIM (file format)}}\n'''Zim''' is  a graphical [[text editor]] designed to maintain a collection of locally stored [[wiki]]-pages, a personal wiki.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/precise/en/man1/zim.1.html |title=Ubuntu Manpage: zim - A Desktop Wiki Editor |publisher=Manpages.ubuntu.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kashyap |first=Varun |url=http://www.makeuseof.com/tag/zim-a-desktop-wiki-note-taking-app-linux-windows/ |title=ZIM \u2013 A Desktop Wiki / Note Taking App [Linux, Windows&#93; |publisher=Makeuseof.com |date=2008-10-25 |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technewsworld.com/story/70869.html |title=Technology News: Reviews: Zim Desktop Brings Wiki Wizardry to Note Taking |publisher=Technewsworld.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://linuxandfriends.com/2009/08/03/note-taking-free-microsoft-onenote-alternatives-for-linux/ |title=Note Taking Software for Linux |publisher=Linux And Friends |date=2009-08-03 |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref> Each wiki-page can contain things like text with [[Lightweight markup language|simple formatting]], links to other pages, attachments, and images. Additional [[Plug-in (computing)|plugins]], such as an equation editor and spell-checker, are also available. The wiki-pages are stored in a folder structure in plain text files with [[wiki markup|wiki formatting]].\n\n''Zim'' is written in [[Python (programming language)|Python]] using [[GTK+]] libraries. It is [[free software]] licensed under the [[GNU General Public License]] (GPL).\n\n==Features==\nFeatures include:\n* Text is written in lightweight text mark-up (hybrid [[DokuWiki]]/[[Markdown]]). Text input has inline preview system similar to [[VisualEditor]]. Writing mark-up text in certain way gets it converted instantly into \"rich text\". These include things like headers and lists, tables, diagrams.\n* Multimedia content: images, files attachment, calendar\n* Links to other pages\n* Multi-documents tabs\n* Application does auto-saving per character. Also cursor position is saved for every note.\n* [[Revision control]] system ([[GNU Bazaar]], [[Git]], [[Mercurial]], [[Fossil (software)|Fossil]])\n* Tagging system\n* Tasks/Todo list system\n* Export single or compilation of the notes into [[HTML]], slideshow, [[Markdown]] or [[reStructuredText]]\n* Support for [[Getting Things Done]] method<ref name=\"Karssenberg\">{{Cite web\n| title = Zim - a desktop wiki - Getting Things Done\n| author = Jaap Karssenberg\n| work = zim-wiki.org\n| date = \n| accessdate = 2015-05-01\n| url = http://zim-wiki.org/manual/Usage/Getting_Things_Done.html\n| language =  \n| quote = \n}}</ref>\n\n===Plugins===\n''Zim'' can be extended with [[Plug-in (computing)|plugins]]. These include:\n* Equations (using [[LaTeX]] and [[dvipng]])\n* Plots (using [[GNU R]] or [[Gnuplot]])\n* Spell checking (using gtkspell)\n* Diagrams (using [[Graphviz]])\n* Table of Content navigation\n* [[Zeitgeist (free software)|GNOME's Zeitgeist]] integration\n* [[Lilypond]] note sheet integration\n*Integration plugins for reference managers ([[Zotero]] and [[Mendeley]])\n\n==Availability==\nSeveral [[Linux]] [[Linux distribution|distributions]] include ''Zim'' in their repositories (as of 2011), in particular [[Debian]], [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]], [[Arch Linux]] and [[Fedora (operating system)|Fedora]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Debian Webmaster, webmaster@debian.org |url=http://packages.debian.org/sid/zim |title=Debian - Details of package zim in sid |publisher=Packages.debian.org |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://launchpad.net/ubuntu/oneiric/+package/zim |title=zim : Oneiric (11.10) : Ubuntu |publisher=Launchpad.net |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archlinux.org/packages/community/any/zim/ |title=zim 0.56-1 (any) |publisher=Arch Linux |date=2012-04-03 |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://admin.fedoraproject.org/pkgdb/acls/name/Zim |title=Fedora Package Database - Zim |publisher=Admin.fedoraproject.org |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref> Also [[FreeBSD]], [[OpenBSD]] and [[OpenSUSE]]{{citation needed|date=October 2018|reason=Does OpenSUSE, being a Linux distribution and not BSD, has ports collection? If so it should also be linked as done with (the preceding) FreeBSD and OpenBSD.}} include ''Zim'' in their [[Freebsd#Ports Collection|ports collections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freshports.org/editors/zim |title=editors/zim |publisher=FreshPorts |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/cvsweb/ports/productivity/zim/ |title=ports/productivity/zim/ |publisher=Openbsd.org |date= |accessdate=2012-08-01}}</ref>\n\nThe core features of ''Zim'' depend on ''python'', ''gtk'' and ''python-gtk'' modules and thus ''Zim'' can be easily ported to any platform where these modules are available. In particular, ''Zim'' has been ported to the Microsoft Windows operating system and works very well with a native feel. It has also been ported to Mac OS, but as of 2015 there were still a few issues, primarily being no native UI integration and the procedure to install being involving<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reagle.org/joseph/zwiki/Archives/2015/Zim_on_Mac_OSX.html|title=Zim on Mac OSX|website=reagle.org|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zim-wiki.org/install.html|title=Zim - a desktop wiki|website=zim-wiki.org|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>. There were attempts and plans to port to [[Android (operating system)|Android]].{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tomboy (software)]]\n* [[Personal wiki]]\n* [[List of wiki software]]\n* [[Comparison of wiki software]]\n* [[Comparison of notetaking software]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Zim (software)|Zim}}\n* {{Official website|zim-wiki.org}}\n\n{{Wiki software|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Note-taking software]]\n[[Category:Free note-taking software]]\n[[Category:Personal wikis]]\n[[Category:Free wiki software]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in Python]]\n", "text_old": "{{prose|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Zim\n| logo = [[File:Zim globe.svg|64px|Zim desktop wiki editor logo]]\n| screenshot = Zim-screenshot.png\n| caption = Zim (version 0.54) Screenshot of the editor window with some arbitrary text\n| developer = Jaap Karssenberg\n| latest release version = 0.71.1\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|05|23}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://github.com/zim-desktop-wiki/zim-desktop-wiki/releases|title=Releases \u2013 zim-desktop-wiki/zim-desktop-wiki\n|accessdate=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n| repo = https://github.com/zim-desktop-wiki/zim-desktop-wiki\n| discontinued = no\n| programming language = [[Python (programming language)|Python]]\n| operating system = [[Cross-platform]]\n| platform = [[Python (programming language)|Python]], [[GTK+]]\n| genre = [[Notetaking]] application, [[Personal wiki]]\n| license = [[GNU General Public License|GNU GPL]]\n| website = {{URL|zim-wiki.org}}\n}}\n{{also|ZIM (file format)}}\n'''Zim''' is  a graphical [[text editor]] designed to maintain a collection of locally stored [[wiki]]-pages, a personal wiki.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/precise/en/man1/zim.1.html |title=Ubuntu Manpage: zim - A Desktop Wiki Editor |publisher=Manpages.ubuntu.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kashyap |first=Varun |url=http://www.makeuseof.com/tag/zim-a-desktop-wiki-note-taking-app-linux-windows/ |title=ZIM \u2013 A Desktop Wiki / Note Taking App [Linux, Windows&#93; |publisher=Makeuseof.com |date=2008-10-25 |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technewsworld.com/story/70869.html |title=Technology News: Reviews: Zim Desktop Brings Wiki Wizardry to Note Taking |publisher=Technewsworld.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://linuxandfriends.com/2009/08/03/note-taking-free-microsoft-onenote-alternatives-for-linux/ |title=Note Taking Software for Linux |publisher=Linux And Friends |date=2009-08-03 |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref> Each wiki-page can contain things like text with [[Lightweight markup language|simple formatting]], links to other pages, attachments, and images. Additional [[Plug-in (computing)|plugins]], such as an equation editor and spell-checker, are also available. The wiki-pages are stored in a folder structure in plain text files with [[wiki markup|wiki formatting]].\n\n''Zim'' is written in [[Python (programming language)|Python]] using [[GTK+]] libraries. It is [[free software]] licensed under the [[GNU General Public License]] (GPL).\n\n==Features==\nFeatures include:\n* Text is written in lightweight text mark-up (hybrid [[DokuWiki]]/[[Markdown]]). Text input has inline preview system similar to [[VisualEditor]]. Writing mark-up text in certain way gets it converted instantly into \"rich text\". These include things like headers and lists, tables, diagrams.\n* Multimedia content: images, files attachment, calendar\n* Links to other pages\n* Multi-documents tabs\n* Application does auto-saving per character. Also cursor position is saved for every note.\n* [[Revision control]] system ([[GNU Bazaar]], [[Git]], [[Mercurial]], [[Fossil (software)|Fossil]])\n* Tagging system\n* Tasks/Todo list system\n* Export single or compilation of the notes into [[HTML]], slideshow, [[Markdown]] or [[reStructuredText]]\n* Support for [[Getting Things Done]] method<ref name=\"Karssenberg\">{{Cite web\n| title = Zim - a desktop wiki - Getting Things Done\n| author = Jaap Karssenberg\n| work = zim-wiki.org\n| date = \n| accessdate = 2015-05-01\n| url = http://zim-wiki.org/manual/Usage/Getting_Things_Done.html\n| language =  \n| quote = \n}}</ref>\n\n===Plugins===\n''Zim'' can be extended with [[Plug-in (computing)|plugins]]. These include:\n* Equations (using [[LaTeX]] and [[dvipng]])\n* Plots (using [[GNU R]] or [[Gnuplot]])\n* Spell checking (using gtkspell)\n* Diagrams (using [[Graphviz]])\n* Table of Content navigation\n* [[Zeitgeist (free software)|GNOME's Zeitgeist]] integration\n* [[Lilypond]] note sheet integration\n*Integration plugins for reference managers ([[Zotero]] and [[Mendeley]])\n\n==Availability==\nSeveral [[Linux]] [[Linux distribution|distributions]] include ''Zim'' in their repositories (as of 2011), in particular [[Debian]], [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]], [[Arch Linux]] and [[Fedora (operating system)|Fedora]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Debian Webmaster, webmaster@debian.org |url=http://packages.debian.org/sid/zim |title=Debian - Details of package zim in sid |publisher=Packages.debian.org |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://launchpad.net/ubuntu/oneiric/+package/zim |title=zim : Oneiric (11.10) : Ubuntu |publisher=Launchpad.net |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archlinux.org/packages/community/any/zim/ |title=zim 0.56-1 (any) |publisher=Arch Linux |date=2012-04-03 |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://admin.fedoraproject.org/pkgdb/acls/name/Zim |title=Fedora Package Database - Zim |publisher=Admin.fedoraproject.org |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref> Also [[FreeBSD]], [[OpenBSD]] and [[OpenSUSE]]{{citation needed|date=October 2018|reason=Does OpenSUSE, being a Linux distribution and not BSD, has ports collection? If so it should also be linked as done with (the preceding) FreeBSD and OpenBSD.}} include ''Zim'' in their [[Freebsd#Ports Collection|ports collections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freshports.org/editors/zim |title=editors/zim |publisher=FreshPorts |date= |accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/cvsweb/ports/productivity/zim/ |title=ports/productivity/zim/ |publisher=Openbsd.org |date= |accessdate=2012-08-01}}</ref>\n\nThe core features of ''Zim'' depend on ''python'', ''gtk'' and ''python-gtk'' modules and thus ''Zim'' can be easily ported to any platform where these modules are available. In particular, ''Zim'' has been ported to the Microsoft Windows operating system and works very well with a native feel. It has also been ported to Mac OS, but as of 2015 there were still a few issues, primarily being no native UI integration and the procedure to install being involving<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reagle.org/joseph/zwiki/Archives/2015/Zim_on_Mac_OSX.html|title=Zim on Mac OSX|website=reagle.org|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zim-wiki.org/install.html|title=Zim - a desktop wiki|website=zim-wiki.org|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>. There were attempts and plans to port to [[Android (operating system)|Android]].{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tomboy (software)]]\n* [[Personal wiki]]\n* [[List of wiki software]]\n* [[Comparison of wiki software]]\n* [[Comparison of notetaking software]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Zim (software)|Zim}}\n* {{Official website|zim-wiki.org}}\n\n{{Wiki software|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Note-taking software]]\n[[Category:Free note-taking software]]\n[[Category:Personal wikis]]\n[[Category:Free wiki software]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in Python]]\n", "name_user": "Py4w", "label": "safe", "comment": "0.72.1", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zim_(software)"}
{"title_page": "Mark Stimson", "text_new": "{{for|Australian rugby league player|Mark Stimson (rugby league)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mark Stimson\n| image = Mark Stimson.JPG\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Mark Stimson\n| fullname = Mark Nicholas Stimson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1967|12|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Plaistow, Newham|Plaistow]], England\n| currentclub = [[Hornchurch F.C.|Hornchurch]] (manager)\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthclubs1 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]\n| youthclubs2 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| youthyears1 = {{0|000}}?\u20131984\n| youthyears2 = 1984\u20131985\n| years1 = 1985\u20131989\n| years2 = 1988\n| years3 = 1989\n| years4 = 1989\u20131993\n| years5 = 1992\n| years6 = 1993\u20131996\n| years7 = 1995\n| years8 = 1996\u20131999\n| years9 = 1999\n| years10 = 1999\u20132002\n| years11 = 2002\u20132004\n| years12 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs1 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] (loan)\n| clubs4 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] (loan)\n| clubs6 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]\n| clubs9 = [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]]\n| clubs10 = [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]]\n| clubs11 = [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]]\n| clubs12 = [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]]\n| caps1 = 2\n| goals1 = 0\n| caps2 = 10\n| goals2 = 0\n| caps3 = 18\n| goals3 = 0\n| caps4 = 86\n| goals4 = 2\n| caps5 = 4\n| goals5 = 0\n| caps6 = 58\n| goals6 = 2\n| caps7 = 5\n| goals7 = 0\n| caps8 = 57\n| goals8 = 0\n| caps9 = 2\n| goals9 = 0\n| caps10 = ?\n| goals10 = ?\n| caps11 = ?\n| goals11 = ?\n| caps12 = 0\n| goals12 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2002\u20132006\n| manageryears2 = 2006\u20132007\n| manageryears3 = 2007\u20132010\n| manageryears4 = 2010\u20132011\n| manageryears5 = 2011\u20132012\n| manageryears6 = 2012\u20132018\n| manageryears7 = 2018\n| manageryears8 = 2018\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]]\n| managerclubs2 = [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n| managerclubs4 = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n| managerclubs5 = [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]\n| managerclubs6 = [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]]\n| managerclubs7 = [[Waltham Abbey F.C.|Waltham Abbey]]\n| managerclubs8 = [[Hornchurch F.C.|Hornchurch]]\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\n| nationalteam1 = [[England C national football team|England National Game XI]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Mark Nicholas Stimson''' (born 27 December 1967)<ref>{{cite book | first=Roger|last= Triggs | title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club| publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd | year=2001| isbn=978-0-7524-2243-5|pages=307}}</ref> is an English former [[association football|footballer]] and is currently [[manager (association football)|manager]] of [[Hornchurch F.C.|Hornchurch]]. He signed his first professional contract with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in 1985, but was unable to gain a regular place in the team. In 1989, he moved on to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], where he made over 80 appearances in [[the Football League]]. He later played for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] and [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] before dropping into [[non-League football]].\n\nHe was appointed manager of [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]] in 2002 and remained in charge until 2006 when he took over as manager of [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]]. He led Grays to victory in the Final of the [[FA Trophy]] in 2005 and 2006, and repeated the feat with Stevenage in 2007. In November 2007, he became manager of a Football League team for the first time when he took over at one of his former clubs, [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], but he was unable to prevent the club's [[Promotion and relegation|relegation]] from [[Football League One|League One]] at the end of the [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]] season. He led Gillingham back into League One the following season via the [[2009 Football League Two play-off Final|League Two play-off Final]], but his contract was terminated after the team were relegated back to League Two the following season. On 1 June 2010, Stimson was appointed as the new manager of League Two club [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]], but he was sacked on New Year's Day 2011 with the club near the bottom of the table. He later had a spell as manager with Conference club [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Plaistow, Newham|Plaistow]] in east London, Stimson played for the [[Essex]] county representative football team and was on the books of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], before joining [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on an apprenticeship in July 1984. A year later, he signed his first professional contract, at the age of 17.<ref name=\"triggs\">{{cite book | first=Roger|last= Triggs | title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club|pages=308}}</ref> He made his [[the Football League|Football League]] debut against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in May 1987,<ref name=\"CI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canveyislandfc.co.uk/2000/squad.htm#Mark%20Stimson|title=2000\u201301 squad|publisher=Canvey Island F.C.|accessdate=1 September 2008}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> but struggled to gain a place in the first team, and was sent to [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] on loan in March 1988, where he played ten times.<ref name=\"SB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=7641|title=Mark Stimson|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=1 September 2008}}</ref> During the following season, he was loaned out again, this time to [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], whose manager, [[Keith Burkinshaw]], had worked with him at Tottenham. Stimson made 18 appearances for the [[Kent]]-based club and, although he was unable to help the team avoid [[Promotion and relegation|relegation]] from the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]], his contribution impressed the fans, who voted him into second place in the club's player of the year ballot.<ref name=\"triggs\" />\n\nAt the end of the [[1988\u201389 in English football|1988\u201389]] season, Stimson was transferred to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], then in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fchd.info/NEWCASTU.HTM|title=Newcastle United|accessdate=3 September 2008|publisher=The Football Club History Database}}</ref> for a fee of \u00a3200,000.<ref name=\"SB\" /> He spent four years with the club and finally gained a regular first team place, making over 80 appearances.<ref name=\"SB\" /> After [[Kevin Keegan]] took over as manager, however, Stimson found himself out of favour and he had a short spell on loan to [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in December 1992, which led to a \u00a3100,000 transfer at the end of that season.<ref name=\"triggs\" /><ref name=\"Sun2\">{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LSNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F934C29685AF044&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815|title=The Great career \u2013 Profile|newspaper=The Sun|accessdate=2 September 2008|date=9 January 1997}}</ref> He made over fifty appearances for Portsmouth but was also loaned out again, this time to [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] during the early part of the [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396]] season.<ref name=\"SB\" /> In March 1996, he was transferred to [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] for a fee of \u00a325,000.<ref name=\"SB\" /> His first season at the club was affected by a long lay-off due to injury,<ref name=\"Sun\">{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LSNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F9350C11D5406C4&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815|title=Foley: Time to get back to our Roots \u2013 Football|newspaper=The Sun|accessdate=2 September 2008|date=2 November 1996}}</ref> meaning that he did not play between August and November,<ref name=\"SB96\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=126&playerid=7641|title=Games played by Mark Stimson in 1996/1997|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref> but he ultimately made over 50 Football League appearances for the club.<ref name=\"SB\" /> During his time at [[Roots Hall]] the club suffered two consecutive relegations, dropping from the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] into the Second Division in 1997 and from there into the Third Division in 1998.<ref name=\"South\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fchd.info/SOUTHENU.HTM|title=Southend United|publisher=The Football Club History Database|accessdate=6 September 2008}}</ref> In March 1999, having not played for Southend since the previous November, he returned to former club Leyton Orient on a [[Free transfer (football)|free transfer]].<ref name=\"SB98\" /> He played for the club in the semi-finals of the [[Football League Two play-offs|play-offs]], but was restricted to an appearance as an unused substitute in the final, which Orient lost.<ref name=\"SB98\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=128&playerid=7641|title=Games played by Mark Stimson in 1998/1999|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"SB99\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=306797|title=League Two Play-Off \u2013 Final \u2013 KO 15:00|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the [[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000]] season, Stimson spent a short period on trial at another of his former clubs, Gillingham, but manager [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]] decided against offering him a contract and he instead joined [[Isthmian League]] club [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]].<ref name=\"triggs\" /> He helped the \"Gulls\" win the [[FA Trophy]] in the [[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301]] season, setting up the only goal and winning the man of the match award in Canvey's 1\u20130 defeat of [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] in the final.<ref name=\"triggs\" /><ref name=\"FG\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/canveys-class-takes-trophy-684653.html|title=Football: Canvey's class takes Trophy|newspaper=The Independent|date=14 May 2001|author=Rupert Metcalf|accessdate=1 September 2008}}</ref> He was also selected to play for the [[England C national football team|England National Game XI]], the national team for semi-professional players,<ref name=\"FA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/NationalGameXI/NewsAndFeatures/33657.htm|archive-url=https://archive.today/20050411002559/http://www.thefa.com/England/NationalGameXI/NewsAndFeatures/33657.htm|url-status=dead|archivedate=11 April 2005|title=Stimson proud to play for England|publisher=The Football Association|date=10 December 2002|accessdate=1 September 2008 }}</ref> earning one [[Cap (sport)|cap]] against an equivalent team from the United States.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Non-League Club Directory 2007|first=Mike|last=Williams|author2=Tony Williams|year=2007|publisher=Tony Williams Publications Ltd|id=1-8698-3355-4|page=860}}</ref> He left Canvey in May 2002 to join [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]] as player-coach.<ref name=\"GA\">{{Cite news|title=Grays in swoop for Gulls|newspaper=The Gazette|date=3 May 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nIn September 2002, Stimson took over as manager of Grays after the sacking of Craig Edwards, initially as [[caretaker manager]], but after leading the team to its first victory of the season, he was quickly given the job on an ongoing basis.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stimson brings in Polston |url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=6057 |publisher=Non-League Daily |date=17 September 2002 |accessdate=30 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921144420/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=6057 |archivedate=21 September 2012}}</ref> Despite the signing of a number of former top-level players, such as [[Carl Leaburn]] and [[Jason Dozzell]],<ref>{{cite web | title = About GAFC | url = http://graysathletic.co.uk/about/ | publisher = Grays Athletic F.C. | accessdate =3 September 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070925220910/http://www.graysathletic.co.uk/about/ |archivedate = 25 September 2007}}</ref> the team escaped relegation by only one point.<ref>{{cite web |title=Isthmian League 2002\u201303 |url=http://www.fchd.info/lghist/isthmian/isth2003.htm |publisher=The Football Club History Database |accessdate=3 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080930070015/http://www.fchd.info/lghist/isthmian/isth2003.htm |archivedate=30 September 2008}}</ref> The following season, however, boosted by a switch to full-time professional status and helped by the goals of [[Freddy Eastwood]], Grays finished in 6th place,<ref name=\"Gr\" /> sufficient to gain a place in the newly formed [[Conference South]] for the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]] season.<ref name=\"CS\" /> Grays won the Conference South at the first attempt by a margin of 23 points,<ref name=\"CS\">{{cite web |title = Football Conference 2004\u201305 |url = http://www.fchd.info/lghist/conf/conf2005.htm |publisher = The Football Club History Database |accessdate = 3 September 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080930064207/http://www.fchd.info/lghist/conf/conf2005.htm |archivedate = 30 September 2008 |df = dmy-all\n}}</ref> thus achieving promotion to the [[Conference National]], the top level of [[non-league football]], for the first time in their history.<ref name=\"Gr\">{{cite web | title = Grays Athletic | url = http://www.fchd.info/GRAYSA.HTM | publisher = The Football Club History Database | accessdate =3 September 2008}}</ref> In the same season, Stimson also led Grays to the FA Trophy Final, where the team beat [[Hucknall Town F.C.|Hucknall Town]] in a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]].<ref name=\"T1\">{{cite web | title = Grays Ath 1-1 Hucknall Town (aet) | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/4570825.stm | publisher = BBC|date=22 May 2005 | accessdate =21 September 2010}}</ref> Grays reached the FA Trophy Final again in the following season, and claimed a second successive win after a 2\u20130 victory over [[Woking F.C.|Woking]] at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]].<ref name=\"T2\">{{cite web | title = Stimson lauds Trophy win | url = http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFATrophy/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2006/05/FATrophy_Stimson.htm | publisher = The Football Association|date=15 May 2006|author=Tony Stevens | accessdate =3 September 2008}}</ref> In the Conference, Grays finished in third place and qualified for the play-offs for [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]] to [[the Football League]], but lost to [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] in the semi-finals.<ref name=\"T2\" />\n\nCiting his disappointment at failing to gain promotion, Stimson resigned from his post at Grays on 16 May 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shock as Stimson calls it a day |url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=35009 |publisher=Non-League Daily |date=16 May 2006 |accessdate=30 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921144434/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=35009 |archivedate=21 September 2012}}</ref> He stated that at the time he had received no firm job offers from other clubs, and acknowledged that he was taking a gamble with his career, but said that if he was unable to find a new job as a manager he would move into youth coaching or open his own football school.<ref>{{cite news | title = Stimmo: \"I'm gambling\"|author=Ryan Goad | url = http://www.thurrockgazette.co.uk/news/762284.stimmo_im_gambling/ | publisher = Thurrock Gazette | date = 16 May 2006 | accessdate =16 September 2008}}</ref> He was linked with the managerial vacancy at [[Football League Two|League Two]] [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Stimson for Posh? |url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=35072 |publisher=Non-League Daily |date=19 May 2006 |accessdate=30 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921144440/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=35072 |archivedate=21 September 2012}}</ref> but eventually took over as manager of [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]] on 28 May,<ref>{{cite news | title = Stevenage name Stimson as manager | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/5024698.stm | work = BBC Sport | date = 28 May 2006 | accessdate =3 September 2008}}</ref> and led the club to an eighth-place finish in the Conference National in his first season in charge.<ref>{{cite web | title = Stevenage Borough | url = http://www.fchd.info/STEVENAB.HTM | publisher = The Football Club History Database | accessdate =3 September 2008}}</ref> Stevenage also defeated Stimson's former club Grays to reach the FA Trophy final,<ref>{{cite web | title = Stevenage march into Final | url = http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFATrophy/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2007/03/Trophy_Stevenage.htm | publisher = The Football Association|author=James Andrew | date = 17 March 2007 | accessdate =2 September 2008}}</ref> and beat [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]] 3\u20132 at the new [[Wembley Stadium]] in the final, giving Stimson a third consecutive Trophy win as a manager.<ref>{{cite news | title = Morison's twist gives new Wembley a first final in the grand tradition | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/14/newsstory.sport15 | newspaper = The Guardian|author=Jeremy Alexander | date = 14 May 2007 | accessdate =2 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:StimmoWarmUp.jpg|thumb|right|Stimson (far left) leading the warm-up before a [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] match in 2008]]\nIn the early part of the [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]] season, speculation began to mount that Stimson would be approached to take over as manager of a Football League club, with Gillingham, [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] all alleged to be interested in his services.<ref name=\"Mill\">{{cite news | title = Gills unveil Stimson as new boss | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/7073636.stm | work = BBC Sport | date = 1 November 2007 | accessdate =6 September 2008}}</ref> He was offered a new contract by Stevenage on 16 October 2007,<ref name=\"Stevenage offer Stimson new deal\">{{cite news | title = Stevenage offer Stimson new deal | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/7047655.stm | work = BBC Sport | date = 16 October 2007 | accessdate =17 October 2007}}</ref> but resigned the following day.<ref name=\"Stimson resigns as Stevenage boss\">{{cite news | title = Stimson resigns as Stevenage boss | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/7049044.stm | work = BBC Sport | date = 17 October 2007 | accessdate =17 October 2007}}</ref> On 1 November, he was appointed as the new manager of Gillingham,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~1157378,00.html |title=New manager at KRBS Priestfield |accessdate=1 November 2007 |publisher=Gillingham F.C. |date=1 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080105135232/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~1157378%2C00.html |archivedate=5 January 2008}}</ref> and quickly moved to sign a number of Stevenage players, including [[Adam Miller (footballer)|Adam Miller]] and [[John Nutter]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/7105653.stm|work=BBC Sport|title=Gillingham capture Stevenage pair|accessdate=22 April 2008|date=23 November 2007}}</ref> He was unable to recreate his previous success, however, and at the end of the 2007\u201308 season Gillingham were relegated from [[Football League One|League One]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7377686.stm|title=Leeds 2\u20131 Gillingham|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 May 2008|date=3 May 2008}}</ref> He was also criticised by departing player [[Aaron Brown (footballer born 1980)|Aaron Brown]], who acknowledged that Stimson had strong coaching skills but described his man-management as \"shocking\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://yourmaidstone.co.uk/kent-news/Unhappy-Brown-lets-rip-at-Stimson-newsinkent14208.aspx?news=sport|title=Unhappy Brown lets rip at Stimson|publisher=Your Maidstone|accessdate=21 September 2010|date=2 July 2008}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The following season the Gills finished fifth in League Two and beat [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] 1\u20130 in the [[2009 Football League Two play-off Final|play-off Final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] to gain promotion,<ref name=\"BBC report\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8048284.stm|title=Gillingham 1\u20130 Shrewsbury|work=[[BBC Sport]]|first=Paul|last= Fletcher|date=24 May 2009|accessdate=12 June 2009}}</ref> but in the [[2009\u201310 in English football|2009\u201310]] season Gillingham were relegated back to League Two, after which Stimson's contract was terminated \"by mutual consent\" on 10 May 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~2048210,00.html |title=Stimson departs Priestfield |date=10 May 2010 |accessdate=10 May 2010 |publisher=[[Gillingham F.C.]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100512203455/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~2048210%2C00.html |archivedate=12 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June, Stimson was appointed as the new manager of League Two club [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnet/8716776.stm|title=Barnet name Mark Stimson as new manager|date=1 June 2010|accessdate=2 June 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> but was sacked seven months later on 1 January 2011 due to a bad string of results which left the club near the bottom of the table.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnet/9332504.stm|title=Boss Mark Stimson shown door by Barnet|date=1 January 2011|accessdate=1 January 2011|work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Towards the latter stages of the 2010\u201311 season, Stimson accepted a coaching role at [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kentnews.co.uk/mobile/sport/ex_gills_boss_mark_stimson_ready_for_managerial_return_1_971758 |title=Ex Gills boss Mark Stimson ready for managerial return |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=31 October 2011 |publisher=Kent News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407035525/http://www.kentnews.co.uk/mobile/sport/ex_gills_boss_mark_stimson_ready_for_managerial_return_1_971758 |archivedate=7 April 2012 }}</ref> After a brief spell at Dagenham, he was appointed manager of [[Conference National]] club [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]] on 7 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14797805.stm|title=Kettering Town to appoint Mark Stimson new manager|date=7 September 2011|accessdate=8 September 2011|work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> On 4 January 2012, Stimson left Kettering with the team placed in the Conference relegation places.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mark Stimson leaves as Kettering Town manager|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16418695.stm|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 January 2012|accessdate=4 January 2012}}</ref> Four months later he was appointed manager of [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]] following the club's relegation to the [[Isthmian League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theenquirer.co.uk/Stimson+is+new+man+at+Thurrock+FC%20id=6921|title=Stimson is new man at Thurrock FC|work=The Enquirer|date=16 May 2012|accessdate=16 May 2012}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> At the age of 49, Stimson was registered as a player again for the 2017\u201318 season and named himself as a substitute on a number of occasions.<ref name=\"FWP-Thurrock\">{{Cite web|title=Appearances - Mark Stimson|publisher=Football Web Pages.co.uk|url=https://www.footballwebpages.co.uk/appearances/458475|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May 2018, after leaving Thurrock as a result of the club folding, Stimson was appointed manager of [[Waltham Abbey F.C.|Waltham Abbey]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Abbotts Appoint New Manager|publisher=Waltham Abbey F.C.|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/walthamabbeysenior/news/abbotts-appoint-new-manager-2297107.html|date=10 May 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> In November of the same year, however, he resigned in order to take over as manager of [[AFC Hornchurch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.romfordrecorder.co.uk/sport/football/non-league/hornchurch-appoint-stimson-1-5800372|title=AFC Hornchurch appoint Mark Stimson|work=Romford Recorder|first=Jacob|last=Ranson|date=29 November 2018|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStimson is married, and when he returned to former club Grays Athletic as manager of Stevenage Borough in 2007, he and his wife were praised for visiting the clubhouse after the game to chat to home supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://graysathletic.co.uk/matches/archives/001646.html|title=Grays Athletic 0 Stevenage Borough 2|publisher=Grays Athletic F.C.|author=Martin Candler|accessdate=16 September 2008|date=17 February 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070221005143/http://www.graysathletic.co.uk/matches/archives/001646.html |archivedate = 21 February 2007}}</ref> He has three children, including a son, [[Charlie Stimson|Charlie]], who in 2008 joined Gillingham's youth team, but turned down the offer of a professional contract in 2010 after his father's dismissal from the manager's job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourfolkestone.co.uk/kent-news/Stimson-is-Scally_s-number-one-newsinkent6526.aspx?news=sport |title=Stimson is Scally's number one |publisher=YourShepway.co.uk |accessdate=2 September 2008 |date=4 November 2007 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/8675912.stm|title=Gillingham put contract talks on hold|publisher=BBC|date=11 May 2010|accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref> In 2000, Stimson presented his [[Essex Senior Cup]] winner's medal to a disabled Canvey Island fan, saying \"it's easy to forget the fans who come along and support us, often in pouring rain.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Soccer: Touching gestures eclipses Gulls' loss|publisher=Billericay Weekly News|date=24 April 2000}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|4 January 2012}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Ref\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]]\n|align=left|17 September 2002\n|align=left|16 May 2006\n|202||111||60||31||{{#expr: 111/202 * 100 round 1}}||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1153&seasonid=132|title=Grays 2002/2003 results and fixtures |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1153&seasonid=133|title=Grays 2003/2004 results and fixtures |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1153&seasonid=134|title=Grays 2004/2005 results and fixtures |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1153&seasonid=135|title=Grays 2005/2006 results and fixtures |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]]\n|align=left|28 May 2006\n|align=left|17 October 2007\n|72||38||13||21||{{#expr: 38/72 * 100 round 1}}||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=2499&seasonid=136|title=Stevenage 2006/2007 results and fixtures|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=2499&seasonid=137|title=Stevenage 2007/2008 results and fixtures|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n|align=left|1 November 2007\n|align=left|10 May 2010\n|144||48||41||55||{{#expr: 48/144 * 100 round 1}}||<ref name=\"sb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=2095|title=Mark Stimson's managerial career|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120912054354/http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=2095|archive-date=12 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n|align=left|1 June 2010\n|align=left|1 January 2011\n|26||5||5||16||{{#expr: 5/26 * 100 round 1}}||<ref name=\"sb\" />\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]\n|align=left|7 September 2011\n|align=left|4 January 2012\n|22||4||5||13||{{#expr: 4/22 * 100 round 1}}||<ref name=\"sb\" />\n|-\n!align=center colspan=3|Total\n!466!!206!!124!!136!!{{#expr: 206/466 * 100 round 1}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===As a player===\n*[[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301]]: [[FA Trophy]] winner \u2013 [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]]\n\n===As a manager===\n*[[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]]: [[Conference South]] champions \u2013 [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]]\n*2004\u201305: FA Trophy winners \u2013 Grays Athletic\n*[[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]]: FA Trophy winners \u2013 Grays Athletic\n*[[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]]: FA Trophy winners \u2013 [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]]\n*[[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309]]: [[Football League Two|League Two]] play-off winners \u2013 [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n*[[2016\u201317 in English football|2016\u201317]]: [[Isthmian League|Isthmian Division One North]] play-off winners \u2013 [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Grays Athletic F.C. managers}}\n{{Stevenage F.C. managers}}\n{{Gillingham F.C. managers}}\n{{Barnet F.C. managers}}\n{{Kettering Town F.C. managers}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stimson, Mark}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Plaistow, Newham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England semi-pro international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leyton Orient F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnet F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Canvey Island F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grays Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Thurrock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Isthmian League players]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Grays Athletic F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Stevenage F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Barnet F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Kettering Town F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Thurrock F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Waltham Abbey F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:A.F.C. Hornchurch managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) managers]]\n[[Category:Player-coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|Australian rugby league player|Mark Stimson (rugby league)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mark Stimson\n| image = Mark Stimson.JPG\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Mark Stimson\n| fullname = Mark Nicholas Stimson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1967|12|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Plaistow, Newham|Plaistow]], England\n| currentclub = [[Hornchurch F.C.|Hornchurch]] (manager)\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthclubs1 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]\n| youthclubs2 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| youthyears1 = {{0|000}}?\u20131984\n| youthyears2 = 1984\u20131985\n| years1 = 1985\u20131989\n| years2 = 1988\n| years3 = 1989\n| years4 = 1989\u20131993\n| years5 = 1992\n| years6 = 1993\u20131996\n| years7 = 1995\n| years8 = 1996\u20131999\n| years9 = 1999\n| years10 = 1999\u20132002\n| years11 = 2002\u20132004\n| years12 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs1 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] (loan)\n| clubs4 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] (loan)\n| clubs6 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]\n| clubs9 = [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]]\n| clubs10 = [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]]\n| clubs11 = [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]]\n| clubs12 = [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]]\n| caps1 = 2\n| goals1 = 0\n| caps2 = 10\n| goals2 = 0\n| caps3 = 18\n| goals3 = 0\n| caps4 = 86\n| goals4 = 2\n| caps5 = 4\n| goals5 = 0\n| caps6 = 58\n| goals6 = 2\n| caps7 = 5\n| goals7 = 0\n| caps8 = 57\n| goals8 = 0\n| caps9 = 2\n| goals9 = 0\n| caps10 = ?\n| goals10 = ?\n| caps11 = ?\n| goals11 = ?\n| caps12 = 0\n| goals12 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2002\u20132006\n| manageryears2 = 2006\u20132007\n| manageryears3 = 2007\u20132010\n| manageryears4 = 2010\u20132011\n| manageryears5 = 2011\u20132012\n| manageryears6 = 2012\u20132018\n| manageryears7 = 2018\n| manageryears8 = 2018\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]]\n| managerclubs2 = [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n| managerclubs4 = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n| managerclubs5 = [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]\n| managerclubs6 = [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]]\n| managerclubs7 = [[Waltham Abbey F.C.|Waltham Abbey]]\n| managerclubs8 = [[Hornchurch F.C.|Hornchurch]]\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\n| nationalteam1 = [[England C national football team|England National Game XI]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Mark Nicholas Stimson''' (born 27 December 1967)<ref>{{cite book | first=Roger|last= Triggs | title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club| publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd | year=2001| isbn=978-0-7524-2243-5|pages=307}}</ref> is an English former [[association football|footballer]] and is currently [[manager (association football)|manager]] of [[Hornchurch F.C.|Hornchurch]]. He signed his first professional contract with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in 1985, but was unable to gain a regular place in the team. In 1989, he moved on to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], where he made over 80 appearances in [[the Football League]]. He later played for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] and [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] before dropping into [[non-League football]].\n\nHe was appointed manager of [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]] in 2002 and remained in charge until 2006 when he took over as manager of [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]]. He led Grays to victory in the Final of the [[FA Trophy]] in 2005 and 2006, and repeated the feat with Stevenage in 2007. In November 2007, he became manager of a Football League team for the first time when he took over at one of his former clubs, [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], but he was unable to prevent the club's [[Promotion and relegation|relegation]] from [[Football League One|League One]] at the end of the [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]] season. He led Gillingham back into League One the following season via the [[2009 Football League Two play-off Final|League Two play-off Final]], but his contract was terminated after the team were relegated back to League Two the following season. On 1 June 2010, Stimson was appointed as the new manager of League Two club [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]], but he was sacked on New Year's Day 2011 with the club near the bottom of the table. He later had a spell as manager with Conference club [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Plaistow, Newham|Plaistow]] in east London, Stimson played for the [[Essex]] county representative football team and was on the books of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], before joining [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on an apprenticeship in July 1984. A year later, he signed his first professional contract, at the age of 17.<ref name=\"triggs\">{{cite book | first=Roger|last= Triggs | title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club|pages=308}}</ref> He made his [[the Football League|Football League]] debut against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in May 1987,<ref name=\"CI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canveyislandfc.co.uk/2000/squad.htm#Mark%20Stimson|title=2000\u201301 squad|publisher=Canvey Island F.C.|accessdate=1 September 2008}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> but struggled to gain a place in the first team, and was sent to [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] on loan in March 1988, where he played ten times.<ref name=\"SB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=7641|title=Mark Stimson|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=1 September 2008}}</ref> During the following season, he was loaned out again, this time to [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], whose manager, [[Keith Burkinshaw]], had worked with him at Tottenham. Stimson made 18 appearances for the [[Kent]]-based club and, although he was unable to help the team avoid [[Promotion and relegation|relegation]] from the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]], his contribution impressed the fans, who voted him into second place in the club's player of the year ballot.<ref name=\"triggs\" />\n\nAt the end of the [[1988\u201389 in English football|1988\u201389]] season, Stimson was transferred to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], then in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fchd.info/NEWCASTU.HTM|title=Newcastle United|accessdate=3 September 2008|publisher=The Football Club History Database}}</ref> for a fee of \u00a3200,000.<ref name=\"SB\" /> He spent four years with the club and finally gained a regular first team place, making over 80 appearances.<ref name=\"SB\" /> After [[Kevin Keegan]] took over as manager, however, Stimson found himself out of favour and he had a short spell on loan to [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in December 1992, which led to a \u00a3100,000 transfer at the end of that season.<ref name=\"triggs\" /><ref name=\"Sun2\">{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LSNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F934C29685AF044&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815|title=The Great career \u2013 Profile|newspaper=The Sun|accessdate=2 September 2008|date=9 January 1997}}</ref> He made over fifty appearances for Portsmouth but was also loaned out again, this time to [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] during the early part of the [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396]] season.<ref name=\"SB\" /> In March 1996, he was transferred to [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] for a fee of \u00a325,000.<ref name=\"SB\" /> His first season at the club was affected by a long lay-off due to injury,<ref name=\"Sun\">{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LSNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F9350C11D5406C4&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815|title=Foley: Time to get back to our Roots \u2013 Football|newspaper=The Sun|accessdate=2 September 2008|date=2 November 1996}}</ref> meaning that he did not play between August and November,<ref name=\"SB96\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=126&playerid=7641|title=Games played by Mark Stimson in 1996/1997|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref> but he ultimately made over 50 Football League appearances for the club.<ref name=\"SB\" /> During his time at [[Roots Hall]] the club suffered two consecutive relegations, dropping from the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] into the Second Division in 1997 and from there into the Third Division in 1998.<ref name=\"South\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fchd.info/SOUTHENU.HTM|title=Southend United|publisher=The Football Club History Database|accessdate=6 September 2008}}</ref> In March 1999, having not played for Southend since the previous November, he returned to former club Leyton Orient on a [[Free transfer (football)|free transfer]].<ref name=\"SB98\" /> He played for the club in the semi-finals of the [[Football League Two play-offs|play-offs]], but was restricted to an appearance as an unused substitute in the final, which Orient lost.<ref name=\"SB98\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=128&playerid=7641|title=Games played by Mark Stimson in 1998/1999|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"SB99\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=306797|title=League Two Play-Off \u2013 Final \u2013 KO 15:00|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the [[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000]] season, Stimson spent a short period on trial at another of his former clubs, Gillingham, but manager [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]] decided against offering him a contract and he instead joined [[Isthmian League]] club [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]].<ref name=\"triggs\" /> He helped the \"Gulls\" win the [[FA Trophy]] in the [[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301]] season, setting up the only goal and winning the man of the match award in Canvey's 1\u20130 defeat of [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] in the final.<ref name=\"triggs\" /><ref name=\"FG\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/canveys-class-takes-trophy-684653.html|title=Football: Canvey's class takes Trophy|newspaper=The Independent|date=14 May 2001|author=Rupert Metcalf|accessdate=1 September 2008}}</ref> He was also selected to play for the [[England C national football team|England National Game XI]], the national team for semi-professional players,<ref name=\"FA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/NationalGameXI/NewsAndFeatures/33657.htm|archive-url=https://archive.today/20050411002559/http://www.thefa.com/England/NationalGameXI/NewsAndFeatures/33657.htm|url-status=dead|archivedate=11 April 2005|title=Stimson proud to play for England|publisher=The Football Association|date=10 December 2002|accessdate=1 September 2008 }}</ref> earning one [[Cap (sport)|cap]] against an equivalent team from the United States.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Non-League Club Directory 2007|first=Mike|last=Williams|author2=Tony Williams|year=2007|publisher=Tony Williams Publications Ltd|id=1-8698-3355-4|page=860}}</ref> He left Canvey in May 2002 to join [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]] as player-coach.<ref name=\"GA\">{{Cite news|title=Grays in swoop for Gulls|newspaper=The Gazette|date=3 May 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nIn September 2002, Stimson took over as manager of Grays after the sacking of Craig Edwards, initially as [[caretaker manager]], but after leading the team to its first victory of the season, he was quickly given the job on an ongoing basis.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stimson brings in Polston |url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=6057 |publisher=Non-League Daily |date=17 September 2002 |accessdate=30 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921144420/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=6057 |archivedate=21 September 2012}}</ref> Despite the signing of a number of former top-level players, such as [[Carl Leaburn]] and [[Jason Dozzell]],<ref>{{cite web | title = About GAFC | url = http://graysathletic.co.uk/about/ | publisher = Grays Athletic F.C. | accessdate =3 September 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070925220910/http://www.graysathletic.co.uk/about/ |archivedate = 25 September 2007}}</ref> the team escaped relegation by only one point.<ref>{{cite web |title=Isthmian League 2002\u201303 |url=http://www.fchd.info/lghist/isthmian/isth2003.htm |publisher=The Football Club History Database |accessdate=3 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080930070015/http://www.fchd.info/lghist/isthmian/isth2003.htm |archivedate=30 September 2008}}</ref> The following season, however, boosted by a switch to full-time professional status and helped by the goals of [[Freddy Eastwood]], Grays finished in 6th place,<ref name=\"Gr\" /> sufficient to gain a place in the newly formed [[Conference South]] for the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]] season.<ref name=\"CS\" /> Grays won the Conference South at the first attempt by a margin of 23 points,<ref name=\"CS\">{{cite web |title = Football Conference 2004\u201305 |url = http://www.fchd.info/lghist/conf/conf2005.htm |publisher = The Football Club History Database |accessdate = 3 September 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080930064207/http://www.fchd.info/lghist/conf/conf2005.htm |archivedate = 30 September 2008 |df = dmy-all\n}}</ref> thus achieving promotion to the [[Conference National]], the top level of [[non-league football]], for the first time in their history.<ref name=\"Gr\">{{cite web | title = Grays Athletic | url = http://www.fchd.info/GRAYSA.HTM | publisher = The Football Club History Database | accessdate =3 September 2008}}</ref> In the same season, Stimson also led Grays to the FA Trophy Final, where the team beat [[Hucknall Town F.C.|Hucknall Town]] in a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]].<ref name=\"T1\">{{cite web | title = Grays Ath 1-1 Hucknall Town (aet) | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/4570825.stm | publisher = BBC|date=22 May 2005 | accessdate =21 September 2010}}</ref> Grays reached the FA Trophy Final again in the following season, and claimed a second successive win after a 2\u20130 victory over [[Woking F.C.|Woking]] at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]].<ref name=\"T2\">{{cite web | title = Stimson lauds Trophy win | url = http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFATrophy/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2006/05/FATrophy_Stimson.htm | publisher = The Football Association|date=15 May 2006|author=Tony Stevens | accessdate =3 September 2008}}</ref> In the Conference, Grays finished in third place and qualified for the play-offs for [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]] to [[the Football League]], but lost to [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] in the semi-finals.<ref name=\"T2\" />\n\nCiting his disappointment at failing to gain promotion, Stimson resigned from his post at Grays on 16 May 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shock as Stimson calls it a day |url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=35009 |publisher=Non-League Daily |date=16 May 2006 |accessdate=30 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921144434/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=35009 |archivedate=21 September 2012}}</ref> He stated that at the time he had received no firm job offers from other clubs, and acknowledged that he was taking a gamble with his career, but said that if he was unable to find a new job as a manager he would move into youth coaching or open his own football school.<ref>{{cite news | title = Stimmo: \"I'm gambling\"|author=Ryan Goad | url = http://www.thurrockgazette.co.uk/news/762284.stimmo_im_gambling/ | publisher = Thurrock Gazette | date = 16 May 2006 | accessdate =16 September 2008}}</ref> He was linked with the managerial vacancy at [[Football League Two|League Two]] [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Stimson for Posh? |url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=35072 |publisher=Non-League Daily |date=19 May 2006 |accessdate=30 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921144440/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=35072 |archivedate=21 September 2012}}</ref> but eventually took over as manager of [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]] on 28 May,<ref>{{cite news | title = Stevenage name Stimson as manager | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/5024698.stm | work = BBC Sport | date = 28 May 2006 | accessdate =3 September 2008}}</ref> and led the club to an eighth-place finish in the Conference National in his first season in charge.<ref>{{cite web | title = Stevenage Borough | url = http://www.fchd.info/STEVENAB.HTM | publisher = The Football Club History Database | accessdate =3 September 2008}}</ref> Stevenage also defeated Stimson's former club Grays to reach the FA Trophy final,<ref>{{cite web | title = Stevenage march into Final | url = http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFATrophy/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2007/03/Trophy_Stevenage.htm | publisher = The Football Association|author=James Andrew | date = 17 March 2007 | accessdate =2 September 2008}}</ref> and beat [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]] 3\u20132 at the new [[Wembley Stadium]] in the final, giving Stimson a third consecutive Trophy win as a manager.<ref>{{cite news | title = Morison's twist gives new Wembley a first final in the grand tradition | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/14/newsstory.sport15 | newspaper = The Guardian|author=Jeremy Alexander | date = 14 May 2007 | accessdate =2 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:StimmoWarmUp.jpg|thumb|right|Stimson (far left) leading the warm-up before a [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] match in 2008]]\nIn the early part of the [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]] season, speculation began to mount that Stimson would be approached to take over as manager of a Football League club, with Gillingham, [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] all alleged to be interested in his services.<ref name=\"Mill\">{{cite news | title = Gills unveil Stimson as new boss | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/7073636.stm | work = BBC Sport | date = 1 November 2007 | accessdate =6 September 2008}}</ref> He was offered a new contract by Stevenage on 16 October 2007,<ref name=\"Stevenage offer Stimson new deal\">{{cite news | title = Stevenage offer Stimson new deal | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/7047655.stm | work = BBC Sport | date = 16 October 2007 | accessdate =17 October 2007}}</ref> but resigned the following day.<ref name=\"Stimson resigns as Stevenage boss\">{{cite news | title = Stimson resigns as Stevenage boss | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/7049044.stm | work = BBC Sport | date = 17 October 2007 | accessdate =17 October 2007}}</ref> On 1 November, he was appointed as the new manager of Gillingham,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~1157378,00.html |title=New manager at KRBS Priestfield |accessdate=1 November 2007 |publisher=Gillingham F.C. |date=1 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080105135232/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~1157378%2C00.html |archivedate=5 January 2008}}</ref> and quickly moved to sign a number of Stevenage players, including [[Adam Miller (footballer)|Adam Miller]] and [[John Nutter]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/7105653.stm|work=BBC Sport|title=Gillingham capture Stevenage pair|accessdate=22 April 2008|date=23 November 2007}}</ref> He was unable to recreate his previous success, however, and at the end of the 2007\u201308 season Gillingham were relegated from [[Football League One|League One]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7377686.stm|title=Leeds 2\u20131 Gillingham|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 May 2008|date=3 May 2008}}</ref> He was also criticised by departing player [[Aaron Brown (footballer born 1980)|Aaron Brown]], who acknowledged that Stimson had strong coaching skills but described his man-management as \"shocking\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://yourmaidstone.co.uk/kent-news/Unhappy-Brown-lets-rip-at-Stimson-newsinkent14208.aspx?news=sport|title=Unhappy Brown lets rip at Stimson|publisher=Your Maidstone|accessdate=21 September 2010|date=2 July 2008}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The following season the Gills finished fifth in League Two and beat [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] 1\u20130 in the [[2009 Football League Two play-off Final|play-off Final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] to gain promotion,<ref name=\"BBC report\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8048284.stm|title=Gillingham 1\u20130 Shrewsbury|work=[[BBC Sport]]|first=Paul|last= Fletcher|date=24 May 2009|accessdate=12 June 2009}}</ref> but in the [[2009\u201310 in English football|2009\u201310]] season Gillingham were relegated back to League Two, after which Stimson's contract was terminated \"by mutual consent\" on 10 May 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~2048210,00.html |title=Stimson departs Priestfield |date=10 May 2010 |accessdate=10 May 2010 |publisher=[[Gillingham F.C.]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100512203455/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~2048210%2C00.html |archivedate=12 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June, Stimson was appointed as the new manager of League Two club [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnet/8716776.stm|title=Barnet name Mark Stimson as new manager|date=1 June 2010|accessdate=2 June 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> but was sacked seven months later on 1 January 2011 due to a bad string of results which left the club near the bottom of the table.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnet/9332504.stm|title=Boss Mark Stimson shown door by Barnet|date=1 January 2011|accessdate=1 January 2011|work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Towards the latter stages of the 2010\u201311 season, Stimson accepted a coaching role at [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kentnews.co.uk/mobile/sport/ex_gills_boss_mark_stimson_ready_for_managerial_return_1_971758 |title=Ex Gills boss Mark Stimson ready for managerial return |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=31 October 2011 |publisher=Kent News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407035525/http://www.kentnews.co.uk/mobile/sport/ex_gills_boss_mark_stimson_ready_for_managerial_return_1_971758 |archivedate=7 April 2012 }}</ref> After a brief spell at Dagenham, he was appointed manager of [[Conference National]] club [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]] on 7 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14797805.stm|title=Kettering Town to appoint Mark Stimson new manager|date=7 September 2011|accessdate=8 September 2011|work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> On 4 January 2012, Stimson left Kettering with the team placed in the Conference relegation places.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mark Stimson leaves as Kettering Town manager|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16418695.stm|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 January 2012|accessdate=4 January 2012}}</ref> Four months later he was appointed manager of [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]] following the club's relegation to the [[Isthmian League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theenquirer.co.uk/Stimson+is+new+man+at+Thurrock+FC%20id=6921|title=Stimson is new man at Thurrock FC|work=The Enquirer|date=16 May 2012|accessdate=16 May 2012}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> At the age of 49, Stimson was registered as a player again for the 2017\u201318 season and named himself as a substitute on a number of occasions.<ref name=\"FWP-Thurrock\">{{Cite web|title=Appearances - Mark Stimson|publisher=Football Web Pages.co.uk|url=https://www.footballwebpages.co.uk/appearances/458475|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May 2018, after leaving Thurrock as a result of the club folding, Stimson was appointed manager of [[Waltham Abbey F.C.|Waltham Abbey]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Abbotts Appoint New Manager|publisher=Waltham Abbey F.C.|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/walthamabbeysenior/news/abbotts-appoint-new-manager-2297107.html|date=10 May 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> In November of the same year, however, he resigned in order to take over as manager of [[AFC Hornchurch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.romfordrecorder.co.uk/sport/football/non-league/hornchurch-appoint-stimson-1-5800372|title=AFC Hornchurch appoint Mark Stimson|work=Romford Recorder|first=Jacob|last=Ranson|date=29 November 2018|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Managerial statistics===\n{{updated|4 January 2012}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Ref\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]]\n|align=left|17 September 2002\n|align=left|16 May 2006\n|202||111||60||31||{{#expr: 111/202 * 100 round 1}}||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1153&seasonid=132|title=Grays 2002/2003 results and fixtures |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1153&seasonid=133|title=Grays 2003/2004 results and fixtures |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1153&seasonid=134|title=Grays 2004/2005 results and fixtures |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1153&seasonid=135|title=Grays 2005/2006 results and fixtures |publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]]\n|align=left|28 May 2006\n|align=left|17 October 2007\n|72||38||13||21||{{#expr: 38/72 * 100 round 1}}||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=2499&seasonid=136|title=Stevenage 2006/2007 results and fixtures|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=2499&seasonid=137|title=Stevenage 2007/2008 results and fixtures|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n|align=left|1 November 2007\n|align=left|10 May 2010\n|144||48||41||55||{{#expr: 48/144 * 100 round 1}}||<ref name=\"sb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=2095|title=Mark Stimson's managerial career|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=27 January 2009|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120912054354/http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=2095|archive-date=12 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n|align=left|1 June 2010\n|align=left|1 January 2011\n|26||5||5||16||{{#expr: 5/26 * 100 round 1}}||<ref name=\"sb\" />\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]\n|align=left|7 September 2011\n|align=left|4 January 2012\n|22||4||5||13||{{#expr: 4/22 * 100 round 1}}||<ref name=\"sb\" />\n|-\n!align=center colspan=3|Total\n!466!!206!!124!!136!!{{#expr: 206/466 * 100 round 1}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===As a player===\n*[[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301]]: [[FA Trophy]] winner \u2013 [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]]\n\n===As a manager===\n*[[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]]: [[Conference South]] champions \u2013 [[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]]\n*2004\u201305: FA Trophy winners \u2013 Grays Athletic\n*[[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]]: FA Trophy winners \u2013 Grays Athletic\n*[[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]]: FA Trophy winners \u2013 [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]]\n*[[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309]]: [[Football League Two|League Two]] play-off winners \u2013 [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n*[[2016\u201317 in English football|2016\u201317]]: [[Isthmian League|Isthmian Division One North]] play-off winners \u2013 [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]]\n\n==Personal life==\nStimson is married, and when he returned to former club Grays Athletic as manager of Stevenage Borough in 2007, he and his wife were praised for visiting the clubhouse after the game to chat to home supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://graysathletic.co.uk/matches/archives/001646.html|title=Grays Athletic 0 Stevenage Borough 2|publisher=Grays Athletic F.C.|author=Martin Candler|accessdate=16 September 2008|date=17 February 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070221005143/http://www.graysathletic.co.uk/matches/archives/001646.html |archivedate = 21 February 2007}}</ref> He has three children, including a son, [[Charlie Stimson|Charlie]], who in 2008 joined Gillingham's youth team, but turned down the offer of a professional contract in 2010 after his father's dismissal from the manager's job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourfolkestone.co.uk/kent-news/Stimson-is-Scally_s-number-one-newsinkent6526.aspx?news=sport |title=Stimson is Scally's number one |publisher=YourShepway.co.uk |accessdate=2 September 2008 |date=4 November 2007 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/8675912.stm|title=Gillingham put contract talks on hold|publisher=BBC|date=11 May 2010|accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref> In 2000, Stimson presented his [[Essex Senior Cup]] winner's medal to a disabled Canvey Island fan, saying \"it's easy to forget the fans who come along and support us, often in pouring rain.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Soccer: Touching gestures eclipses Gulls' loss|publisher=Billericay Weekly News|date=24 April 2000}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Grays Athletic F.C. managers}}\n{{Stevenage F.C. managers}}\n{{Gillingham F.C. managers}}\n{{Barnet F.C. managers}}\n{{Kettering Town F.C. managers}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stimson, Mark}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Plaistow, Newham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England semi-pro international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leyton Orient F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnet F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Canvey Island F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grays Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Thurrock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Isthmian League players]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Grays Athletic F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Stevenage F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Barnet F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Kettering Town F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Thurrock F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Waltham Abbey F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:A.F.C. Hornchurch managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) managers]]\n[[Category:Player-coaches]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Standardise section order.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Stimson"}
{"title_page": "Emergency Action Notification", "text_new": "[[Image:EAStest.jpg|thumb|Screen seen on cable TV systems announcing a national test of the Emergency Alert System using the Emergency Action Notification protocol, November 9, 2011]][[File:U.S. presidential mobile phone alert (animated).gif|thumb|An emergency action notification test on an Android smartphone; October 2018.]]\nAn '''Emergency Action Notification''' ([[Specific Area Message Encoding|SAME]] code: EAN) is the national activation of the [[Emergency Alert System]] (EAS) and is used to alert the residents of the [[United States]] of a national emergency such as a nuclear war or any other mass casualty situation. Emergency Action Notifications can only be activated by the [[President of the United States|President]] or the President's representative (i.e. the [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.53 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.4.239.3&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064407/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.4.239.3&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref>  The [[Emergency Broadcast System]] (EBS) also carried the Emergency Action Notification. No situation since the alert's creation has been serious enough to cause a [[US President]] to broadcast it. Block me!\n\n==Operation==\nEAN messages are treated similarly to other EAS messages. When a message is received, the receiver is to open an audio channel to the originating source until the '''[[End of Message]] (EOM)''' tones are received. After the EOM is received, the station is then allowed to resume normal programming.{{efn|Unlike other messages EANs do not time out after two minutes}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Review of the Emergency Alert System  A Rule by the Federal Communications Commission on 03/22/2012|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2012/03/22/2012-6601/review-of-the-emergency-alert-system#h-14|work=Federal Register|accessdate=1 September 2013|author=FCC}}</ref>\n\n==The order of broadcast==\nOn participating stations, the following message would be read:\n{{Quote\n|text=\u201cWe interrupt our programming; this is a national emergency.\u201d\n}} \nAfter the header codes and attention signal are sent, the participating station reads an introductory script. Emergency messages are then read in this order: \n# Presidential messages, which \"take priority over any other message\"\n# Local messages\n# State messages\n# National Information Center messages\n\nA standby script is used in the case of there being no new information available.\n\nThe end-of-message codes are transmitted after presidential messages are read. The operator logs the time and date the Emergency Action Notification was received, and monitors their EAS source, awaiting an Emergency Action Termination message.<ref name=\"eas\">{{cite web|title=Emergency Alert System - 2007 TV (including Digital TV) Hndbook|url=https://apps.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DOC-278628A5.pdf|accessdate=30 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[Image:WGN EBS EAN.JPG|thumb|200px|Video slide from a prerecorded announcement of the beginning of an EAN from [[WGN-TV]], [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], in 1985, during the period of the Emergency Broadcast System. This EAN announcement was never seen on the airwaves of WGN-TV itself, but was posted to [[YouTube]] in March 2017.<ref>{{Citation|last=The Museum of Classic Chicago Television (www.FuzzyMemories.TV)|title=WGN Channel 9 - Emergency Broadcast System - \"This is NOT a Test\" (1985)|date=2017-03-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4TTEWRKnRC0|accessdate=2017-04-26}}</ref>]]\nThe term \"Emergency Action Notification\" was created when the Emergency Broadcast System went into place in 1963.  Before the mid-1970s, this was the only non-test activation permitted (the same rule also applied to the earlier [[CONELRAD]] system). The EAN signifies of a national emergency, as the wording shows. The [[Office of Civil Defense]] originally created the term for the national emergency notification enactment. FEMA soon took over after its creation.\n\n==Past operation==\nUnlike other messages, the EAN was not the alert itself, but rather a notice that the activation is beginning.<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.13 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.1.239.5&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064413/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.1.239.5&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref>   After the [[End of Message]] (EOM) tones were sent, normal programming did not resume.  Instead, most stations were to broadcast emergency information in a specific priority order.  Messages from the President are always broadcast first.  Next comes local messages, statewide and regional messages, and finally national messages not originating from the President.{{efn|Some documents refer to these as \"messages from the National Information Center (or NIC)\".  While there is a SAME code for this type of message (NIC), there exists no FCC definition of the National Information Center.}}<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.44 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.3.239.4&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064424/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.3.239.4&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref> When an EAN was initially received, and during any time a new message was not available, an FCC mandated standby script was used (and repeated).<ref name=\"fcc1154\">{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.54 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.4.239.4&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064429/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.4.239.4&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref>   Other stations, which held special permission from the FCC, would sign off until the end of the EAN.<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.41 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.3.239.1&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064445/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.3.239.1&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nNormal programming would not resume until the transmission of an [[Emergency Action Termination]] message (SAME code: EAT).<ref name=\"fcc1154\"/>\n\n==False alarms==\nA properly authenticated Emergency Action Notification was incorrectly sent to United States broadcast stations at 9:33&nbsp;a.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Standard Time]] on February 20, 1971.<ref name=conel>{{cite web|title=Code Word \"Hatefulness\": The Great EBS Scare of 1971|url=http://conelrad.blogspot.com/2010/09/code-word-hatefulness-great-ebs-scare.html|publisher=CONELRAD Adjacent|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref> At the usual time, a weekly EAN test was performed. NORAD teletype operator, W.S. Eberhardt had three tapes in front of him: a test tape, and 2 tapes indicating a real emergency, instructing the use of EAN Message #1, and #2, respectively. He inadvertently used the wrong tape, with codeword \"HATEFULNESS\". This message ordered stations to cease regular programming immediately, and begin an Emergency Action Notification using Message #1.<ref>(Timestamp to WCCO white card script instruction) {{Citation|last=2001scoop, W6LDS|title=1971 False Emergency Broadcast System EAN (Heard On WOWO-AM And WCCO-AM)|date=2012-09-16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1B1EAeh6H_I&t=384|accessdate=2018-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ebstest.stlmedia.net/pix/ebsaccident1.jpg|title=EAN Teletype message (February 20, 1971 09:33 EST)|date=2014-10-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016190942/http://ebstest.stlmedia.net/pix/ebsaccident1.jpg|archive-date=2014-10-16|url-status=dead|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref> Message 1 states that regular programming has been interrupted at the request of the United States government, but is not specific about the cause.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ae5d.com/ebs.html|title=The EBS Authenticator Word List|website=www.ae5d.com|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref> A cancellation message was sent at 9:59&nbsp;a.m. EST, but it used an incorrect codeword.<ref name=\"ebstest\">{{cite web|url=http://ebstest.stlmedia.net/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121195955/http://ebstest.stlmedia.net/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 January 2013|title=The Great Accidental Test Broadcast of 1971|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref> A cancellation message with the ''correct'' codeword, \"IMPISH\", was not sent until 10:13&nbsp;a.m. EST<ref name=\"ebstest\" /> After 40 minutes and six incorrect or improperly formatted cancellation messages, the accidental activation was officially terminated.\n\nOn June 26, 2007, an EAN was accidentally activated for the state of Illinois, when new satellite delivery equipment for the EAS was accidentally left connected to a live network during what was meant to be a closed-circuit test.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cbs2chicago.com/topstories/Emergency.Alert.System.2.337932.html |title=Emergency Alert System Activated By Mistake |website=cbs2chicago.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080806205146/http://cbs2chicago.com/topstories/Emergency.Alert.System.2.337932.html |archivedate=August 6, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Inadvertent Activation of the Illinois Emergency Alert System |url=http://www.fema.gov/media/fact_sheets/eas.shtm |publisher=FEMA |date=June 28, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070717212239/http://www.fema.gov/media/fact_sheets/eas.shtm |archivedate=July 17, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2014, [[Bobby Bones]]' [[The Bobby Bones Show|syndicated radio program]] broadcast audio from the 2011 national test of the EAS (the only one that was coded as an EAN), during a segment where he ranted over his local [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate's scheduling of an EAS test during a [[World Series]] game. The broadcast triggered the EAS on some broadcasters and cable systems; the program's distributor [[iHeartMedia]] was fined $1 million by the FCC for the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2015/05/multi-state-cascade-of-false-emergency-alerts-nets-1-million-fine/|title=\u201cMulti-state cascade\u201d of false emergency alerts nets $1 million fine|last=Brodkin|first=Jon|date=2015-05-19|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 or 2017, [[KUCO-LD]] in the Sacramento Valley area of California conducted an unauthorized test of the EAS. However, the message read in Spanish said that the activation was for an Emergency Action Notification relaying from station K20FZ. It was due to a wrong video cartridge being inserted instead of an EAS test cartridge.<ref>[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=F8vwVx6QkhU Emergency Action Notification Mistake? (AKA: Spanish EAS?)] - ''YouTube'' (uploaded May 24th, 2017)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n[[Category:Emergency Alert System]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:EAStest.jpg|thumb|Screen seen on cable TV systems announcing a national test of the Emergency Alert System using the Emergency Action Notification protocol, November 9, 2011]][[File:U.S. presidential mobile phone alert (animated).gif|thumb|An emergency action notification test on an Android smartphone; October 2018.]]\nAn '''Emergency Action Notification''' ([[Specific Area Message Encoding|SAME]] code: EAN) is the national activation of the [[Emergency Alert System]] (EAS) and is used to alert the residents of the [[United States]] of a national emergency such as a nuclear war or any other mass casualty situation. Emergency Action Notifications can only be activated by the [[President of the United States|President]] or the President's representative (i.e. the [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.53 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.4.239.3&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064407/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.4.239.3&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref>  The [[Emergency Broadcast System]] (EBS) also carried the Emergency Action Notification. No situation since the alert's creation has been serious enough to cause a [[US President]] to broadcast it.\n\n==Operation==\nEAN messages are treated similarly to other EAS messages. When a message is received, the receiver is to open an audio channel to the originating source until the '''[[End of Message]] (EOM)''' tones are received. After the EOM is received, the station is then allowed to resume normal programming.{{efn|Unlike other messages EANs do not time out after two minutes}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Review of the Emergency Alert System  A Rule by the Federal Communications Commission on 03/22/2012|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2012/03/22/2012-6601/review-of-the-emergency-alert-system#h-14|work=Federal Register|accessdate=1 September 2013|author=FCC}}</ref>\n\n==The order of broadcast==\nOn participating stations, the following message would be read:\n{{Quote\n|text=\u201cWe interrupt our programming; this is a national emergency.\u201d\n}} \nAfter the header codes and attention signal are sent, the participating station reads an introductory script. Emergency messages are then read in this order: \n# Presidential messages, which \"take priority over any other message\"\n# Local messages\n# State messages\n# National Information Center messages\n\nA standby script is used in the case of there being no new information available.\n\nThe end-of-message codes are transmitted after presidential messages are read. The operator logs the time and date the Emergency Action Notification was received, and monitors their EAS source, awaiting an Emergency Action Termination message.<ref name=\"eas\">{{cite web|title=Emergency Alert System - 2007 TV (including Digital TV) Hndbook|url=https://apps.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DOC-278628A5.pdf|accessdate=30 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[Image:WGN EBS EAN.JPG|thumb|200px|Video slide from a prerecorded announcement of the beginning of an EAN from [[WGN-TV]], [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], in 1985, during the period of the Emergency Broadcast System. This EAN announcement was never seen on the airwaves of WGN-TV itself, but was posted to [[YouTube]] in March 2017.<ref>{{Citation|last=The Museum of Classic Chicago Television (www.FuzzyMemories.TV)|title=WGN Channel 9 - Emergency Broadcast System - \"This is NOT a Test\" (1985)|date=2017-03-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4TTEWRKnRC0|accessdate=2017-04-26}}</ref>]]\nThe term \"Emergency Action Notification\" was created when the Emergency Broadcast System went into place in 1963.  Before the mid-1970s, this was the only non-test activation permitted (the same rule also applied to the earlier [[CONELRAD]] system). The EAN signifies of a national emergency, as the wording shows. The [[Office of Civil Defense]] originally created the term for the national emergency notification enactment. FEMA soon took over after its creation.\n\n==Past operation==\nUnlike other messages, the EAN was not the alert itself, but rather a notice that the activation is beginning.<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.13 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.1.239.5&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064413/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.1.239.5&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref>   After the [[End of Message]] (EOM) tones were sent, normal programming did not resume.  Instead, most stations were to broadcast emergency information in a specific priority order.  Messages from the President are always broadcast first.  Next comes local messages, statewide and regional messages, and finally national messages not originating from the President.{{efn|Some documents refer to these as \"messages from the National Information Center (or NIC)\".  While there is a SAME code for this type of message (NIC), there exists no FCC definition of the National Information Center.}}<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.44 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.3.239.4&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064424/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.3.239.4&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref> When an EAN was initially received, and during any time a new message was not available, an FCC mandated standby script was used (and repeated).<ref name=\"fcc1154\">{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.54 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.4.239.4&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064429/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.4.239.4&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref>   Other stations, which held special permission from the FCC, would sign off until the end of the EAN.<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC Rules Part 11 Subpart D \u00a7 11.41 |url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47:1.0.1.1.11.3.239.1&idno=47 |work=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064445/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=043b8e5d0d80fd6dca6acf1f271b1cfc&rgn=div8&view=text&node=47%3A1.0.1.1.11.3.239.1&idno=47 |archivedate=9 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nNormal programming would not resume until the transmission of an [[Emergency Action Termination]] message (SAME code: EAT).<ref name=\"fcc1154\"/>\n\n==False alarms==\nA properly authenticated Emergency Action Notification was incorrectly sent to United States broadcast stations at 9:33&nbsp;a.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Standard Time]] on February 20, 1971.<ref name=conel>{{cite web|title=Code Word \"Hatefulness\": The Great EBS Scare of 1971|url=http://conelrad.blogspot.com/2010/09/code-word-hatefulness-great-ebs-scare.html|publisher=CONELRAD Adjacent|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref> At the usual time, a weekly EAN test was performed. NORAD teletype operator, W.S. Eberhardt had three tapes in front of him: a test tape, and 2 tapes indicating a real emergency, instructing the use of EAN Message #1, and #2, respectively. He inadvertently used the wrong tape, with codeword \"HATEFULNESS\". This message ordered stations to cease regular programming immediately, and begin an Emergency Action Notification using Message #1.<ref>(Timestamp to WCCO white card script instruction) {{Citation|last=2001scoop, W6LDS|title=1971 False Emergency Broadcast System EAN (Heard On WOWO-AM And WCCO-AM)|date=2012-09-16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1B1EAeh6H_I&t=384|accessdate=2018-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ebstest.stlmedia.net/pix/ebsaccident1.jpg|title=EAN Teletype message (February 20, 1971 09:33 EST)|date=2014-10-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016190942/http://ebstest.stlmedia.net/pix/ebsaccident1.jpg|archive-date=2014-10-16|url-status=dead|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref> Message 1 states that regular programming has been interrupted at the request of the United States government, but is not specific about the cause.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ae5d.com/ebs.html|title=The EBS Authenticator Word List|website=www.ae5d.com|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref> A cancellation message was sent at 9:59&nbsp;a.m. EST, but it used an incorrect codeword.<ref name=\"ebstest\">{{cite web|url=http://ebstest.stlmedia.net/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121195955/http://ebstest.stlmedia.net/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 January 2013|title=The Great Accidental Test Broadcast of 1971|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref> A cancellation message with the ''correct'' codeword, \"IMPISH\", was not sent until 10:13&nbsp;a.m. EST<ref name=\"ebstest\" /> After 40 minutes and six incorrect or improperly formatted cancellation messages, the accidental activation was officially terminated.\n\nOn June 26, 2007, an EAN was accidentally activated for the state of Illinois, when new satellite delivery equipment for the EAS was accidentally left connected to a live network during what was meant to be a closed-circuit test.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cbs2chicago.com/topstories/Emergency.Alert.System.2.337932.html |title=Emergency Alert System Activated By Mistake |website=cbs2chicago.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080806205146/http://cbs2chicago.com/topstories/Emergency.Alert.System.2.337932.html |archivedate=August 6, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Inadvertent Activation of the Illinois Emergency Alert System |url=http://www.fema.gov/media/fact_sheets/eas.shtm |publisher=FEMA |date=June 28, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070717212239/http://www.fema.gov/media/fact_sheets/eas.shtm |archivedate=July 17, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2014, [[Bobby Bones]]' [[The Bobby Bones Show|syndicated radio program]] broadcast audio from the 2011 national test of the EAS (the only one that was coded as an EAN), during a segment where he ranted over his local [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate's scheduling of an EAS test during a [[World Series]] game. The broadcast triggered the EAS on some broadcasters and cable systems; the program's distributor [[iHeartMedia]] was fined $1 million by the FCC for the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2015/05/multi-state-cascade-of-false-emergency-alerts-nets-1-million-fine/|title=\u201cMulti-state cascade\u201d of false emergency alerts nets $1 million fine|last=Brodkin|first=Jon|date=2015-05-19|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 or 2017, [[KUCO-LD]] in the Sacramento Valley area of California conducted an unauthorized test of the EAS. However, the message read in Spanish said that the activation was for an Emergency Action Notification relaying from station K20FZ. It was due to a wrong video cartridge being inserted instead of an EAS test cartridge.<ref>[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=F8vwVx6QkhU Emergency Action Notification Mistake? (AKA: Spanish EAS?)] - ''YouTube'' (uploaded May 24th, 2017)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n[[Category:Emergency Alert System]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c0:8483:f101:bcd4:727a:9c41:8b29", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emergency_Action_Notification"}
{"title_page": "Stavros Mavroudeas", "text_new": "'''Stavros D. Mavroudeas''' (born 1961) is a [[Greek people|Greek]] [[economist]] working in the tradition of Political Economy. He is currently Professor of Political Economy at the Department of Social Policy of [[Panteion University]]. He was previously Professor of Political Economy at the Department of Economics of the [[University of Macedonia]].  His work in political economy has focused on [[Marxism|Marxist]] Political Economy, Development Economics, Labour Economics, History of Economic Thought and Greek Economic History. He has written on economic crises, Greek macroeconomic policy, growth theory, economics of the European integration, postmodernist economics, Regulation Approach and radical institutionalist theories.\n\n==  Biography ==\nStavros Mavroudeas was born in [[Athens]], in 1961.\nHe graduated from Varvakeios Model School in 1979.\nHe received his BA in Economics in 1984 from the Economics Department of the [[University of Athens]]. He subsequently received his MSc in Economics in 1986 from the School of Oriental and African Studies (SOAS) of the [[University of London]].   Finally, he completed his PhD in Economics in 1990 at [[Birkbeck College]] of the University of London. The title of his PhD was ''[http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=1&uin=uk.bl.ethos.529309 Regulation Approach: A Critical Appraisal]'' and was supervised by Prof. [[Ben Fine]]. His postgraduate studies were funded by the Greek State Scholarships Foundation (IKY).\n\nIn 1993, he joined the Economics Department of the University of Macedonia as a lecturer and later promoted to assistant professor, associate professor and professor. He moved to the Department of Social Policy of Panteion University in January 2020 and he is working there as professor of Political Economy.\n\nHe is teaching or has taught '''''Political Economy''''' (at an introductory, advanced and postgraduate level), '''''Economic Analysis''''' and '''''Development Economics'''''. Some of the optional courses taught by S.Mavroudeas include '''''Theories of Economic Crises''''', '''''Structural Problems of the Greek Economy''''', '''''Economic Problems of Contemporary Capitalism, Economics of Social Policy, Labour Economics & Labour Market Policies'''''.\n\nS.Mavroudeas has given many lectures in Greece and abroad on relevant matters.\n\nHis major political influences stem from the Left in Greece and from progressive movements abroad. He has been a student union activist, an academic trade unionist and a Left political activist. His major theoretical influences come from Marxism.\n\nHe is a founding member and subsequently a council member (secretary, president) of the Greek Association of Political Economy (GAPE). He has published and refereed in many academic journal including Science & Society, Review of Radical Political Economics, Review of Political Economy, World Review of Political Economy, Review of Keynesian Economics, Industrial Relations Journal, Economie Appliquee, International Critical Thought etc. He has also reviewed books for well-known publishing houses like Routledge, Palgrave-Macmillan etc. He had also participated in many conferences as presenter, discussant, chair and organiser. He was also visiting researcher in several universities (SOAS, City University London, Kingston University London, University of Siena etc.). \n\nIn 2018 he was awarded the World Association of Political Economy (WAPE) prize for \u2018Distinguished Achievement Award on World Political Economy of the Twenty-first Century\u2019 for his book \u2018Greek Capitalism in Crisis: Marxist Analyses\u2019 (Routledge). \n\n== Selected publications ==\n* Mavroudeas S. - Siriopoulos C. (1998), \u2018Convergence or divergence: the data from Greece\u2019, Journal of Applied Business Research vol.14 no.1.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2004), \u2018Forms of existence of abstract labour and value-form\u2019, Freeman A.-Kliman A.-Wells J. (2004), eds, \u2018The New Value Controversy: the Foundations of Economics\u2019, Cheltenham: Edward Elgar.\n* Mavroudeas S. (1999), \u2018Regulation Theory: The Road from Creative Marxism to Post-Modern Disintegration\u2019, Science & Society vol.63 no.3 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/40384308?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents[.\n* Mavroudeas S. (1999), \u2018Periodising Capitalism: Problems and Method - The case of the Regulation Approach\u2019 in Research in Political Economy vol.17 [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228273784_Periodising_Capitalism_Problems_and_Method_-_The_Case_of_the_Regulation_Approach<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2001), \u2018The Falling Rate of Profit\u2019, review essay for the Routledge Encyclopedia of International Political Economy.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2001), \u2018The Mode of Regulation\u2019, review essay for the Routledge Encyclopedia of International Political Economy.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2001), \u2018The Monetary Equivalent of Labour and certain issues regarding Money and the Value of Labour-Power\u2019, Economie Applique tome LIV no.1.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2003), \u2018Commodities, workers and institutions: Analytical and empirical problems in Regulation\u2019s Consumption Theory\u2019, Review of Radical Political Economics vol.35 no.4 [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0486613403257805<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. & Ioannides A. (2006), \u2018Grossmann, Kalecki and the theory of crisis: A comment on Trigg\u2019, Science & Society vol.7 no. 3 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/40404844?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. & Ioannides A. (2006), \u2018Henryk Grossmann\u2019s Falling Rate of Profit theory of crisis: a presentation and a reply to old and new critics\u2019, Indian Development Review vol.4 no.1 [https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/6603071.pdf<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2006), \u2018A History of Contemporary Political Economy and Post-Modernism\u2019, Review of Radical Political Economics vol.38 no.4 [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0486613406293217<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. & Papadatos D. (2007), \u2018Reform, Reform the Reforms or Simply Regression? The 'Washington Consensus' and its Critics\u2019, Bulletin of Political Economy vol.1 no.1 [https://ideas.repec.org/p/pra/mprapa/19735.html<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. & Ioannides A. (2007), \u2018Overworked Greeks? Working time trends in Greece\u2019, Asian-African Journal of Economics and Econometrics vol.7 no.1-2 [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/40842984_Overworked_Greeks_Working_time_trends_in_Greece<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2010), \u2018Development and crises: The turbulent course of Greek capitalism\u2019 in the collective volume Topos (2010), The chart of crisis: The end of self-deceit, Athens: Topos Publishers (in Greek).\n* Ioannides A. & Mavroudeas S. (2010), \u2018Work more or work harder? The length and the intensity of work in Marx\u2019s \u2018Capital\u2019, Science & Society, vol.74 no.1 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/40404662?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2011), \u2018The Regulation Approach\u2019 in Fine B. & Saad-Filho A. (eds.) Companion to Marxist Economics, Edward Elgar.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2011), \u2018The Social Structures of Accumulation approach\u2019 in Fine B. & Saad-Filho A. (eds.) Companion to Marxist Economics, Edward Elgar.\n* Ioannides A. & Mavroudeas S. (2011), \u2018Duration, Intensity and Productivity of Labour and the Distinction between Absolute and Relative Surplus-Value\u2019, Review of Political Economy, vol.23 no.3 [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/09538259.2011.583833<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Ioannides A. & Mavroudeas S. (2011), \u2018A model for the relationship between working time and the intensity of labour\u2019, Bulletin of Political Economy vol.5 no.2.\n* Mavroudeas S. & Papadatos D. (2012), \u2018Financial Regulation in the light of the current global economic crisis\u2019, International Critical Thought vol.2 no.4 [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/21598282.2012.730381<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2013), \u2018Development and Crisis: The Turbulent Course of Greek Capitalism\u2019, International Critical Thought vol.3 no.3 [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/21598282.2013.818090<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Gialis S. & Mavroudeas S. (2014), \u2018Virtual Water: more heat than light?\u2019, Capitalism Nature Socialism vol.5 no.2 [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10455752.2013.877512<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2013), \u2018Teaching Political Economy and Marxism at an introductory level: A view from Greece\u2019, International Journal of Pluralism and Economics Education vol.4 no.3.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2014) ed., Greek capitalism in crisis: Marxist Analyses, London: Routledge [https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/9781317756149<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Ioannides A., Oxouzi E. & Mavroudeas S. (2014), \u2018All work and no ... pay? Unpaid overtime in Greece: determining factors and theoretical explanations\u2019, Industrial Relations Journal vol.45 no.1 [https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/irj.12041<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2011), 'The Limits of Regulation: A Critical Analysis of Capitalist Development', Cheltenham: Edward Elgar [https://www.e-elgar.com/shop/the-limits-of-regulation?___website=uk_warehouse<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2016), \u2018The Greek crisis: a structural or a conjunctural crisis?\u2019 in Subasat T. (ed.) The Great Financial Meltdown: Systemic, Conjunctural or Policy-Created? New Directions in Modern Economics series, Cheltenham: Edward Elgar [https://www.e-elgar.com/shop/the-great-financial-meltdown<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2017), \u2018Is Cartelier\u2019s Monetary Approach a Convincing Alternative to the Labour Theory of Value? A Comment\u2019, Stavros Mavroudeas, ''Economic Thought'' vol.6 no.2, October [http://et.worldeconomicsassociation.org/papers/is-carteliers-monetary-approach-a-convincing-alternative-to-the-labour-theory-of-value-a-comment/<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2017), \u2018Troika\u2019s Economic Adjustment Programmes for Greece: Why do they Systematically Fail\u2019 in Marangos, J., (ed.), ''The Internal Impact and External Influence of the Greek Financial Crisis,'' Palgrave Macmillan, New York [https://www.palgrave.com/gp/book/9783319602004<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2018), \u2018Competing explanations and strategies for the Greek crisis and the problem of the productive model\u2019 in Fouskas V. & Dimoulas K. (eds), ''Greece in the 21st Century. The Politics and Economics of a Crisis'', Routledge [https://www.routledge.com/Greece-in-the-21st-Century-The-Politics-and-Economics-of-a-Crisis/Fouskas-Dimoulas/p/book/9781857438673<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2018), \u2018Economic Adjustment Programmes for Greece: Origins, Structure, Deficiencies and Systematic Failures\u2019 in Anastasios Karasavvoglou, Sre\u0107ko Goi\u0107, Persefoni Polychronidou, Delias Pavlos (eds.), ''Economy, Finance and Business in Southeastern and Central Europe - Proceedings of the 8th International Conference on the Economies of the Balkan and Eastern European Countries in the Changing World (EBEEC)'' in Split, Croatia, 2016, Springer [https://www.springer.com/la/book/9783319703763<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. & Seretis S. (2018), \u2018Imperialist exploitation and the Greek crisis\u2019, ''East-West Journal of Economics and Business'', Vol. XXI \u2013 2018, Nos 1-2 [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/328654460_IMPERIALIST_EXPLOITATION_AND_THE_GREEK_CRISIS<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2018), \u2018The Greek crisis: Causes and Alternative Strategies\u2019 in Sotiris P. (ed.), ''Crisis, Movement, Strategy: The Greek experience,'' Historical Materialism series, Leiden: Brill [https://brill.com/abstract/title/26716<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. & Papadatos F. (2018), \u2018Is the Financialisation Hypothesis a theoretical blind alley?\u2019, World Review of Political Economy vol.9 no.4\n*Mavroudeas S. (2019), \u2018De-globalisation and the Return of the Theory of Imperialism\u2019, in Kaoru Natsuda K. et al (eds.), ''Globalisation and Public Policy'', London: IJOPEC\n*Mavroudeas S. (2019), \u2018The Financialisation Hypothesis and Marxism: a positive contribution or a Trojan Horse?\u2019 in Proceedings of the SECOND WORLD CONGRESS ON MARXISM \u2018Marxism and the current world and China\u2019, Peking University \n*Mavroudeas S. (2019), \u2018Comment on Miguel Ramirez\u2019s paper, \u201cCredit, Indebtedness and Speculation in Marx\u2019s Political Economy\u201d\u2019 ''Economic Thought'', vol.8 no.2, [http://www.worldeconomicsassociation.org/files/journals/economicthought/WEA-ET-8-2-Mavroudeas.pdf<nowiki>]</nowiki> <br />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://stavrosmavroudeas.wordpress.com Stavros Mavroudeas homepage]\n*[https://220.academia.edu/StavrosMavroudeas Academia page]\n* [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Stavros_Mavroudeas Researchgate page]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mavroudeas, Stavros}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Athens]]\n[[Category:Greek economists]]\n[[Category:National and Kapodistrian University of Athens alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Birkbeck, University of London]]\n", "text_old": "'''Stavros D. Mavroudeas''' (born 1961) is a [[Greek people|Greek]] [[economist]] working in the tradition of Political Economy. He is currently Professor of Political Economy at the Department of Social Policy of [[Panteion University]]. He was previously Professor of Political Economy at the Department of Economics of the [[University of Macedonia]].  His work in political economy has focused on [[Marxism|Marxist]] Political Economy, Development Economics, Labour Economics, History of Economic Thought and Greek Economic History. He has written on economic crises, Greek macroeconomic policy, growth theory, economics of the European integration, postmodernist economics, Regulation Approach and radical institutionalist theories.\n\n==  Biography ==\nStavros Mavroudeas was born in [[Athens]], in 1961.\nHe graduated from Varvakeios Model School in 1979.\nHe received his BA in Economics in 1984 from the Economics Department of the [[University of Athens]]. He subsequently received his MSc in Economics in 1986 from the School of Oriental and African Studies (SOAS) of the [[University of London]].   Finally, he completed his PhD in Economics in 1990 at [[Birkbeck College]] of the University of London. The title of his PhD was ''[http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=1&uin=uk.bl.ethos.529309 Regulation Approach: A Critical Appraisal]'' and was supervised by Prof. [[Ben Fine]]. His postgraduate studies were funded by the Greek State Scholarships Foundation (IKY).\n\nIn 1993, he joined the Economics Department of the University of Macedonia as a lecturer and later promoted to assistant professor, associate professor and professor. He moved to the Department of Social Policy of Panteion University in January 2020 and he is working there as professor of Political Economy.\n\nHe is teaching or has taught '''''Political Economy''''' (at an introductory, advanced and postgraduate level), '''''Economic Analysis''''' and '''''Development Economics'''''. Some of the optional courses taught by S.Mavroudeas include '''''Theories of Economic Crises''''', '''''Structural Problems of the Greek Economy''''', '''''Economic Problems of Contemporary Capitalism, Economics of Social Policy, Labour Economics & Labour Market Policies'''''.\n\nS.Mavroudeas has given many lectures in Greece and abroad on relevant matters.\n\nHis major political influences stem from the Left in Greece and from progressive movements abroad. He has been a student union activist, an academic trade unionist and a Left political activist. His major theoretical influences come from Marxism.\n\nHe is a founding member and subsequently a council member (secretary, president) of the Greek Association of Political Economy (GAPE). He has published and refereed in many academic journal including Science & Society, Review of Radical Political Economics, Review of Political Economy, World Review of Political Economy, Review of Keynesian Economics, Industrial Relations Journal, Economie Appliquee, International Critical Thought etc. He has also reviewed books for well-known publishing houses like Routledge, Palgrave-Macmillan etc. He had also participated in many conferences as presenter, discussant, chair and organiser. He was also visiting researcher in several universities (SOAS, City University London, Kingston University London, University of Siena etc.). \n\nIn 2018 he was awarded the World Association of Political Economy (WAPE) prize for \u2018Distinguished Achievement Award on World Political Economy of the Twenty-first Century\u2019 for his book \u2018Greek Capitalism in Crisis: Marxist Analyses\u2019 (Routledge). \n\n== Selected publications ==\n* Mavroudeas S. - Siriopoulos C. (1998), \u2018Convergence or divergence: the data from Greece\u2019, Journal of Applied Business Research vol.14 no.1.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2004), \u2018Forms of existence of abstract labour and value-form\u2019, Freeman A.-Kliman A.-Wells J. (2004), eds, \u2018The New Value Controversy: the Foundations of Economics\u2019, Cheltenham: Edward Elgar.\n* Mavroudeas S. (1999), \u2018Regulation Theory: The Road from Creative Marxism to Post-Modern Disintegration\u2019, Science & Society vol.63 no.3 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/40384308?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents[.\n* Mavroudeas S. (1999), \u2018Periodising Capitalism: Problems and Method - The case of the Regulation Approach\u2019 in Research in Political Economy vol.17 [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228273784_Periodising_Capitalism_Problems_and_Method_-_The_Case_of_the_Regulation_Approach<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2001), \u2018The Falling Rate of Profit\u2019, review essay for the Routledge Encyclopedia of International Political Economy.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2001), \u2018The Mode of Regulation\u2019, review essay for the Routledge Encyclopedia of International Political Economy.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2001), \u2018The Monetary Equivalent of Labour and certain issues regarding Money and the Value of Labour-Power\u2019, Economie Applique tome LIV no.1.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2003), \u2018Commodities, workers and institutions: Analytical and empirical problems in Regulation\u2019s Consumption Theory\u2019, Review of Radical Political Economics vol.35 no.4 [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0486613403257805<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. & Ioannides A. (2006), \u2018Grossmann, Kalecki and the theory of crisis: A comment on Trigg\u2019, Science & Society vol.7 no. 3 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/40404844?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. & Ioannides A. (2006), \u2018Henryk Grossmann\u2019s Falling Rate of Profit theory of crisis: a presentation and a reply to old and new critics\u2019, Indian Development Review vol.4 no.1 [https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/6603071.pdf<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2006), \u2018A History of Contemporary Political Economy and Post-Modernism\u2019, Review of Radical Political Economics vol.38 no.4 [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0486613406293217<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. & Papadatos D. (2007), \u2018Reform, Reform the Reforms or Simply Regression? The 'Washington Consensus' and its Critics\u2019, Bulletin of Political Economy vol.1 no.1 [https://ideas.repec.org/p/pra/mprapa/19735.html<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. & Ioannides A. (2007), \u2018Overworked Greeks? Working time trends in Greece\u2019, Asian-African Journal of Economics and Econometrics vol.7 no.1-2 [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/40842984_Overworked_Greeks_Working_time_trends_in_Greece<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2010), \u2018Development and crises: The turbulent course of Greek capitalism\u2019 in the collective volume Topos (2010), The chart of crisis: The end of self-deceit, Athens: Topos Publishers (in Greek).\n* Ioannides A. & Mavroudeas S. (2010), \u2018Work more or work harder? The length and the intensity of work in Marx\u2019s \u2018Capital\u2019, Science & Society, vol.74 no.1 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/40404662?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2011), \u2018The Regulation Approach\u2019 in Fine B. & Saad-Filho A. (eds.) Companion to Marxist Economics, Edward Elgar.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2011), \u2018The Social Structures of Accumulation approach\u2019 in Fine B. & Saad-Filho A. (eds.) Companion to Marxist Economics, Edward Elgar.\n* Ioannides A. & Mavroudeas S. (2011), \u2018Duration, Intensity and Productivity of Labour and the Distinction between Absolute and Relative Surplus-Value\u2019, Review of Political Economy, vol.23 no.3 [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/09538259.2011.583833<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Ioannides A. & Mavroudeas S. (2011), \u2018A model for the relationship between working time and the intensity of labour\u2019, Bulletin of Political Economy vol.5 no.2.\n* Mavroudeas S. & Papadatos D. (2012), \u2018Financial Regulation in the light of the current global economic crisis\u2019, International Critical Thought vol.2 no.4 [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/21598282.2012.730381<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2013), \u2018Development and Crisis: The Turbulent Course of Greek Capitalism\u2019, International Critical Thought vol.3 no.3 [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/21598282.2013.818090<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Gialis S. & Mavroudeas S. (2014), \u2018Virtual Water: more heat than light?\u2019, Capitalism Nature Socialism vol.5 no.2 [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10455752.2013.877512<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2013), \u2018Teaching Political Economy and Marxism at an introductory level: A view from Greece\u2019, International Journal of Pluralism and Economics Education vol.4 no.3.\n* Mavroudeas S. (2014) ed., Greek capitalism in crisis: Marxist Analyses, London: Routledge [https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/9781317756149<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Ioannides A., Oxouzi E. & Mavroudeas S. (2014), \u2018All work and no ... pay? Unpaid overtime in Greece: determining factors and theoretical explanations\u2019, Industrial Relations Journal vol.45 no.1 [https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/irj.12041<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n* Mavroudeas S. (2011), 'The Limits of Regulation: A Critical Analysis of Capitalist Development', Cheltenham: Edward Elgar [https://www.e-elgar.com/shop/the-limits-of-regulation?___website=uk_warehouse<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2016), \u2018The Greek crisis: a structural or a conjunctural crisis?\u2019 in Subasat T. (ed.) The Great Financial Meltdown: Systemic, Conjunctural or Policy-Created? New Directions in Modern Economics series, Cheltenham: Edward Elgar [https://www.e-elgar.com/shop/the-great-financial-meltdown<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2017), \u2018Is Cartelier\u2019s Monetary Approach a Convincing Alternative to the Labour Theory of Value? A Comment\u2019, Stavros Mavroudeas, ''Economic Thought'' vol.6 no.2, October [http://et.worldeconomicsassociation.org/papers/is-carteliers-monetary-approach-a-convincing-alternative-to-the-labour-theory-of-value-a-comment/<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2017), \u2018Troika\u2019s Economic Adjustment Programmes for Greece: Why do they Systematically Fail\u2019 in Marangos, J., (ed.), ''The Internal Impact and External Influence of the Greek Financial Crisis,'' Palgrave Macmillan, New York [https://www.palgrave.com/gp/book/9783319602004<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2018), \u2018Competing explanations and strategies for the Greek crisis and the problem of the productive model\u2019 in Fouskas V. & Dimoulas K. (eds), ''Greece in the 21st Century. The Politics and Economics of a Crisis'', Routledge [https://www.routledge.com/Greece-in-the-21st-Century-The-Politics-and-Economics-of-a-Crisis/Fouskas-Dimoulas/p/book/9781857438673<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2018), \u2018Economic Adjustment Programmes for Greece: Origins, Structure, Deficiencies and Systematic Failures\u2019 in Anastasios Karasavvoglou, Sre\u0107ko Goi\u0107, Persefoni Polychronidou, Delias Pavlos (eds.), ''Economy, Finance and Business in Southeastern and Central Europe - Proceedings of the 8th International Conference on the Economies of the Balkan and Eastern European Countries in the Changing World (EBEEC)'' in Split, Croatia, 2016, Springer [https://www.springer.com/la/book/9783319703763<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. & Seretis S. (2018), \u2018Imperialist exploitation and the Greek crisis\u2019, ''East-West Journal of Economics and Business'', Vol. XXI \u2013 2018, Nos 1-2 [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/328654460_IMPERIALIST_EXPLOITATION_AND_THE_GREEK_CRISIS<nowiki>].</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2018), \u2018The Greek crisis: Causes and Alternative Strategies\u2019 in Sotiris P. (ed.), ''Crisis, Movement, Strategy: The Greek experience,'' Historical Materialism series, Leiden: Brill [https://brill.com/abstract/title/26716<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. & Papadatos F. (2018), \u2018Is the Financialisation Hypothesis a theoretical blind alley?\u2019, World Review of Political Economy vol.9 no.4 [https://stavrosmavroudeas.wordpress.com/2020/03/11/is-the-financialization-hypothesis-a-theoretical-blind-alley-s-mavroudeas-d-papadatos-world-review-of-political-economy/<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2019), \u2018De-globalisation and the Return of the Theory of Imperialism\u2019, in Kaoru Natsuda K. et al (eds.), ''Globalisation and Public Policy'', London: IJOPEC [https://stavrosmavroudeas.wordpress.com/2019/10/04/de-globalisation-and-the-return-of-the-theory-of-imperialism-s-mavroudeas/<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2019), \u2018The Financialisation Hypothesis and Marxism: a positive contribution or a Trojan Horse?\u2019 in Proceedings of the SECOND WORLD CONGRESS ON MARXISM \u2018Marxism and the current world and China\u2019, Peking University [https://stavrosmavroudeas.wordpress.com/2018/05/09/the-financialisation-hypothesis-and-marxism-a-positive-contribution-or-a-trojan-horse-s-mavroudeas-2nd-world-congress-on-marxism-peking-university-5-6-may-2018/<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n*Mavroudeas S. (2019), \u2018Comment on Miguel Ramirez\u2019s paper, \u201cCredit, Indebtedness and Speculation in Marx\u2019s Political Economy\u201d\u2019 ''Economic Thought'', vol.8 no.2, [http://www.worldeconomicsassociation.org/files/journals/economicthought/WEA-ET-8-2-Mavroudeas.pdf<nowiki>]</nowiki> <br />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://stavrosmavroudeas.wordpress.com Stavros Mavroudeas homepage]\n*[https://220.academia.edu/StavrosMavroudeas Academia page]\n* [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Stavros_Mavroudeas Researchgate page]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mavroudeas, Stavros}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Athens]]\n[[Category:Greek economists]]\n[[Category:National and Kapodistrian University of Athens alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Birkbeck, University of London]]\n", "name_user": "Steve Mavro", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stavros_Mavroudeas"}
{"title_page": "Robert Persons", "text_new": "{{short description|English Jesuit priest}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n[[File:Portrait of P. Robertus Personius (4671756).jpg|thumb|Engraving of Robert Persons {{circa|1640}}]]\n\n'''Robert Persons''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Society of Jesus|SJ]]}} (24 June 1546&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;15 April 1610),<ref name=\"DNB\" /> later known as '''Robert Parsons''', was an English [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] priest. He was a major figure in establishing the 16th-century \"English Mission\" of the [[Society of Jesus]].\n\n==Early life==\nRobert Persons was born at [[Nether Stowey]], [[Somerset]] to [[yeoman]] parents. Through the favour of local parson named John Hayward, a former monk, he was educated in 1562 at [[St. Mary's Hall, Oxford]]. After completing his degrees with distinction, he became a fellow and tutor at [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol]] in 1568.<ref name=pollen>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11729a.htm Pollen, John Hungerford. \"Robert Persons.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 25 March 2016</ref>\n\n==College fellow and priest==\nAs a Fellow of Balliol College, Persons clashed with the Master there, [[Adam Squire]], and also the academic and Roman Catholic priest [[Christopher Bagshaw]].<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Parsons, Robert (1546-1610)|volume=43}}</ref> On 13 February 1574, he was subsequently forced to resign. Through discussion and encouraged by pupillage with [[William Good (Jesuit)|Father William Good, SJ]], he travelled overseas to become a Jesuit priest at St Paul's, Rome on 3 July 1575.\n\n==English mission: 1580\u20131581==\nPersons accompanied [[Edmund Campion]] on his mission to fellow English Catholics in 1580. The Jesuit General, [[Everard Mercurian]], had been reluctant to involve the Society directly in English ecumenical affairs. He was persuaded by an Italian Jesuit provincial, and later by Superior General [[Claudio Acquaviva]], after [[William Allen (cardinal)|William Cardinal Allen]] had found Mercurian resistant to change in October 1579.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> Persons fast tracked English recruits to the Jesuits, and planned to set up cooperation with the remaining English [[secular clergy]]. He became impatient with Father Good's approach to the situation. Campion was much less of an enthusiast than he was.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA124|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|page=124 note 22}}</ref>\n\nThe mission was immediately compromised as [[Pope Gregory XIII|the pope]] had sent a separate group to the Jesuit mission, to support the Irish rebel, [[James FitzMaurice FitzGerald]]. Persons and Campion only learned of this event in [[Reims]] while they were en route to England. After the initial invasion force under the mercenary [[Thomas Stukley]] had achieved nothing successful in 1578, the intervention under FitzGerald caused the English authorities to monitor the [[recusancy|recusants]] closely, and try to finance the campaign against the papal forces with exactions from them.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA259|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|page=259}}</ref> Campion and Persons crossed separately into England.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nIn June 1580 [[Thomas Pounde]], then in the [[Marshalsea Prison]], went to speak to Persons. This action then resulted in a petition from Pounde to the Privy Council to allow a disputation where the Jesuits would take on [[Robert Crowley (printer)|Robert Crowley]] and [[Henry Tripp]], who used to preach to the [[Marshalsea]] inmates. Campion and Persons also prepared their own personal statements, to be kept in reserve. The immediate consequence was that Pounde was then transferred to [[Bishop's Stortford Castle]]; but the prepared statement by Campion was later circulated soon after his capture.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=69038|title=Pounde, Thomas|first=Thomas M.|last=McCoog}}</ref>\n\nMuch of the time Persons spent in England was taken up with covert printing, and pamphleteering. He made his negative view on church [[Papist|papism]] clear to the local Catholic clergy, before a synod in [[Southwark]]. The secret printing press needed to be relocated, moving it in early 1581 to [[Stonor Park]]. Campion was captured in July of that year; and then [[Stephen Brinkley]], who ran the printing press, was taken captive in August. Quite soon after that date Persons left for France.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> His underlying strategy of trying to embarrass the English government by demanding a forum for his ideals was consistent with the general approach of Allen and Persons, but met with much criticism from the Catholic members. Allen and Parsons persisted with their demand for another two years, but Jesuit opinion was against further confrontation. Campion was forced into disputation in the [[Tower of London]] under adverse conditions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA137|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|pages=137\u20138}}</ref> When Persons left England, he was never to return.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==To the Armada==\nPersons spent the winter of 1581\u201382 at [[Rouen]], and embarked on writing projects. He was in close contact with [[Henry I, Duke of Guise]], and through the Duke founded a school for English boys at [[Eu, Seine-Maritime|Eu]], on the coast to the north-east. [[William Creighton (Jesuit)|Father William Creighton, SJ]], was on the way to Scotland. He arrived in January 1582 and was briefed by Persons and the duke. In April Creighton returned with word from [[Esm\u00e9 Stewart, 1st Duke of Lennox]]; and they went to Paris to confer with [[William Allen (cardinal)|William Allen]], [[James Beaton (archbishop of Glasgow)|James Beaton]] and Claude Mathieu, Jesuit provincial in France, on his military plans and the imprisoned [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. The scheme, which Persons supported confidently, advanced further, but was stopped after the [[raid of Ruthven]] of August 1582. One consequence was that Allen was made Cardinal, as Persons had recommended.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nA new enterprise was projected for September 1583, this time through England. Persons was sent by the Duke of Guise with written instructions to Rome. He returned to [[Flanders]], and stayed for some time at the court of the [[Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma|Duke of Parma]]. The discovery of the [[Throckmorton Plot]] disrupted the plan, and the Duke of Guise became absorbed in French domestic affairs. [[Philip II of Spain]] took over the lead, placed the Duke of Parma in charge, and limited involvement to Persons, Allen, and Hew Owen.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIt was during this period that Persons was involved in the work later known as ''[[Leicester's Commonwealth]]''. Distributed covertly, it came to light in 1584. Persons is now generally thought not to be the author.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> The British historian John Bossy, from the University of York, is inclined to disagree.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA146|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|page=146}}</ref>\n\nThere is a scholarly consensus that the intention was to affect French domestic politics, strengthening the Guise faction against Anglophiles. Correspondingly his own standing suffered in some quarters.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> Claudio Acquaviva by the end of the year was concerned that the Jesuit strategies for France and the English mission would turn out to be inconsistent in the longer term, and consulted Pope Gregory XIII on the matter. Persons as his subordinate had been told to drop plans to assassinate Elizabeth.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA155|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|pages=155\u20137}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1585, [[Pope Sixtus V]] succeeded Pope Gregory XIII, and Persons and Allen went to Rome; Persons was still there when the [[Spanish Armada]] sailed in 1588. At this period Allen and Persons made a close study of the [[succession to Elizabeth I of England]], working with noted genealogist Robert Heighinton.<ref name=\"DNB\"/> Persons took his vows of final profession in the Jesuits in Rome on 7 May 1587.\n\n==Later life==\nPersons was sent to Spain at the close of 1588 to conciliate [[Philip II of Spain]], who was offended with [[Claudio Acquaviva]]. Persons was successful, and then made use of the royal favour to found the seminaries of [[English College, Valladolid|Valladolid]], [[English College of St Gregory|Seville]], and [[Madrid]] (1589, 1592, 1598) and the residences of [[San-Lucar]] and of [[Lisbon]] (which became a college in 1622). He then succeeded in establishing at [[Saint-Omer|St Omer]] (1594) a larger institution to which the boys from Eu were transferred. It is the institutional ancestor of [[Stonyhurst College]].<ref name=pollen/>\n\nIn 1596, in [[Seville]], he wrote ''Memorial for the Reformation of England'', which gave in some detail a blueprint for the kind of society England was to become after its return to the faith. He had hoped to succeed [[William Allen (cardinal)|Allen]] as Cardinal on the latter's death. Unsuccessful, he was rewarded with the rectorship of the [[English College at Rome|English College]] in Rome, where he died at the age of 63.\n\n==Works==\nPersons's published works were:<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n* ''A brief discovrs contayning certayne reasons why Catholiques refuse to goe to Church . . . dedicated by I. H. to the queenes most excellent Maiestie. Doway, John Lyon'' [London], 1580. This work was from a clandestine press in London, printed as a consequence of decisions at a synod at [[Southwark]] held not long after Persons and Campion landed. It was aimed at implementing a 1563 declaration of [[Pope Pius IV]] that Catholics should not mix with heretics.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Peter Lake|author2=Michael C. Questier|title=Conformity and Orthodoxy in the English Church: c. 1560 - 1660|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QGuVwbcmaMC&pg=PA214|accessdate=16 July 2013|year=2000|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=978-0-85115-797-9|page=214}}</ref>\n* ''A Discouerie of I. Nicols, minister, misreported a Jesuite, latelye recanted in the Tower of London. Doway'' [London], 1580. Printed by Persons at [[Stonor Park]], it concerned a renegade Catholic priest.<ref name=\"Houliston2007\">{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA28|accessdate=16 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|page=28}}</ref>\n* ''A briefe censure upon two bookes written in answer to M. Edmund Campians offer of disputation. Doway, John Lyon'' [really at Mr. Brooke's house near London], 1581. Against [[William Charke]] and [[Meredith Hanmer]], who had engaged in controversy with Campion.<ref name=\"Houliston2007\"/>\n* ''De persecvtione Anglicana commentariolus a collegio Anglicano Romano hoc anno 1582 in vrbe editus et iam denuo Ingolstadii excusus . . . anno eodem.'' Also, ''De persecutione Angl. libellus, Rom\u00e6, ex typogr. G. Ferrarii, 1582.''\n[[File:De persecutione dedication.jpg|thumb|Dedication of ''De persecvtione Anglicana commentariolus'' (1582) by Robert Persons to Cardinal [[Filippo Boncompagni]]]]\n* ''A Defence of the censvre gyven vpon tvvo bookes of William Charke and Meredith Hanmer, mynysters'', 1582.\n* ''The first booke of the Christian exercise, appertayning to Resolution'' [Rouen], 1582. Preface signed R. P. Afterwards much enlarged, under the title of ''A Christian Directorie, guiding men to their saluation, devided into three books, anno 1585'', and often reprinted (40 editions by 1640). This was a major devotional work in English, and was soon adapted by [[Edmund Bunny]] to Protestant needs.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Parsons|title=Robert Persons S.J.: The Christian Directory (1582): The First Booke of the Christian Exercise, Appertayning to Resolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U7V4hjea5-oC&pg=PR11|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=1998|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11009-0|page=xi}}</ref>\n* ''Relacion de algunos martyres ... en Inglaterra, traduzida en Castellano'', 1590. [[William Thomas Lowndes]] considered that Persons was the probable author of this work on the [[List of Catholic martyrs of the English Reformation|English martyrs]], as well as its translator into Spanish.<ref>{{cite book|author=William Thomas Lowndes|title=The Bibliographer's Manual of English Literature: L - R|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JElJAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1227|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=1834|publisher=Pickering|page=1227}}</ref>\n* ''Elizabeth\u00e6 Angli\u00e6 regin\u00e6 h\u00e6resim Calvinianam propvgnantis s\u00e6vissimvm in Catholicos sui regni Edictvm . . . promulgatum Londini 29 Nouembris 1591. Cum responsione ad singula capita . . . per D. Andream Philopatrum, presb. ac theol. Romanum, Lvgduni'', 1592. This Latin work was a detailed rebuttal of a proclamation of Elizabeth I of October 1591, against seminary priests and Jesuits.<ref>[[Ethelred Luke Taunton]], ''The History of the Jesuits in England, 1580-1773'' (1901), p. 148; [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924029413600#page/n173/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref>\n* ''[[A Conference about the Next Succession|A Conference abovt the next svccession to the crowne of Ingland, divided into tvvo partes]]. . . . Where vnto is added a new & perfect arbor or genealogie.... Published by R. Doleman. Imprinted at N. [St. Omer] with license'', 1594. The book suggests [[Isabella Clara Eugenia]] of Spain as the proper successor.<ref>{{cite book|author=Clark Hulse|title=Elizabeth I: Ruler and Legend|url=https://archive.org/details/elizabethirulerl0000huls|url-access=registration|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=2003|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-07161-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/elizabethirulerl0000huls/page/102 102]}}</ref>\n[[File:Succession to the crowne of Ingland Arbella.jpg|thumb|left|Page from Robert Persons's anonymous work of 1594 on the future succession to Elizabeth I, discussing [[Lady Arbella Stuart]]]]\n* ''A Memoriall for the Reformation of England conteyning certayne notes and advertisements which seeme might be proposed in the first parliament and nationall councell of our country after God of his mercie shall restore it to the catholique faith [...]; gathered and set downe by R. P.,'' 1596. Left in manuscript, the circulation having included Isabella Clara Eugenia.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=21474|title=Persons, Robert|first=Victor|last=Houliston}}</ref> It was first published in 1690 by [[Edward Gee]], as ''Jesuits Memorial for the intended Reformation of England''.\n* ''A Temperate Ward-word to the turbulent and seditious Wach-word of Sir Francis Hastinges, knight, who indevoreth to slander the whole Catholique cause.... By N. D.'' 1599. Controversy with [[Sir Francis Hastings]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA95|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|page=95}}</ref>\n* ''The Copie of a letter written by F. Rob. Persons, the jesuite, 9 Oct 1599, to M. D. Bis[op] and M. Cha[rnock], two banished and consigned priests... for presuming to goe to Rome in the affaires of the Catholicke church''. This was printed in ''Copies of certain Discourses'', Roane, 1601, pp.&nbsp;49\u201367, edited by [[William Bishop (bishop)|William Bishop]], one of the appellants in the [[Archpriest controversy]]; the other appellant named is Robert Charnock.<ref>[[Thomas Graves Law]], ''A Historical Sketch of the Conflicts between Jesuits and Seculars in the Reign of Queen Elizabeth'' (1889), p. lxxxvi; [https://archive.org/stream/ahistoricalsket00bagsgoog#page/n98/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref><ref>Thomas Graves Law, ''The Archpriest Controversy'' vol. 1 (1838), p. 235 note; [https://archive.org/stream/archpriestcont01camduoft#page/234/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref>\n* ''A Briefe Apologie or Defence of the Catholike ecclesiastical hierarchie & subordination in England, erected these later yeares by our holy Father ... and impugned by certayne libels printed ... by some vnquiet persons under the name of priests of the seminaries. Written ... by priests vnited in due subordination to the right rev. Archpriest'' [early in 1602]. Anti-appellant work in the Archpriest controversy.<ref>{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YFgRCTMoHtUC&pg=PA117|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 October 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-8668-2|page=117}}</ref>\n* ''An Appendix to the Apologie lately set forth for the defence of the hierarchie'' [1602]. A Latin translation of the 'Appendix' was also published in the same year.\n* ''A Manifestation of the great folly and bad spirit of certayne in England calling themselves secular priestes, who set forth dayly most infamous and contumelious libels against worthy men of their own religion. By priests liuing in obedience,'' 1602. Anti-appellant work in the Archpriest controversy.<ref name=\"Houliston2007\"/>\n* ''The Warn-word to Sir F. Hastings Wastword: conteyning the issue of three former treatises, the Watchword, the Ward-word, and the Wastword . . . Whereunto is adjoyned a brief rejection of an insolent . . . minister masked with the letters O. E.'' (i.e. [[Matthew Sutcliffe]]). ''By N. D.'', 1602.\n* ''A Treatise of Three Conversions of England ... divided into three parts. The former two whereof are handled in this book. . . . By N. D., author of the Ward-word'', 1603. Polemical work against [[John Foxe]]'s anti-Catholic reading of history.<ref name=\"Houliston2007a\">{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA93|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|page=93}}</ref>\n* ''The Third part of a treatise intituled of the Three Conversions of England. Conteyning an examen of the Calendar or Catalogue of Protestant saints . . . devised by Fox. By N. D.'' (preface dated November 1603).\n* ''A Review of ten pvblike dispvtations or conferences held within the compasse of foure yeares vnder K. Edward and Qu. Mary. By N.D.'', 1604 (separately paged but issued with third part of '''Three Conversions'').\n[[File:Ten Publike Disputations page 33.png|thumb|Page from ''A Review of ten pvblike dispvtations or conferences'' (1604) by Robert Persons. The disputations were those involving [[Peter Martyr Vermigli]] (1549); [[John Madew]] around the same time; [[Andrew Perne]] and [[Edmund Grindal]] (23 June 1549); Perne again; public determination by [[Nicholas Ridley (martyr)|Nicholas Ridley]]; [[Martin Bucer]], still in 1549; [[Hugh Weston]] in [[St Paul's Cathedral]] on 18 October 1553; and the three days in 1554 of [[Thomas Cranmer]], [[Hugh Latimer]] and Ridley.]]\n* ''A Relation of the triall made before the king of France upon the yeare 1600 betweene the bishop of \u00c9vreux and the L. Plessis Mornay. Newly reviewed . . . with a defence thereof against the impugnations both of the L. Plessis in France and O. E. in England. By N. D.,'' 1604. On the debate at [[Fontainebleu]] on 4 May 1600 between [[Jacques-Davy Duperron]] and [[Philippe de Mornay]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Mack P. Holt|title=Adaptations of Calvinism in Reformation Europe: Essays in Honour of Brian G. Armstrong|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SwI47ys7HIAC&pg=PA174|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-8693-4|page=174}}</ref>\n* ''An Ansvvere to the fifth part of Reportes lately set forth by Syr Edward Cooke knight, the King's attorney generall, concerning the ancient and moderne municipal lawes of England, which do appertayne to spiritual power and jurisdiction. By a Catholick Deuyne [St. Omer],'' 1606. Polemical work against [[Sir Edward Coke]]'s anti-Catholic reading of the [[common law]].<ref name=\"Houliston2007a\"/>\n* ''Qu\u00e6stiones du\u00e6: quarum 1a est, an liceat Catholicis Anglicanis . . . Protestantium ecclesias vel preces adire: 2da utrum non si precibus ut concionibus saltem h\u00e6reticis . . . licite possint interesse easque audire'' [St. Omer], 1607. [[Pope Paul V]] had repeated the declaration against Catholics attending Protestant churches.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Peter Lake|author2=Michael C. Questier|title=Conformity and Orthodoxy in the English Church: C. 1560 - 1660|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QGuVwbcmaMC&pg=PA231|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=2000|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=978-0-85115-797-9|page=231}}</ref>\n* ''A treatise tending to mitigation tovvards Catholicke-subiectes in England. . . . Against the seditious wrytings of Thomas Morton, minister. By P. R.'', 1607 (the first part is on [[rebellion]], the second concerns the doctrine of [[mental reservation|equivocation]]). Written in the aftermath of the [[Gunpowder Plot]], the work argues for [[religious toleration]] in England.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Roger D. Sell|author2=Anthony W. Johnson|title=Writing and Religion in England 1558-1689: Studies in Community-Making and Cultural Memory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dB-2ZzlXyBMC&pg=PA59|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 April 2013|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-4094-7559-0|page=59}}</ref>\n* ''The Judgment of a Catholicke Englishman liuing in banishment for his religion . . . concerning a late booke [by K. James] entituled: Triplici nodo triplex cuneus, or an apologie for the oath of allegiance. . . . wherin the said oath is shewn to be vnlawful. . . .'' 1608. Contribution to the [[allegiance oath controversy]].<ref name=\"Houliston2007b\">{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA142|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|pages=142\u20133}}</ref>\n* ''Dutifull and respective considerations upon foure severall heads . . . proposed by the high and mighty Prince James ... in his late book of Premonition to all Christian princes. . . . By a late minister and preacher in England'', St. Omer, 1609 (written by Persons for [[Humphrey Leech]], under whose name it appeared). Argues for tolerance for Catholicism in its integrity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA136|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|page=136}}</ref>\n* ''A quiet and sober reckoning with M. Thomas Morton, somewhat set in choler by his advesary P. R. ... There is also adioyned a peece of reckoning with Syr Edward Cooke, now LL. Chief Justice'', 1609. Against [[Thomas Morton (bishop)|Thomas Morton]], who had argued that recusant Catholics were necessarily disloyal, Persons argued that Catholicism could co-exist peacefully with the Church of England.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n* ''A Discussion of the answer of M. William Barlow, Doctor of Diuinity, to the book intituled, The Judgment of a Catholic Englishman, St. Omers'', 1612 (published after Persons's death, with a supplement by [[Thomas Fitzherbert]]). Reply to [[William Barlow (bishop of Lincoln)|William Barlow]] in the allegiance oath controversy.<ref name=\"Houliston2007b\"/>\n* ''Epitome controversiarum hujus temporis'' was a manuscript preserved in Balliol College.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n===Misattributed===\n''An Apologicall Epistle: directed to the right honorable lords and others of her majesties privie counsell. Serving as well for a preface to a Booke entituled A Resolution of Religion'' [signed R. B.], Antwerp, 1601, is by [[Richard Broughton (priest)|Richard Broughton]] rather than Persons (as the ''Dictionary of National Biography'' says).<ref>{{cite book|author=Molly Murray|title=The Poetics of Conversion in Early Modern English Literature: Verse and Change from Donne to Dryden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=POPqPXI4U7YC&pg=PA89|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=15 October 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-11387-8|page=89 note 77}}</ref> Some works against [[Thomas Bell (Catholic priest)|Thomas Bell]] were thought to be by Persons (as in the DNB), but were in fact by Philip Woodward.<ref name=\"Questier1996\">{{cite book|author=Michael C. Questier|title=Conversion, Politics and Religion in England, 1580-1625|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JczSYC5riR4C&pg=PA48|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=13 July 1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-44214-5|page=48 note 42}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Suellen Mutchow Towers|title=The control of religious printing in early Stuart England|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8u87-D44jwC&pg=PA98|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=2003|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-0-85115-939-3|page=98}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Frederick Wilse Bateson|title=The Cambridge bibliography of English literature. 2. 1660-1800|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ebM6AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA327|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=1940|publisher=CUP Archive|page=327|id=GGKEY:QNELW3AWW36}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Thomas Abell]]\n* [[William Allen (cardinal)]]\n* [[Christopher Bagshawe]]\n* [[Pacificus Baker]]\n* [[Robert Bellarmine]]\n* [[Edmund Campion]]\n* [[Richard Challoner]]\n* [[Johann Eck]]\n* [[John Fisher]]\n* [[Antony Hickey]]\n* [[Angelus of St. Francis Mason]]\n* [[Thomas More]]\n* [[Gregorio Panzani]]\n* [[Reginald Pole]]\n* [[John Punch (theologian)|John Punch]]\n* [[John Proctor (historian)|John Proctor]]\n* [[Luke Wadding]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last=Hogge|first=Alice|title=God's Secret Agents: Queen Elizabeth's Forbidden Priests and the Hatching of the Gunpowder Plot|date=2006|publisher=Harper Perennial|isbn=978-0007156382}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sullivan|first=Ceri|title=Dismembered Rhetoric: English Recusant Writing, 1580 to 1603|date=1995|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson University Press|isbn=978-1611471168}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Parsons, Robert (1546-1610)|volume=43}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Catholicism|England}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Persons, Robert}}\n[[Category:1546 births]]\n[[Category:1610 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century English Jesuits]]\n[[Category:17th-century English Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Mary Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Italy]]\n[[Category:Early modern Christian devotional writers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:People from Sedgemoor (district)]]\n[[Category:Rectors of the English College, Rome]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n[[File:Portrait of P. Robertus Personius (4671756).jpg|thumb|Engraving of Robert Persons {{circa|1640}}]]\n\n'''Robert Persons''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Society of Jesus|SJ]]}} (24 June 1546&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;15 April 1610),<ref name=\"DNB\" /> later known as '''Robert Parsons''', was an English [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] priest. He was a major figure in establishing the 16th-century \"English Mission\" of the [[Society of Jesus]].\n\n==Early life==\nRobert Persons was born at [[Nether Stowey]], [[Somerset]] to [[yeoman]] parents. Through the favour of local parson named John Hayward, a former monk, he was educated in 1562 at [[St. Mary's Hall, Oxford]]. After completing his degrees with distinction, he became a fellow and tutor at [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol]] in 1568.<ref name=pollen>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11729a.htm Pollen, John Hungerford. \"Robert Persons.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 25 March 2016</ref>\n\n==College fellow and priest==\nAs a Fellow of Balliol College, Persons clashed with the Master there, [[Adam Squire]], and also the academic and Roman Catholic priest [[Christopher Bagshaw]].<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Parsons, Robert (1546-1610)|volume=43}}</ref> On 13 February 1574, he was subsequently forced to resign. Through discussion and encouraged by pupillage with [[William Good (Jesuit)|Father William Good, SJ]], he travelled overseas to become a Jesuit priest at St Paul's, Rome on 3 July 1575.\n\n==English mission: 1580\u20131581==\nPersons accompanied [[Edmund Campion]] on his mission to fellow English Catholics in 1580. The Jesuit General, [[Everard Mercurian]], had been reluctant to involve the Society directly in English ecumenical affairs. He was persuaded by an Italian Jesuit provincial, and later by Superior General [[Claudio Acquaviva]], after [[William Allen (cardinal)|William Cardinal Allen]] had found Mercurian resistant to change in October 1579.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> Persons fast tracked English recruits to the Jesuits, and planned to set up cooperation with the remaining English [[secular clergy]]. He became impatient with Father Good's approach to the situation. Campion was much less of an enthusiast than he was.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA124|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|page=124 note 22}}</ref>\n\nThe mission was immediately compromised as [[Pope Gregory XIII|the pope]] had sent a separate group to the Jesuit mission, to support the Irish rebel, [[James FitzMaurice FitzGerald]]. Persons and Campion only learned of this event in [[Reims]] while they were en route to England. After the initial invasion force under the mercenary [[Thomas Stukley]] had achieved nothing successful in 1578, the intervention under FitzGerald caused the English authorities to monitor the [[recusancy|recusants]] closely, and try to finance the campaign against the papal forces with exactions from them.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA259|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|page=259}}</ref> Campion and Persons crossed separately into England.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nIn June 1580 [[Thomas Pounde]], then in the [[Marshalsea Prison]], went to speak to Persons. This action then resulted in a petition from Pounde to the Privy Council to allow a disputation where the Jesuits would take on [[Robert Crowley (printer)|Robert Crowley]] and [[Henry Tripp]], who used to preach to the [[Marshalsea]] inmates. Campion and Persons also prepared their own personal statements, to be kept in reserve. The immediate consequence was that Pounde was then transferred to [[Bishop's Stortford Castle]]; but the prepared statement by Campion was later circulated soon after his capture.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=69038|title=Pounde, Thomas|first=Thomas M.|last=McCoog}}</ref>\n\nMuch of the time Persons spent in England was taken up with covert printing, and pamphleteering. He made his negative view on church [[Papist|papism]] clear to the local Catholic clergy, before a synod in [[Southwark]]. The secret printing press needed to be relocated, moving it in early 1581 to [[Stonor Park]]. Campion was captured in July of that year; and then [[Stephen Brinkley]], who ran the printing press, was taken captive in August. Quite soon after that date Persons left for France.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> His underlying strategy of trying to embarrass the English government by demanding a forum for his ideals was consistent with the general approach of Allen and Persons, but met with much criticism from the Catholic members. Allen and Parsons persisted with their demand for another two years, but Jesuit opinion was against further confrontation. Campion was forced into disputation in the [[Tower of London]] under adverse conditions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA137|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|pages=137\u20138}}</ref> When Persons left England, he was never to return.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==To the Armada==\nPersons spent the winter of 1581\u201382 at [[Rouen]], and embarked on writing projects. He was in close contact with [[Henry I, Duke of Guise]], and through the Duke founded a school for English boys at [[Eu, Seine-Maritime|Eu]], on the coast to the north-east. [[William Creighton (Jesuit)|Father William Creighton, SJ]], was on the way to Scotland. He arrived in January 1582 and was briefed by Persons and the duke. In April Creighton returned with word from [[Esm\u00e9 Stewart, 1st Duke of Lennox]]; and they went to Paris to confer with [[William Allen (cardinal)|William Allen]], [[James Beaton (archbishop of Glasgow)|James Beaton]] and Claude Mathieu, Jesuit provincial in France, on his military plans and the imprisoned [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. The scheme, which Persons supported confidently, advanced further, but was stopped after the [[raid of Ruthven]] of August 1582. One consequence was that Allen was made Cardinal, as Persons had recommended.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nA new enterprise was projected for September 1583, this time through England. Persons was sent by the Duke of Guise with written instructions to Rome. He returned to [[Flanders]], and stayed for some time at the court of the [[Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma|Duke of Parma]]. The discovery of the [[Throckmorton Plot]] disrupted the plan, and the Duke of Guise became absorbed in French domestic affairs. [[Philip II of Spain]] took over the lead, placed the Duke of Parma in charge, and limited involvement to Persons, Allen, and Hew Owen.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIt was during this period that Persons was involved in the work later known as ''[[Leicester's Commonwealth]]''. Distributed covertly, it came to light in 1584. Persons is now generally thought not to be the author.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> The British historian John Bossy, from the University of York, is inclined to disagree.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA146|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|page=146}}</ref>\n\nThere is a scholarly consensus that the intention was to affect French domestic politics, strengthening the Guise faction against Anglophiles. Correspondingly his own standing suffered in some quarters.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> Claudio Acquaviva by the end of the year was concerned that the Jesuit strategies for France and the English mission would turn out to be inconsistent in the longer term, and consulted Pope Gregory XIII on the matter. Persons as his subordinate had been told to drop plans to assassinate Elizabeth.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. McCoog|author2=Campion Hall (University of Oxford)|title=The Reckoned Expense: Edmund Campion and the Early English Jesuits : Essays in Celebration of the First Centenary of Campion Hall, Oxford (1896-1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f01RY4H7MfoC&pg=PA155|accessdate=25 May 2012|year=1996|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-0-85115-590-6|pages=155\u20137}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1585, [[Pope Sixtus V]] succeeded Pope Gregory XIII, and Persons and Allen went to Rome; Persons was still there when the [[Spanish Armada]] sailed in 1588. At this period Allen and Persons made a close study of the [[succession to Elizabeth I of England]], working with noted genealogist Robert Heighinton.<ref name=\"DNB\"/> Persons took his vows of final profession in the Jesuits in Rome on 7 May 1587.\n\n==Later life==\nPersons was sent to Spain at the close of 1588 to conciliate [[Philip II of Spain]], who was offended with [[Claudio Acquaviva]]. Persons was successful, and then made use of the royal favour to found the seminaries of [[English College, Valladolid|Valladolid]], [[English College of St Gregory|Seville]], and [[Madrid]] (1589, 1592, 1598) and the residences of [[San-Lucar]] and of [[Lisbon]] (which became a college in 1622). He then succeeded in establishing at [[Saint-Omer|St Omer]] (1594) a larger institution to which the boys from Eu were transferred. It is the institutional ancestor of [[Stonyhurst College]].<ref name=pollen/>\n\nIn 1596, in [[Seville]], he wrote ''Memorial for the Reformation of England'', which gave in some detail a blueprint for the kind of society England was to become after its return to the faith. He had hoped to succeed [[William Allen (cardinal)|Allen]] as Cardinal on the latter's death. Unsuccessful, he was rewarded with the rectorship of the [[English College at Rome|English College]] in Rome, where he died at the age of 63.\n\n==Works==\nPersons's published works were:<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n* ''A brief discovrs contayning certayne reasons why Catholiques refuse to goe to Church . . . dedicated by I. H. to the queenes most excellent Maiestie. Doway, John Lyon'' [London], 1580. This work was from a clandestine press in London, printed as a consequence of decisions at a synod at [[Southwark]] held not long after Persons and Campion landed. It was aimed at implementing a 1563 declaration of [[Pope Pius IV]] that Catholics should not mix with heretics.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Peter Lake|author2=Michael C. Questier|title=Conformity and Orthodoxy in the English Church: c. 1560 - 1660|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QGuVwbcmaMC&pg=PA214|accessdate=16 July 2013|year=2000|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=978-0-85115-797-9|page=214}}</ref>\n* ''A Discouerie of I. Nicols, minister, misreported a Jesuite, latelye recanted in the Tower of London. Doway'' [London], 1580. Printed by Persons at [[Stonor Park]], it concerned a renegade Catholic priest.<ref name=\"Houliston2007\">{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA28|accessdate=16 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|page=28}}</ref>\n* ''A briefe censure upon two bookes written in answer to M. Edmund Campians offer of disputation. Doway, John Lyon'' [really at Mr. Brooke's house near London], 1581. Against [[William Charke]] and [[Meredith Hanmer]], who had engaged in controversy with Campion.<ref name=\"Houliston2007\"/>\n* ''De persecvtione Anglicana commentariolus a collegio Anglicano Romano hoc anno 1582 in vrbe editus et iam denuo Ingolstadii excusus . . . anno eodem.'' Also, ''De persecutione Angl. libellus, Rom\u00e6, ex typogr. G. Ferrarii, 1582.''\n[[File:De persecutione dedication.jpg|thumb|Dedication of ''De persecvtione Anglicana commentariolus'' (1582) by Robert Persons to Cardinal [[Filippo Boncompagni]]]]\n* ''A Defence of the censvre gyven vpon tvvo bookes of William Charke and Meredith Hanmer, mynysters'', 1582.\n* ''The first booke of the Christian exercise, appertayning to Resolution'' [Rouen], 1582. Preface signed R. P. Afterwards much enlarged, under the title of ''A Christian Directorie, guiding men to their saluation, devided into three books, anno 1585'', and often reprinted (40 editions by 1640). This was a major devotional work in English, and was soon adapted by [[Edmund Bunny]] to Protestant needs.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Parsons|title=Robert Persons S.J.: The Christian Directory (1582): The First Booke of the Christian Exercise, Appertayning to Resolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U7V4hjea5-oC&pg=PR11|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=1998|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11009-0|page=xi}}</ref>\n* ''Relacion de algunos martyres ... en Inglaterra, traduzida en Castellano'', 1590. [[William Thomas Lowndes]] considered that Persons was the probable author of this work on the [[List of Catholic martyrs of the English Reformation|English martyrs]], as well as its translator into Spanish.<ref>{{cite book|author=William Thomas Lowndes|title=The Bibliographer's Manual of English Literature: L - R|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JElJAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1227|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=1834|publisher=Pickering|page=1227}}</ref>\n* ''Elizabeth\u00e6 Angli\u00e6 regin\u00e6 h\u00e6resim Calvinianam propvgnantis s\u00e6vissimvm in Catholicos sui regni Edictvm . . . promulgatum Londini 29 Nouembris 1591. Cum responsione ad singula capita . . . per D. Andream Philopatrum, presb. ac theol. Romanum, Lvgduni'', 1592. This Latin work was a detailed rebuttal of a proclamation of Elizabeth I of October 1591, against seminary priests and Jesuits.<ref>[[Ethelred Luke Taunton]], ''The History of the Jesuits in England, 1580-1773'' (1901), p. 148; [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924029413600#page/n173/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref>\n* ''[[A Conference about the Next Succession|A Conference abovt the next svccession to the crowne of Ingland, divided into tvvo partes]]. . . . Where vnto is added a new & perfect arbor or genealogie.... Published by R. Doleman. Imprinted at N. [St. Omer] with license'', 1594. The book suggests [[Isabella Clara Eugenia]] of Spain as the proper successor.<ref>{{cite book|author=Clark Hulse|title=Elizabeth I: Ruler and Legend|url=https://archive.org/details/elizabethirulerl0000huls|url-access=registration|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=2003|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-07161-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/elizabethirulerl0000huls/page/102 102]}}</ref>\n[[File:Succession to the crowne of Ingland Arbella.jpg|thumb|left|Page from Robert Persons's anonymous work of 1594 on the future succession to Elizabeth I, discussing [[Lady Arbella Stuart]]]]\n* ''A Memoriall for the Reformation of England conteyning certayne notes and advertisements which seeme might be proposed in the first parliament and nationall councell of our country after God of his mercie shall restore it to the catholique faith [...]; gathered and set downe by R. P.,'' 1596. Left in manuscript, the circulation having included Isabella Clara Eugenia.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=21474|title=Persons, Robert|first=Victor|last=Houliston}}</ref> It was first published in 1690 by [[Edward Gee]], as ''Jesuits Memorial for the intended Reformation of England''.\n* ''A Temperate Ward-word to the turbulent and seditious Wach-word of Sir Francis Hastinges, knight, who indevoreth to slander the whole Catholique cause.... By N. D.'' 1599. Controversy with [[Sir Francis Hastings]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA95|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|page=95}}</ref>\n* ''The Copie of a letter written by F. Rob. Persons, the jesuite, 9 Oct 1599, to M. D. Bis[op] and M. Cha[rnock], two banished and consigned priests... for presuming to goe to Rome in the affaires of the Catholicke church''. This was printed in ''Copies of certain Discourses'', Roane, 1601, pp.&nbsp;49\u201367, edited by [[William Bishop (bishop)|William Bishop]], one of the appellants in the [[Archpriest controversy]]; the other appellant named is Robert Charnock.<ref>[[Thomas Graves Law]], ''A Historical Sketch of the Conflicts between Jesuits and Seculars in the Reign of Queen Elizabeth'' (1889), p. lxxxvi; [https://archive.org/stream/ahistoricalsket00bagsgoog#page/n98/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref><ref>Thomas Graves Law, ''The Archpriest Controversy'' vol. 1 (1838), p. 235 note; [https://archive.org/stream/archpriestcont01camduoft#page/234/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref>\n* ''A Briefe Apologie or Defence of the Catholike ecclesiastical hierarchie & subordination in England, erected these later yeares by our holy Father ... and impugned by certayne libels printed ... by some vnquiet persons under the name of priests of the seminaries. Written ... by priests vnited in due subordination to the right rev. Archpriest'' [early in 1602]. Anti-appellant work in the Archpriest controversy.<ref>{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YFgRCTMoHtUC&pg=PA117|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 October 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-8668-2|page=117}}</ref>\n* ''An Appendix to the Apologie lately set forth for the defence of the hierarchie'' [1602]. A Latin translation of the 'Appendix' was also published in the same year.\n* ''A Manifestation of the great folly and bad spirit of certayne in England calling themselves secular priestes, who set forth dayly most infamous and contumelious libels against worthy men of their own religion. By priests liuing in obedience,'' 1602. Anti-appellant work in the Archpriest controversy.<ref name=\"Houliston2007\"/>\n* ''The Warn-word to Sir F. Hastings Wastword: conteyning the issue of three former treatises, the Watchword, the Ward-word, and the Wastword . . . Whereunto is adjoyned a brief rejection of an insolent . . . minister masked with the letters O. E.'' (i.e. [[Matthew Sutcliffe]]). ''By N. D.'', 1602.\n* ''A Treatise of Three Conversions of England ... divided into three parts. The former two whereof are handled in this book. . . . By N. D., author of the Ward-word'', 1603. Polemical work against [[John Foxe]]'s anti-Catholic reading of history.<ref name=\"Houliston2007a\">{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA93|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|page=93}}</ref>\n* ''The Third part of a treatise intituled of the Three Conversions of England. Conteyning an examen of the Calendar or Catalogue of Protestant saints . . . devised by Fox. By N. D.'' (preface dated November 1603).\n* ''A Review of ten pvblike dispvtations or conferences held within the compasse of foure yeares vnder K. Edward and Qu. Mary. By N.D.'', 1604 (separately paged but issued with third part of '''Three Conversions'').\n[[File:Ten Publike Disputations page 33.png|thumb|Page from ''A Review of ten pvblike dispvtations or conferences'' (1604) by Robert Persons. The disputations were those involving [[Peter Martyr Vermigli]] (1549); [[John Madew]] around the same time; [[Andrew Perne]] and [[Edmund Grindal]] (23 June 1549); Perne again; public determination by [[Nicholas Ridley (martyr)|Nicholas Ridley]]; [[Martin Bucer]], still in 1549; [[Hugh Weston]] in [[St Paul's Cathedral]] on 18 October 1553; and the three days in 1554 of [[Thomas Cranmer]], [[Hugh Latimer]] and Ridley.]]\n* ''A Relation of the triall made before the king of France upon the yeare 1600 betweene the bishop of \u00c9vreux and the L. Plessis Mornay. Newly reviewed . . . with a defence thereof against the impugnations both of the L. Plessis in France and O. E. in England. By N. D.,'' 1604. On the debate at [[Fontainebleu]] on 4 May 1600 between [[Jacques-Davy Duperron]] and [[Philippe de Mornay]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Mack P. Holt|title=Adaptations of Calvinism in Reformation Europe: Essays in Honour of Brian G. Armstrong|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SwI47ys7HIAC&pg=PA174|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-8693-4|page=174}}</ref>\n* ''An Ansvvere to the fifth part of Reportes lately set forth by Syr Edward Cooke knight, the King's attorney generall, concerning the ancient and moderne municipal lawes of England, which do appertayne to spiritual power and jurisdiction. By a Catholick Deuyne [St. Omer],'' 1606. Polemical work against [[Sir Edward Coke]]'s anti-Catholic reading of the [[common law]].<ref name=\"Houliston2007a\"/>\n* ''Qu\u00e6stiones du\u00e6: quarum 1a est, an liceat Catholicis Anglicanis . . . Protestantium ecclesias vel preces adire: 2da utrum non si precibus ut concionibus saltem h\u00e6reticis . . . licite possint interesse easque audire'' [St. Omer], 1607. [[Pope Paul V]] had repeated the declaration against Catholics attending Protestant churches.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Peter Lake|author2=Michael C. Questier|title=Conformity and Orthodoxy in the English Church: C. 1560 - 1660|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QGuVwbcmaMC&pg=PA231|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=2000|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=978-0-85115-797-9|page=231}}</ref>\n* ''A treatise tending to mitigation tovvards Catholicke-subiectes in England. . . . Against the seditious wrytings of Thomas Morton, minister. By P. R.'', 1607 (the first part is on [[rebellion]], the second concerns the doctrine of [[mental reservation|equivocation]]). Written in the aftermath of the [[Gunpowder Plot]], the work argues for [[religious toleration]] in England.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Roger D. Sell|author2=Anthony W. Johnson|title=Writing and Religion in England 1558-1689: Studies in Community-Making and Cultural Memory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dB-2ZzlXyBMC&pg=PA59|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 April 2013|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-4094-7559-0|page=59}}</ref>\n* ''The Judgment of a Catholicke Englishman liuing in banishment for his religion . . . concerning a late booke [by K. James] entituled: Triplici nodo triplex cuneus, or an apologie for the oath of allegiance. . . . wherin the said oath is shewn to be vnlawful. . . .'' 1608. Contribution to the [[allegiance oath controversy]].<ref name=\"Houliston2007b\">{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA142|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|pages=142\u20133}}</ref>\n* ''Dutifull and respective considerations upon foure severall heads . . . proposed by the high and mighty Prince James ... in his late book of Premonition to all Christian princes. . . . By a late minister and preacher in England'', St. Omer, 1609 (written by Persons for [[Humphrey Leech]], under whose name it appeared). Argues for tolerance for Catholicism in its integrity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Victor Houliston|title=Catholic Resistance in Elizabethan England: Robert Persons's Jesuit Polemic, 1580-1610|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpY1LefqYDAC&pg=PA136|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-5840-5|page=136}}</ref>\n* ''A quiet and sober reckoning with M. Thomas Morton, somewhat set in choler by his advesary P. R. ... There is also adioyned a peece of reckoning with Syr Edward Cooke, now LL. Chief Justice'', 1609. Against [[Thomas Morton (bishop)|Thomas Morton]], who had argued that recusant Catholics were necessarily disloyal, Persons argued that Catholicism could co-exist peacefully with the Church of England.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n* ''A Discussion of the answer of M. William Barlow, Doctor of Diuinity, to the book intituled, The Judgment of a Catholic Englishman, St. Omers'', 1612 (published after Persons's death, with a supplement by [[Thomas Fitzherbert]]). Reply to [[William Barlow (bishop of Lincoln)|William Barlow]] in the allegiance oath controversy.<ref name=\"Houliston2007b\"/>\n* ''Epitome controversiarum hujus temporis'' was a manuscript preserved in Balliol College.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n===Misattributed===\n''An Apologicall Epistle: directed to the right honorable lords and others of her majesties privie counsell. Serving as well for a preface to a Booke entituled A Resolution of Religion'' [signed R. B.], Antwerp, 1601, is by [[Richard Broughton (priest)|Richard Broughton]] rather than Persons (as the ''Dictionary of National Biography'' says).<ref>{{cite book|author=Molly Murray|title=The Poetics of Conversion in Early Modern English Literature: Verse and Change from Donne to Dryden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=POPqPXI4U7YC&pg=PA89|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=15 October 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-11387-8|page=89 note 77}}</ref> Some works against [[Thomas Bell (Catholic priest)|Thomas Bell]] were thought to be by Persons (as in the DNB), but were in fact by Philip Woodward.<ref name=\"Questier1996\">{{cite book|author=Michael C. Questier|title=Conversion, Politics and Religion in England, 1580-1625|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JczSYC5riR4C&pg=PA48|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=13 July 1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-44214-5|page=48 note 42}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Suellen Mutchow Towers|title=The control of religious printing in early Stuart England|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8u87-D44jwC&pg=PA98|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=2003|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-0-85115-939-3|page=98}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Frederick Wilse Bateson|title=The Cambridge bibliography of English literature. 2. 1660-1800|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ebM6AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA327|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=1940|publisher=CUP Archive|page=327|id=GGKEY:QNELW3AWW36}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Thomas Abell]]\n* [[William Allen (cardinal)]]\n* [[Christopher Bagshawe]]\n* [[Pacificus Baker]]\n* [[Robert Bellarmine]]\n* [[Edmund Campion]]\n* [[Richard Challoner]]\n* [[Johann Eck]]\n* [[John Fisher]]\n* [[Antony Hickey]]\n* [[Angelus of St. Francis Mason]]\n* [[Thomas More]]\n* [[Gregorio Panzani]]\n* [[Reginald Pole]]\n* [[John Punch (theologian)|John Punch]]\n* [[John Proctor (historian)|John Proctor]]\n* [[Luke Wadding]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last=Hogge|first=Alice|title=God's Secret Agents: Queen Elizabeth's Forbidden Priests and the Hatching of the Gunpowder Plot|date=2006|publisher=Harper Perennial|isbn=978-0007156382}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sullivan|first=Ceri|title=Dismembered Rhetoric: English Recusant Writing, 1580 to 1603|date=1995|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson University Press|isbn=978-1611471168}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Parsons, Robert (1546-1610)|volume=43}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Catholicism|England}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Persons, Robert}}\n[[Category:1546 births]]\n[[Category:1610 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century English Jesuits]]\n[[Category:17th-century English Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Mary Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Italy]]\n[[Category:Early modern Christian devotional writers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:People from Sedgemoor (district)]]\n[[Category:Rectors of the English College, Rome]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"English Jesuit priest\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Persons"}
{"title_page": "Peter A. Dowling", "text_new": "{{short description|British screenwriter}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{BLP sources|date = March 2008}}}}\n\n'''Peter Anthony Dowling''' is a British [[screenwriter]] and [[film director]]. He was born in [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]], England, in 1969 and started his career in children's animation in both the UK and Germany, working on cartoons such as ''[[The Raggy Dolls]]'', ''[[Benjamin Bluemchen]]'' and ''[[Renada]]''.\n\nAfter winning the Fulbright [[TEB Clarke]] Fellowship in Screenwriting 1996/7, judged by [[William Goldman]] and paid for by [[John Cleese]], Dowling moved to the [[United States]], briefly attending the [[University of Southern California]], and then sold a spec screenplay to [[Arnold Kopelson]] (Platoon, Se7en) and [[20th Century Fox]].\n\nHis first produced movie was ''[[Flightplan]]'' starring [[Jodie Foster]] which was commercially successful in the U.S. and grossed over $223,000,000 worldwide.\n\nStarting in 2007 he began to direct, and his first film was ''[[Stag Night]]''.\n\n== Filmography ==\n* ''[[Flightplan]]'' (2005) - Writer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tracking-board.com/abc-developing-reincarnation-cop-drama-then-again-exclusive/|title=ABC Developing Reincarnation Cop Drama \"Then Again\" (Exclusive)|date=2018-01-17|website=The Tracking Board|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/tenacity-itv-bad-wolf-eone-peter-dowling-1202627975/|title=\u2018Flightplan\u2019 Writer Peter A. Dowling Scores ITV Submarine Drama \u2018Tenacity\u2019 With Bad Wolf & eOne|last=White|first=Peter|last2=White|first2=Peter|date=2019-06-06|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Stag Night]]'' (2007) - Writer/Director\n* ''[[Reasonable Doubt (2014 film)|Reasonable Doubt]]'' (2014) - Writer\n* ''[[Sacrifice (2016 film)|Sacrifice]]'' (2016) - Writer/Director<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kenny|first=Glenn|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/29/movies/sacrifice-review.html|title=Review: \u2018Sacrifice\u2019 Yields Corpses and Clich\u00e9s|date=2016-04-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''[[Black and Blue (2019 film)|Black and Blue]]'' (2019) - Writer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*{{IMDb name|1618225}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dowling, Peter A.}}\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British screenwriter}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date = March 2008}}\n{{no footnotes|date=December 2014}}\n{{BLP IMDb refimprove|only=yes|date=December 2014}} \n}}\n\n'''Peter Anthony Dowling''' is a British [[screenwriter]] and [[film director]]. He was born in [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]], England, in 1969 and started his career in children's animation in both the UK and Germany, working on cartoons such as ''[[The Raggy Dolls]]'', ''[[Benjamin Bluemchen]]'' and ''[[Renada]]''.\n\nAfter winning the Fulbright [[TEB Clarke]] Fellowship in Screenwriting 1996/7, judged by [[William Goldman]] and paid for by [[John Cleese]], Dowling moved to the [[United States]], briefly attending the [[University of Southern California]], and then sold a spec screenplay to [[Arnold Kopelson]] (Platoon, Se7en) and [[20th Century Fox]].\n\nHis first produced movie was ''[[Flightplan]]'' starring [[Jodie Foster]] which was commercially successful in the U.S. and grossed over $223,000,000 worldwide.\n\nStarting in 2007 he began to direct, and his first film was ''[[Stag Night]]''.\n\n== Filmography ==\n* ''[[Flightplan]]'' (2005) - Writer\n* ''[[Stag Night]]'' (2007) - Writer/Director\n* ''[[Reasonable Doubt (2014 film)|Reasonable Doubt]]'' (2014) - Writer\n* ''[[Sacrifice (2016 film)|Sacrifice]]'' (2016) - Writer/Director\n* ''[[Black and Blue (2019 film)|Black and Blue]]'' (2019) - Writer\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1618225}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dowling, Peter A.}}\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n", "name_user": "Cardiffbear88", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_A._Dowling"}
